s: [http://www.irishmanuscripts.ie/digital/The%20Correspondence%20of%20Daniel%20O'Connell%20Vol.%20I.%201792-1814/ Vol. I. 1792\u20131814] [http://www.irishmanuscripts.ie/digital/The%20Correspondence%20of%20Daniel%20O'Connell%20Vol.%20II.%201815-1823/ Vol. II. 1815\u20131823] [http://www.irishmanuscripts.ie/digital/The%20Correspondence%20of%20Daniel%20O'Connell%20Vol.%20III.%201824-1828/ Vol. III. 1824\u20131828] [http://www.irishmanuscripts.ie/digital/The%20Correspondence%20of%20Daniel%20O'Connell%20Vol.%20IV.%201829-1832/ Vol. IV. 1829\u20131832] [http://www.irishmanuscripts.ie/digital/The%20Correspondence%20of%20Daniel%20O'Connell%20Vol.%20V.%201833-1836/ Vol. V. 1833\u20131836] [http://www.irishmanuscripts.ie/digital/The%20Correspondence%20of%20Daniel%20O'Connell%20Vol.%20VI.%201837-1840/ Vol. VI. 1837\u20131840] [http://www.irishmanuscripts.ie/digital/The%20Correspondence%20of%20Daniel%20O'Connell%20Vol.%20VII.%201841-1845/ Vol. VII. 1841\u20131845] [http://www.irishmanuscripts.ie/digital/The%20Correspondence%20of%20Daniel%20O'Connell%20Vol.%20VIII.%201846-1847/index.html Vol. VIII. 1846\u20131847]\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[History of Ireland (1801-1922)]]\n* [[Irish nobility]]\n* [[List of people on stamps of Ireland]]\n* [[List of public art in Dublin]]\n* [[List of public art in Limerick]]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n{{wikisourceauthor}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.heritage.nf.ca/society/oconnell.html Daniel O'Connell and Newfoundland]\n* [http://www.fordham.edu/halsall/mod/1836oconnell.html Modern History Sourcebook: Daniel O'Connell: Justice for Ireland, Feb 4, 1836]\u2014O'Connell's speech in the House of Commons\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130730164720/http://multitext.ucc.ie/d/Daniel_OConnell Daniel O\u2019Connell]\u2014Multitext Project in Irish History (with extensive image gallery)\n* {{hansard-contribs | mr-daniel-oconnell | Daniel O'Connell }}\n* [http://bc-primo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo_library/libweb/action/dlDisplay.do?institution=BCL&vid=bclib&onCampus=false&docId=ALMA-BC21381539170001021 Daniel O'Connell Collection] \u2013 at Boston College John J. Burns Library\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oconnell, Daniel}}\n[[Category:1775 births]]\n[[Category:1847 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at Glasnevin Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Duellists]]\n[[Category:Irish barristers]]\n[[Category:Irish Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Irish tax resisters]]\n[[Category:Lord Mayors of Dublin]]\n[[Category:Members of Lincoln's Inn]]\n[[Category:O'Connell family|Daniel]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Kerry]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic activists]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1826\u20131830]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1830\u20131831]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1831\u20131832]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1832\u20131835]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1835\u20131837]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1837\u20131841]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1841\u20131847]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Clare constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Waterford constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Kerry constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Dublin constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Kilkenny constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Meath constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Cork constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Irish Repeal Association MPs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish political leader}}\n{{Other people|Daniel O'Connell}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Daniel O'Connell<br>D\u00f3nall \u00d3 Conaill\n| image = Daniel O'Connell by Sir George Hayter.jpg\n| caption = 1834 portrait of Daniel O'Connell by [[George Hayter]]\n| office = [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]] <br> for [[Clare (UK Parliament constituency)|Clare]]\n| term_start = 5 July 1828\n| term_end = 29 July 1830\n| predecessor = [[William Vesey-FitzGerald, 2nd Baron FitzGerald and Vesey|William Vesey-FitzGerald]]\n| successor = [[William Nugent Macnamara|William Macnamara]]\n| office2 = [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]] <br> for [[Dublin City (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin City]]\n| term_start2 = 22 December 1832\n| term_end2 = 16 May 1836\n| predecessor2 = [[Sir Frederick Shaw, 3rd Baronet|Sir Frederick Shaw]]\n| successor2 = [[George Alexander Hamilton|George Hamilton]]\n| office3 = [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]] <br>  for [[Dublin City (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin City]]\n| predecessor3 = George  Hamilton\n| successor3 = John West\n| term_start3 = 5 August 1837\n| term_end3 = 10 July 1841\n| office4 = [[List of Lord Mayors of Dublin#19th century|Lord Mayor]] of [[Dublin]]\n| term_start4 = 1841\n| term_end4 = 1842\n| predecessor4 = [[Sir John James, 1st Baronet]]\n| successor4 = George Roe\n| office5 = [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Cork County (UK Parliament constituency)|Cork County]] \n| term_start5 = 1841\n| term_end5 = 1847\n| predecessor5 = [[Garrett Standish Barry]]\n| successor5 = [[Edmund Burke Roche]] \n| birth_date = {{birth date|1775|8|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place = {{nowrap|[[Cahersiveen]], [[County Kerry]], [[Kingdom of Ireland|Ireland]]}}\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1847|5|15|1775|8|6|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Genoa]], [[Kingdom of Sardinia]]\n| restingplace = [[Glasnevin Cemetery]], Dublin\n| party = {{unbulleted list | [[Radicals (UK)|Radicals]] | [[Repeal Association]] }}\n| spouse = [[Mary O'Connell (1778\u20131836)|Mary O'Connell]] (m. 1802)\n| children = {{unbulleted list | [[Maurice O'Connell (MP)|Maurice]] | [[Ellen Bridget O'Connell|Ellen]] | Catherine | Timothy | Elizabeth | [[John O'Connell (MP)|John]] | [[Morgan O'Connell|Morgan]] | [[Daniel O'Connell Jnr|Daniel]] }}\n| occupation = [[Barrister]], political activist\n| alma_mater = [[Lincoln's Inn]] <br> [[King's Inns]]\n| signature = Daniel O'Connell signature c1835.jpg\n<!--Military service-->| nickname = \n| allegiance = {{Flag|Kingdom of Ireland}}\n| branch = [[Yeomanry]]\n| serviceyears = 1797\n| rank = \n| unit = Lawyer's Artillery Corps\n| commands = \n| battles = \n| awards = \n| military_blank1 = \n| military_data1 = \n}}\n\n'''Daniel O'Connell''' ({{lang-ga|D\u00f3nall \u00d3 Conaill}}; 6 August 1775&nbsp;\u2013 15 May 1847), often referred to as '''The Liberator'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irish-society.org/home/hedgemaster-archives-2/people/o-connell-daniel|title=O'Connell, Daniel \u2013 Irish Cultural Society of the Garden City Area|work=irish-society.org}}</ref> or '''The Emancipator''',<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/northernireland/ashorthistory/archive/intro177.shtml A Short History of Ireland]</ref> was an Irish political leader in the first half of the 19th century. He campaigned for [[Catholic emancipation]]\u2014including the right for Catholics to sit in the [[Westminster Parliament]], denied for over 100 years\u2014and repeal of the [[Acts of Union 1800|Acts of Union]] which combined [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Great Britain and Ireland]].\n\nThroughout his career in Irish politics, O'Connell was able to gain a large following among the Irish masses in support of him and his [[Catholic Association]]. O'Connell's main strategy was one of political [[reformism]], working within the parliamentary structures of the British state in Ireland and forming an alliance of convenience with the [[Whigs (British political party)|Whigs]]. More radical elements broke with O'Connell to found the [[Young Ireland]] movement.\n\n==Early life==\nO'Connell was born at Carhan near [[Cahersiveen]], [[County Kerry]], to the [[O'Connells of Derrynane]], a wealthy Roman Catholic family  that had been dispossessed of its lands. His parents were Morgan O'Connell  and Catherine O'Mullane. Among his uncles was [[Daniel Charles, Count O'Connell]], an officer in the Irish Brigades of the [[French Army]].  A famous aunt was [[Eibhl\u00edn Dubh N\u00ed Chonaill]], while [[Sir James O'Connell, 1st Baronet]], was his younger brother.  Under the patronage of his wealthy bachelor uncle [[Maurice O'Connell (Hunting Cap)|Maurice \"Hunting Cap\" O'Connell]]. O'Connell was first sent with his brother Maurice to Reddington Academy at Long Island, near Queenstown (Cobh)<ref>J. J. Fr. Harrington's Reddington Academy Walterstown (Baile Ualtair) is a townland in Cobh Rural ED, in Templerobin Civil Parish, in Barony, in Co. Cork, Ireland. O'Kelly \"O'Connell Calling: the Liberator\u2019s place in the world\" (Kerryman, 1949)</ref> They both studied at [[Douai]] in France from 1790 and O'Connell was admitted as a [[barrister]] to [[Lincoln's Inn]] in 1794, transferring to [[Dublin]]'s [[King's Inns]] two years later. In his early years, he became acquainted with the pro-democracy radicals of the time and committed himself to bringing equal rights and religious tolerance to his own country.<ref name=\"Boylan1998\">{{cite book | last = Boylan | first = Henry | year = 1998 | title = A Dictionary of Irish Biography | edition = 3rd | page = 306 | location = Dublin | publisher = Gill and MacMillan | isbn = 0-7171-2945-4 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:O'Connells Home At Derrynane Abby.JPG|thumb|left|O'Connell's home at [[Derrynane House|Derrynane]]]]\nWhile in Dublin studying for the law, O'Connell was under his Uncle Maurice's instructions not to become involved in any militia activity. When [[Theobald Wolfe Tone|Wolfe Tone]]'s [[Wolfe Tone#Hoche's expedition and the 1798 rebellion|French invasion fleet]] entered [[Bantry Bay]] in December 1796, O'Connell found himself in a quandary. Politics was the cause of his unsettlement.<ref name=\"Gywnn\">\nDennis Gywnn, ''Daniel O'Connell The Irish Liberator'', Hutchinson & Co. Ltd pg 71</ref> Dennis Gwynn in his ''Daniel O'Connell: The Irish Liberator'' suggests that the unsettlement was because he was enrolled as a volunteer in defence of Government, yet the Government was intensifying its persecution of the Catholic people\u2014of which he was one.<ref name=\"Gywnn\" /> He desired to enter Parliament, yet every allowance that the Catholics had been led to anticipate, two years previously, was now flatly vetoed.<ref name=\"Gywnn\" />\n\nAs a law student, O'Connell was aware of his own talents, but the higher ranks of the Bar were closed to him. He read the ''[[Jockey Club]]'' as a picture of the governing class in England and was persuaded by it that, \"vice reigns triumphant in the English court at this day. The spirit of [[liberty]] shrinks to protect property from the attacks of French innovators. The corrupt higher orders tremble for their vicious enjoyments.\"<ref name=\"Gywnn\" />\n\nO'Connell's studies at the time had concentrated upon the legal and political history of Ireland, and the debates of the Historical Society concerned the records of governments, and from this he was to conclude, according to one of his biographers, \"in Ireland the whole policy of the Government was to repress the people and to maintain the ascendancy of a privileged and corrupt minority\".<ref name=\"Gywnn\" />\n\nOn 3 January 1797, in an atmosphere of alarm over the French invasion fleet in Bantry Bay, he wrote to his uncle saying that he was the last of his colleagues to join a volunteer corps and \"being young, active, healthy and single\" he could offer no plausible excuse.<ref>O'Connell Correspondence, Vol I, Letter No. 24a</ref> Later that month, for the sake of expediency, he joined the Lawyers' Artillery Corps.<ref>O'Ferrall, F., ''Daniel O'Connell, Dublin'', 1981, p. 12</ref>\n\nOn 19 May 1798, O'Connell was called to the [[Irish Bar]] and became a [[barrister]]. Four days later, the [[Society of the United Irishmen|United Irishmen]] staged their [[Irish Rebellion of 1798|rebellion]] which was put down by the British with great bloodshed. O'Connell did not support the rebellion; he believed that the Irish would have to assert themselves politically rather than by force.\n\nHe went on the [[Munster]] circuit, and for over a decade, he went into a fairly quiet period of private law practice in the south of Ireland.<ref name=\"Boylan1998\" /> He was reputed to have the largest income of any Irish barrister but, due to natural extravagance and a growing family, was usually in debt; his brother remarked caustically that Daniel was in debt all his life from the age of seventeen. Although he was ultimately to inherit Derrynane from his uncle Maurice, the old man lived to be almost 100 and in the event Daniel's inheritance did not cover his debts.\n\nHe also condemned [[Robert Emmet]]'s [[Irish Rebellion of 1803|Rebellion of 1803]]. Of Emmet, a Protestant, he wrote: \"A man who could coolly prepare so much bloodshed, so many murders\u2014and such horrors of every kind has ceased to be an object of compassion.\"<ref>O'Connell Correspondence, Vol I, Letter No. 97</ref>\n\nDespite his opposition to the use of violence, he was willing to defend those accused of political crimes, particularly if he suspected that they had been falsely accused, as in the [[Doneraile]] conspiracy trials of 1829, his last notable court appearance. He was noted for his fearlessness in court: if he thought poorly of a judge (as was very often the case) he had no hesitation in making this clear. Most famous perhaps was his retort to [[James McClelland (Solicitor-General)|Baron McClelland]], who had said that as a barrister he would never have taken the course O'Connell had adopted: O'Connell said that McClelland had never been his model as a barrister, neither would he take directions from him as a judge.<ref>O'Faol\u00e1in, Sean (1936). ''King of the Beggars: a life of Daniel O'Connell''. Alan Figgis reissue, p. 97</ref> He did not lack the ambition to become a judge himself: in particular he was attracted by the position of [[Master of the Rolls in Ireland]], yet although he was offered it more than once, finally refused.\n\n==Family==\n[[File:Mary O'Connell.tif|thumb| 1836 Portrait of Mary O'Connell by John Gubbins]]\n[[File:Daniel O'Connell.png|thumb|left|Daniel O'Connell, in an 1836 watercolour by Bernard Mulrenin. <!--''Daniel O'Connell'', 1836, by [[Bernard Mulrenin]]-->]]\n[[File:St Patricks Cathedral (Daniel O'Connell Statue).jpg|thumb|Statue of Daniel O'Connell outside [[St Patrick's Cathedral, Melbourne]]|alt=]]In 1802 O'Connell married his third cousin, [[Mary O'Connell (1778-1836)|Mary O'Connell]]. It was a love marriage, and to persist in it was an act of considerable courage, since Daniel's uncle Maurice was outraged (as Mary had no fortune) and for a time threatened to disinherit them.<ref>Geoghegan  ''King Dan''  pp.94\u20137</ref> They had four daughters (three surviving), [[Ellen Bridget O'Connell|Ellen]] (1805\u20131883), Catherine (1808), Elizabeth (1810), and Rickarda (1815) and four sons. The sons\u2014[[Maurice O'Connell (MP)|Maurice]] (1803), [[Morgan O'Connell|Morgan]]  (1804), [[John O'Connell (MP)|John]] (1810), and [[Daniel O'Connell Jnr|Daniel]] (1816)\u2014all sat in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]]. The marriage was happy and Mary's death in 1837 was a blow from which her husband never fully recovered. He was a devoted father; O'Faol\u00e1in suggests that despite his wide acquaintance he had few close friends and therefore the family circle meant a great deal to him.<ref>O'Faol\u00e1in p.87</ref>\n\n=== O'Connell's Ale and connection with the 'licensed trade' ===\nO'Connell assisted his younger son, Daniel junior, to acquire the Phoenix Brewery in James's Street, Dublin in 1831.<ref>''Irish Whiskey: A 1000 Year Tradition'', Malachy Magee, O'Brien Press, Dublin, {{ISBN|0-86278-228-7}}. pg 68\u201374.</ref> The brewery produced a brand known as \"O'Connell's Ale\" and enjoyed some popularity. By 1832, O'Connell was forced to state that he would not be a political patron of the brewing trade or his son's company, until he was no longer a member of parliament, particularly because O'Connell and [[Arthur Guinness]] were political enemies. Guinness was the \"moderate\" liberal candidate, O'Connell was the \"radical\" liberal candidate. The rivalry caused dozens of Irish firms to boycott Guinness during the 1841 Repeal election. It was at this time that Guinness was accused of supporting the \"Orange system\", and its beer was known as \"Protestant porter\". When the O'Connell family left brewing, the rights to \"O'Connell Dublin Ale\" was sold to John D'Arcy. The brewing business proved to be unsuccessful though, and after a few years was taken over by the manager, John Brennan, while Daniel junior embraced a political career. Brennan changed the name back to the Phoenix Brewery but continued to brew and sell O'Connell's Ale. When the Phoenix Brewery was effectively closed after being absorbed into the Guinness complex in 1909, the brewing of O'Connell's Ale was carried out by John D'Arcy and Son Ltd at the Anchor Brewery in Usher Street. In 1926, D'Arcy's ceased trading and the firm of Watkins, Jameson and Pim carried on the brewing until they too succumbed to the pressures of trying to compete with Guinness.<ref>T. Halpin: History of the Irish Brewing Industry, 1988</ref><ref name=\"sim\">[http://www.simtec.us/dublinbrewing/history.html History of Brewing in Dublin]</ref>\n\nDaniel junior was the committee chairman of the licensed trade association of the period and gave considerable and valuable support to Daniel O'Connell in his public life. Some time later a quarrel arose and O'Connell turned his back on the association and became a strong advocate of [[temperance movement|temperance]]. During the period of [[Theobald Mathew (temperance reformer)|Fr. Mathew]]'s total abstinence crusades many temperance rallies were held, the most notable being a huge rally held on [[St. Patrick's Day]] in 1841. Daniel O'Connell was a guest of honour at another such rally held at the [[Rotunda Hospital]].<ref name=\"sim\" /><ref>St Martin Magazine (ISSN 1393-1008), June 2003 St Martin Apostolate, Dublin</ref>\n\n== Political beliefs and programme ==\n[[File:Daniel O'Connell2.jpg|thumb|\"Daniel O'Connell: The Champion of Liberty\" poster published in [[Pennsylvania]], 1847]]\n\nA critic of violent insurrection ''in Ireland'', O'Connell once said that \"the altar of liberty totters when it is cemented only with blood\", and yet as late as 1841, O'Connell had whipped his MPs into line to keep the [[First Opium War|(First) Opium War]] going in China. The Tories at the time had proposed a motion of censure over the war, and O'Connell had to call upon his MPs to support the Whig Government. As a result of this intervention, the Government was saved.<ref>''[[Charles Gavan Duffy]]: Conversations With Carlyle (1892), with Introduction, Stray Thoughts on Young Ireland'', Brendan Clifford, Athol Books, Belfast, {{ISBN|0-85034-114-0}}.pg 17 &21</ref>\n\nPolitically, he focused on parliamentary and populist methods to force change and made regular declarations of his loyalty to the British Crown. He often warned the British establishment that if they did not reform the governance of Ireland, Irishmen would start to listen to the \"counsels of violent men\". Successive British governments continued to ignore this advice, long after his death, although he succeeded in extracting by the sheer force of will and the power of the Catholic peasants and clergy much of what he wanted, i.e., eliminating disabilities on Roman Catholics; ensuring that lawfully elected Roman Catholics could serve their constituencies in the British Parliament (until the [[Parliament of Ireland|Irish Parliament]] was restored); and amending the Oath of Allegiance so as to remove clauses offensive to Roman Catholics who could then take the Oath in good conscience.<ref name=\"Boylan1998\" />\n\nAlthough a native speaker of the [[Irish language]], O'Connell encouraged Irish people to learn English to better themselves.<ref name=\"Boylan1998\" /> Although he is best known for the campaign for Catholic emancipation; he also supported similar efforts for Irish Jews. At his insistence, in 1846, the British law \"[[History of the Jews in Ireland#18th and 19th century|De Judaismo]]\", which prescribed a special dress for Jews, was repealed. O'Connell said: \"Ireland has claims on your ancient race, it is the only country that I know of unsullied by any one act of persecution of the Jews\".<ref>[http://www.jewishireland.org/history_2.html Jewish Ireland] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100222092245/http://www.jewishireland.org/history_2.html|date=22 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Campaigning for Catholic emancipation ==\nO'Connell returned to politics in the 1810s. In 1811, he established the Catholic Board, which campaigned for [[Catholic emancipation]], that is, the opportunity for Irish Catholics to become members of parliament. In 1823, he set up the [[Catholic Association]] which embraced other aims to better Irish Catholics, such as: electoral reform, reform of the [[Church of Ireland]], tenants' rights, and economic development.<ref>Paul Adelmann and Robert Pearce, ''Great Britain and the Irish Question 1798\u20131922'', Hodder Murray, London, {{ISBN|0-340-88901-2}}, p. 33</ref>\n\nThe Association was funded by membership dues of one penny per month, a minimal amount designed to attract Catholic peasants. The subscription was highly successful, and the Association raised a large sum of money in its first year. The money was used to campaign for Catholic emancipation, specifically funding pro-emancipation members of parliament (MPs) standing for the [[British House of Commons]].<ref>Geoghegan, Patrick M. (2008). ''King Dan''. Gill and Macmillan, Dublin, p. 168</ref>\n\nThe Crown moved to suppress the Association by a series of prosecutions, with mixed success. O'Connell was often briefed for the defence, and showed extraordinary vigour in pleading the rights of Catholics to argue for emancipation. He clashed repeatedly with [[William Saurin]], the [[Attorney General for Ireland]] and most influential figure in the Dublin administration, and political differences between the two men were fuelled by a bitter personal antipathy.<ref>O'Faol\u00e1in pp. 151\u2013179</ref>\n\nIn 1815 a serious event in his life occurred. [[Dublin Corporation]] was considered a stronghold of the [[Protestant Ascendancy]] and O'Connell, in an 1815 speech, referred to it as a \"beggarly corporation\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Millingen|first=John Gideon|title=The history of duelling: including, narratives of the most remarkable personal encounters that have taken place from the earliest period to the present time, Volume 2|year=1841|publisher=R. Bentley|pages=215|url=https://books.google.com/?id=VSH6ZhIuBucC&pg=PA215&lpg=PA215&dq=%E2%80%98beggarly+Corporation%E2%80%99+of+Dublin#v=onepage&q=%E2%80%98beggarly%20Corporation%E2%80%99%20of%20Dublin&f=false}}</ref> Its members and leaders were outraged and because O'Connell would not apologise, one of their number, the noted [[duel]]list John D'Esterre, challenged him. The duel had filled [[Dublin Castle]] (from where the [[Dublin Castle administration|British Government administered Ireland]]) with tense excitement at the prospect that O'Connell would be killed. They regarded O'Connell as \"worse than a public nuisance\", and would have welcomed any prospect of seeing him removed at this time.<ref name=\"Dennis Gywnn Pg 138-145\">Dennis Gywnn, ''Daniel O'Connell The Irish Liberator'', Hutchinson & Co. Ltd pp 138\u2013145</ref>\n\nO'Connell met D'Esterre and [[Oughter Ard#Duel|mortally wounded him]] (he was shot in the hip, the bullet then lodging in his stomach), in a duel at [[Oughterard, County Kildare]]. His conscience was bitterly sore by the fact that, not only had he killed a man, but he had left his family almost destitute.<ref>Geoghegan, ''King Dan''  p. 155</ref>\n\nO'Connell offered to \"share his income\" with D'Esterre's widow, but she declined; however, she consented to accept an allowance for her daughter, which O'Connell regularly paid for more than thirty years until his death. The memory of the duel haunted him for the remainder of his life, and he refused ever to fight another, being prepared to risk accusations of cowardice rather than kill again.<ref name=\"Dennis Gywnn Pg 138-145\" />\n\nAs part of his campaign for Catholic emancipation, O'Connell created the Catholic Association in 1823; this organisation acted as a pressure group against the British government so as to achieve emancipation. The [[Catholic Rent]], which was established in 1824 by O'Connell and the Catholic Church raised funds from which O'Connell was able to help finance the Catholic Association in its push for emancipation. Official opinion was gradually swinging towards emancipation, as shown by the summary dismissal of William Saurin, the Attorney General and a leading opponent of religious toleration, whom O'Connell called \"our mortal foe\".\n\nO'Connell stood in a [[1828 Clare by-election|by-election]] to the British House of Commons in 1828 for [[Clare (UK Parliament constituency)|County Clare]] against [[William Vesey-FitzGerald, 2nd Baron FitzGerald and Vesey|William Vesey Fitzgerald]], who had just joined the British Cabinet as President of the Board of Trade. By law at the time, Cabinet office was deemed to be \"an office of profit\" under the Crown, requiring the promoted man to obtain the endorsement of his constituents by standing for re-election.\n\nAfter O'Connell won election, he was unable to take his seat as members of parliament had to take the [[Oath of Supremacy]], which was incompatible with Catholicism. The Prime Minister, the [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Duke of Wellington]], and the [[Home Secretary]], Sir [[Robert Peel]], even though they opposed Catholic participation in Parliament, saw that denying O'Connell his seat would cause outrage and could lead to another rebellion or uprising in Ireland, which was about 85% Catholic.<ref>Oliver MacDonagh (1991), ''The Life of Daniel O'Connell''</ref>\n\nPeel and Wellington managed to convince [[George IV of the United Kingdom|King George IV]] that Catholic emancipation and the right of Catholics and [[Presbyterian]]s and members of all Christian faiths other than the established [[Church of Ireland]] to sit in Parliament needed to be established; with the help of the [[Whig (British political party)|Whigs]], the [[Roman Catholic Relief Act 1829|Catholic Relief Act]] became law in 1829.\n\nHowever, the Emancipation Act was not made retroactive, meaning that O'Connell had either to seek re-election or to attempt to take the oath of supremacy. When O'Connell attempted on 15 May to take his seat without taking the oath of supremacy,  Solicitor-General [[Nicholas Conyngham Tindal]] moved that his seat be declared vacant and another election ordered; O'Connell was elected unopposed on 30 July 1829.<ref name=\"Hist Parl\">''[[The History of Parliament]] 1820\u20131832'' vol VI pp. 535\u2013536.</ref>\n\nHe took his seat when Parliament resumed in February 1830, by which time [[Henry Charles Howard, 13th Duke of Norfolk]] and Earl of Surrey, had already become the first Roman Catholic to have taken advantage of the Emancipation Act and sit in Parliament.<ref name=\"Not first\">''[[History of Parliament]] 1820\u20131832'' vol I p. 253.</ref><ref name=\"Not first2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deskeenan.com/1GrChap8.htm|title=The Grail Chapter Eight|work=deskeenan.com}}</ref>\n\n\"Wellington is the King of England\", King George IV once complained, \"O'Connell is King of Ireland, and I am only the dean of Windsor.\" The regal jest expressed the general admiration for O'Connell at the height of his career.\n\nThe Catholic emancipation campaign led by O'Connell served as the precedent and model for the emancipation of [[British Jews]], the subsequent [[Jews Relief Act 1858]] allowing Jewish MPs to omit the words in the [[Oath of Allegiance]] \"and I make this Declaration upon the true Faith of a Christian\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/Vict/21-22/49/enacted|title=Jews Relief Act 1858|work=legislation.gov.uk}}</ref> O'Connell himself was an opponent of the persecution of Jews praising Ireland as the \"only Christian country that I know of unsullied by any one act of persecution of the Jews.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://books.google.com/?id=CkULAAAAIAAJ&q=Ireland+has+claims+on+your+ancient+race,+it+is+the+only+country+that+I+know+of+unsullied+by+any+one+act+of+persecution+of+the+Jews%E2%80%9D&dq=Ireland+has+claims+on+your+ancient+race,+it+is+the+only+country+that+I+know+of+unsullied+by+any+one+act+of+persecution+of+the+Jews%E2%80%9D | title=Transactions - the Jewish Historical Society of England| year=1908}}</ref>\n\n===Comments on emancipation===\n[[Michael Doheny]], in his ''The Felon's Track'', says that the very character of emancipation has assumed an \"exaggerated and false guise\" and that it is an error to call it emancipation. He went on, that it was neither the first nor the last nor even the most important in the concessions, which are entitled to the name of emancipation, and that no one remembered the men whose exertions \"wrung from the reluctant spirit of a far darker time the right of living, of worship, of enjoying property, and exercising the franchise\".<ref name=\"doheny\">Michael Doheny's ''The Felon's Track'', M. H. Gill & Son, Ltd., 1951, pp 2\u20134</ref> Doheny's opinion was, that the penalties of the \"[[Penal Laws]]\" had been long abolished, and that barbarous code had been compressed into cold and stolid exclusiveness and yet Mr. O'Connell monopolised its entire renown.<ref name=\"doheny\" /> The view put forward by [[John Mitchel]], also one of the leading members of the [[Young Ireland]] movement, in his \"Jail Journal\"<ref>[[John Mitchel]]'s ''Jail Journal'' which was first serialised in his first New York City newspaper, ''The Citizen'', from 14 January 1854 to 19 August 1854. The book referenced is an exact reproduction of the ''Jail Journal'', as it first appeared.</ref> was that there were two distinct movements in Ireland during this period, which were rousing the people, one was the Catholic Relief Agitation (led by O'Connell), which was both open and legal, the other was the secret societies known as the Ribbon and White\u2014boy movements.<ref name=\"mitchell\">[[John Mitchel]], ''Jail Journal, or five years in British Prisons'', M. H. Gill & Son, Ltd., 1914, pp. xxxiv\u2013xxxvi</ref> The first proposed the admission of professional and genteel Catholics to Parliament and to the honours of the professions, all under British law\u2014the other, originating in an utter horror and defiance of British law, contemplated nothing less than a social, and ultimately, a political revolution.<ref name=\"mitchell\" /> According to Mitchel, for fear of the latter, Great Britain with a \"very ill grace yielded to the first\". Mitchel agrees that Sir Robert Peel and the Duke of Wellington ''said'' they brought in this measure, to avert civil war; but says that \"no British statesman ever officially tells the truth, or assigns to any act its real motive.\"<ref name=\"mitchell\" /> Their real motive was, according to Mitchel, to buy into the British interests, the landed and educated Catholics, these \"Respectable Catholics\" would then be contented, and \"become [[West Brit]]ons\" from that day.<ref name=\"mitchell\" />\n\n==The Tithe War==\nIronically, considering O'Connell's dedication to peaceful methods of political agitation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/11200c.htm|title=CATHOLIC ENCYCLOPEDIA: Daniel O'Connell|work=newadvent.org}}</ref> his greatest political achievement ushered in a period of violence in Ireland. There was an obligation for those working the land to support the established Church (i.e., the [[United Church of England and Ireland]]) by payments known as [[tithes]]. The fact that the vast majority of those working the land in Ireland were Catholic or Presbyterian tenant farmers, supporting what was a minority religion within that island (but not the United Kingdom as a whole), had been causing tension for some time.<ref name=ste>{{cite book|last=Stewart|first= Jay Brown |year=2001|title=The National Churches of England, Ireland and Scotland, 1801\u201346|pages=20\u201345|location=Oxford|publisher= Oxford University Press|isbn= 0-19-924235-6}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1830, he and several others were tried for holding a meeting as an association or assemblage in violation of the orders of the Lord Lieutenant of Ireland, but the statute expired in course of judgment and the prosecution was terminated by the judiciary.<ref>State Trials (New Series) II, 629</ref>\n\nAn initially peaceful campaign of non-payment turned violent in 1831 when the newly founded [[Royal Irish Constabulary|Irish Constabulary]] were used to seize property in lieu of payment resulting in the [[Tithe War]] of 1831\u20131836.\n\nAlthough opposed to the use of force, O'Connell successfully defended participants in the [[Tithe War|Battle of Carrickshock]] and all the defendants were acquitted. Nonetheless O'Connell rejected [[William Sharman Crawford]]'s call for the complete abolition of tithes in 1838, as he felt he could not embarrass the Whigs (the [[Lichfield House Compact]] secured an alliance between Whigs, radicals and Irish MPs in 1835).<ref name=ste/> In 1838, parliament introduced a {{anchor|Tithe Commutation Act}}Tithe Commutation Act for Ireland.<ref>{{cite book|editor1=Moody, T. W. |editor2=Martin, F. X. |year=1967|title=The Course of Irish History|publisher=Mercier Press|location=Cork|page=375}}</ref> This reduced the amount payable directly by about a quarter and made the remainder payable in rent to [[landlord]]s. They in turn were to pass payment to the authorities. Tithes were thus effectively added to a tenant's rent payment. This partial relief and elimination of the confrontational collections ended the violent aspect of the Tithe War.\n\nFull relief from the tax was not achieved until the [[Irish Church Act 1869]], which disestablished the Church of Ireland, by the [[William Ewart Gladstone|Gladstone]] government.\n\n\nIn 1841, Daniel O'Connell became the first Roman Catholic [[Lord Mayor of Dublin]] since the reign of [[James II of England|James II]], who had been the last Roman Catholic monarch of England, Ireland and Scotland.<ref name=\"Boylan1998\" />\n\n==Campaign for repeal of the Union==\n[[Image:The Monster Meeting at Clifden in 1843.png|thumb|''The Monster Meeting at [[Clifden]] in 1843'' by [[Joseph Patrick Haverty]]. O'Connell is depicted in the center addressing the gathered masses.|alt=]]\nOnce Catholic emancipation was achieved, O'Connell campaigned for [[Repeal (Ireland)|repeal]] of the [[Act of Union 1800|Act of Union]], which in 1801 had merged the Parliaments of the [[Kingdom of Great Britain]] and the [[Kingdom of Ireland]] to form the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]]. To campaign for repeal, O'Connell set up the [[Repeal Association]]. He argued for the re-creation of an independent Kingdom of Ireland to govern itself, with [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Queen Victoria]] as the Queen of Ireland.\n\nTo push for this, he held a series of \"Monster Meetings\" throughout much of Ireland outside the Protestant and Unionist-dominated province of [[Ulster]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bartleby.com/268/6/17.html|title=In Favor of the Repeal of the Union by Daniel O'Connell. Ireland (1775\u20131902). Vol. VI. Bryan, William Jennings, ed. 1906. The World's Famous Orations|website=www.bartleby.com|access-date=2016-03-18}}</ref> They were so called because each was attended by around 100,000 people. These rallies concerned the [[British Government]] and the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]], Sir [[Robert Peel]], banned one such proposed monster meeting at [[Clontarf, Dublin|Clontarf]], [[County Dublin]], just outside Dublin city in 1843. This move was made after the biggest monster meeting was held at [[Tara, Ireland|Tara]].\n\n[[File:OConnellMonument.JPG|thumb|O'Connell Monument on [[O'Connell Street]] in Dublin]]\n[[Tara, Ireland|Tara]] held great significance to the Irish population as it was the historic seat of the [[High Kings of Ireland]]. Clontarf was symbolic because of its association with the [[Battle of Clontarf]] in 1014, when the Irish King [[Brian Boru]] defeated his rival Maelmordha, although Brian himself died during the battle. Despite appeals from his supporters, O'Connell refused to defy the authorities and he called off the meeting, as he was unwilling to risk bloodshed and had no others.<ref name=\"Boylan1998\" /> He was arrested, charged with conspiracy and sentenced to a year's imprisonment and a fine of \u00a32,000, although he was released after three months by the [[House of Lords]], which quashed the conviction and severely criticised the unfairness of the trial. Having deprived himself of his most potent weapon, the monster meeting, O'Connell with his health failing had no plan and dissension broke out in the Repeal Association.<ref name=\"Boylan1998\" />\n\nO'Connell's lengthy reliance on [[Whigs (British political party)|Whig party]] support for his policies in the Commons resulted in his tacit assent to the [[First Russell ministry]] that adopted a laissez-faire attitude to the [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Irish Famine]] from 1846.\n\n==Feud with Disraeli==\nIn April 1835, misled by inaccurate press reports, O'Connell thought [[Benjamin Disraeli]] had slandered him and launched an outspoken attack upon him:\n\n{{quote|His name shows that he is of Jewish origin. I do not use it as a term of reproach; there are many most respectable Jews. But there are, as in every other people, some of the lowest and most disgusting grade of moral turpitude; and of those I look upon Mr. Disraeli as the worst. He has just the qualities of the impenitent thief on the Cross, and I verily believe, if Mr. Disraeli's family herald were to be examined and his genealogy traced, the same personage would be discovered to be the heir at law of the exalted individual to whom I allude. I forgive Mr. Disraeli now, and as the lineal descendant of the blasphemous robber, who ended his career beside the Founder of the Christian Faith, I leave the gentleman to the enjoyment of his infamous distinction and family honours.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BmB4jYrsiQoC&pg=PT146&lpg=PT146&dq=perfidy,+selfishness,+depravity#v=onepage&q=perfidy%2C%20selfishness%2C%20depravity&f=false|title=Disraeli|first=Robert|last=Blake|isbn=9780571287550|publisher=Faber & Faber|year=2012}}</ref>}}\n\nDisraeli sought satisfaction by challenging  O'Connell's son Morgan to a duel, Daniel having sworn never to duel again after previously killing a man. Morgan declined, replying that he was not responsible for his father's words.\n\n<br />\n\n== \"Neglectful landlord\" ==\nIn an article written by Thomas Campbell Foster, O'Connell was accused of being one of the worst landlords in Ireland on December 25 1845, the [[London Times]]. It created international scandal, describing horrible conditions and painting the picture his tenants \"were living in abject poverty and neglect\". This was however written during the [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Irish Potato Famine]], and the Irish press asserted it was a politically motivated attack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.advertiser.ie/galway/article/76842/daniel-oconnell-a-man-not-without-flaws|title=Daniel O'Connell - A man not without flaws|last=Advertiser|first=Galway|last2=Thu|website=Galway Advertiser|access-date=2019-12-08|last3=Apr 02|last4=2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Literature and the Irish famine, 1845-1919|last=Fegan, Melissa.|date=2002|publisher=Clarendon Press|isbn=1-4237-6751-9|location=Oxford|oclc=67614412}}</ref>\n\nO'Connell did own land, but was from humble beginnings in [[Cahersiveen]]. As a youth he moved to his uncle \"Hunting Cap\" O'Connell's [[Derrynane House]]. He later inherited it in 1825.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.advertiser.ie/galway/article/76842/daniel-oconnell-a-man-not-without-flaws|title=Daniel O'Connell - A man not without flaws|last=Advertiser|first=Galway|last2=Thu|website=Galway Advertiser|access-date=2019-12-08|last3=Apr 02|last4=2015}}</ref>\n<br />\n== Career ==\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n| title = Member of Parliament for [[Clare (UK Parliament constituency)|Clare]]\n| with = [[Lucius O'Brien, 13th Baron Inchiquin|Lucius O'Brien]]\n| before = [[William Vesey-FitzGerald, 2nd Baron FitzGerald and Vesey|William Vesey-FitzGerald]] <br /> [[Lucius O'Brien, 13th Baron Inchiquin|Lucius O'Brien]]\n| after = [[William Nugent Macnamara]] <br /> [[Charles Mahon]]\n| years = 1828\u20131830\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = Member of Parliament for [[County Waterford (UK Parliament constituency)|County Waterford]]\n| with = [[Lord George Beresford]]\n| before = [[Richard Power (1776-1833)|Richard Power]] <br /> [[Lord George Beresford]]\n| after = [[Sir Richard Musgrave, 3rd Baronet, of Tourin|Sir Richard Musgrave, Bt]] <br /> [[Robert Power (British politician)|Robert Power]]\n| years = 1830\u20131831\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = Member of Parliament for [[Kerry (UK Parliament constituency)|Kerry]]\n| with = [[Frederick William Mullins]]\n| before = [[Maurice FitzGerald, 18th Knight of Kerry|Maurice Fitzgerald]] <br /> [[William Browne (MP for Kerry)|William Browne]]\n| after = [[Frederick Mullins]] <br /> Charles O'Connell\n| years = 1831\u20131832\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = Member of Parliament for [[Dublin City (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin City]]\n| with = [[Edward Southwell Ruthven]]\n| before = [[Sir Frederick Shaw, 3rd Baronet]] <br /> [[Henry Chetwynd-Talbot, 18th Earl of Shrewsbury|Viscount Ingestre]]\n| after = [[George Alexander Hamilton]] <br /> [[John Beattie West]]\n| years = 1832\u20131835\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = Member of Parliament for [[Kilkenny City (UK Parliament constituency)|Kilkenny City]]\n| before = [[Richard Sullivan (MP)|Richard Sullivan]]\n| after = [[Joseph Hume]]\n| years = 1836\u20131837\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = Member of Parliament for [[Dublin City (UK Parliament constituency)|Dublin City]]\n| with = [[Robert Hutton (politician)|Robert Hutton]]\n| before = [[George Alexander Hamilton]] <br /> [[John Beattie West]]\n| after = [[John Beattie West]] <br /> [[Sir Edward Grogan, 1st Baronet|Edward Grogan]]\n| years = 1837\u20131841\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = Member of Parliament for [[Meath (UK Parliament constituency)|Meath]]\n| with = [[Henry Grattan (junior)|Henry Grattan]]\n| before = [[Matthew Corbally]]\n| after = [[Matthew Corbally]]\n| years = 1841\u20131842\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = Member of Parliament for [[Cork County (UK Parliament constituency)|Cork County]]\n| with = [[Edmund Burke Roche]]\n| before = [[Garrett Standish Barry]] <br /> [[Edmund Burke Roche]]\n| after = [[Edmund Burke Roche]] <br /> [[Maurice Power]]\n| years = 1841\u20131847\n}}\n{{s-end}}<br />{{s-start}}\n{{s-civ}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = Sir John Kingston James\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = [[Lord Mayor of Dublin]]\n| years = 1841\u20131842\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = George Roe\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Death==\n[[File:Glasnevintower.jpg|thumb|The round tower marking O'Connell's mausoleum]]\n\nO'Connell died of softening of the brain ([[cerebral softening]]) in 1847 in [[Genoa, Italy]], while on a pilgrimage to Rome at the age of 71; his term in prison had seriously weakened him, and the appallingly cold weather he had to endure on his journey was probably the final blow. According to his dying wish, his heart was buried in Rome (at [[Sant'Agata dei Goti]], then the chapel of the Irish College), and the remainder of his body in [[Glasnevin Cemetery]] in Dublin, beneath a round tower. His sons are buried in his [[crypt]].\n== Legacy ==\n[[File:Daniel O'Connell 1929 issue set3.jpg|thumb|<center>Daniel O'Connell is honoured on the first commemorative [[Postage stamps of Ireland|stamps of Ireland]], <br /> issued in 1929.</center>]]\n[[File:The Anti-Slavery Society Convention, 1840 by Benjamin Robert Haydon.jpg|thumb|The Anti-Slavery Society Convention, 1840 by Benjamin Robert Haydon, O'Connell is on the left edge in this painting which is of the 1840 [[World Anti-Slavery Convention]]<ref name=\"npg\">[http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait.php?search=ap&npgno=599&eDate=&lDate= The Anti-Slavery Society Convention, 1840], [[Benjamin Robert Haydon]], 1841, [[National Portrait Gallery, London]], NPG599, Given by [[Anti-Slavery International|British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society]] in 1880</ref>]]\nOn 6 August 1875, [[Charles Herbert Mackintosh]] won the gold and silver medals offered by the St. Patrick's Society during the O'Connell centenary at Major's Hill Park in [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]] for a prize poem entitled ''The Irish Liberator''.<ref>''Canadian Illustrated News'' 28 08 1875 vol.XII, no. 9, 136. Library & Archives Canada 3682</ref>\n\nO'Connell's philosophy and career have inspired leaders all over the world, including [[Mahatma Gandhi]] (1869\u20131948) and [[Martin Luther King]] (1929\u20131968).{{cn|date=November 2019}} He was told by [[William Makepeace Thackeray]] (1811\u20131863) \"you have done more for your nation than any man since Washington ever did\". [[William Ewart Gladstone|William Gladstone]] (1809\u20131898) described him as \"the greatest popular leader the world has ever seen\". [[Honor\u00e9 de Balzac]] (1799\u20131850) wrote that \"Napoleon and O'Connell were the only great men the 19th century had ever seen.\" [[Jean-Henri Merle d'Aubign\u00e9]] (1794\u20131872) wrote that \"the only man like Luther, in the power he wielded was O'Connell\". [[William Grenville]] (1759\u20131834) wrote that \"history will speak of him as one of the most remarkable men that ever lived\". O'Connell met, befriended, and became a great inspiration to [[Frederick Douglass]] (1818\u20131895) the former US slave who became a highly influential leader of the abolitionist movement, social reformer, orator, writer and statesman.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/lifeandtimesfre01douggoog|title=The Life and Times of Frederick Douglass: From 1817\u20131882|publisher=Christian Age Office|last=Douglass|first=Frederick|year=1882|page=[https://archive.org/details/lifeandtimesfre01douggoog/page/n235 205]|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/02/25/frederick-douglasss-irish-liberty/|title=Frederick Douglass's Irish Liberty|last=Chaffin|first=Tom|date=25 February 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=26 February 2011}}</ref> O'Connell's attacks on slavery were made with his usual vigour, and often gave great offence, especially in the United States: he called [[George Washington]] a hypocrite, and was challenged to a duel by [[Andrew Stevenson]], the American minister, whom he was reported to have called a slave breeder.  Notwithstanding his pronounced opposition to slavery, however, O'Connell, in the words of Lee M. Jenkins in her 1999 ''Irish Review'' article \"Beyond the Pale: Frederick Douglass in Cork\", \"accepted money for his Repeal cause from Southern slaveholders\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jenkins|first=Lee|date=Autumn 1999|title=Beyond the Pale: Frederick Douglass in Cork|url=https://www.ucc.ie/en/media/academic/schoolofenglish/worddocuments/IrishReviewpdfJenkins.pdf|journal=The Irish Review|volume=|issue=24|page=92|via=}}</ref>\n\nHistorian Michael Tierney says he was:\n{{quote|A splendid orator, a moderate but creative radical, an uncompromising believer in peaceful agitation, he was acclaimed as the first to reconcile modern democratic principles with the Catholic religion and may be called the forerunner of modern Christian democratic movements.<ref>Michael Tierney, \"Daniel O'Connell\", ''Collier Encyclopedia'' (1996)</ref>}}\n\nHowever, the founder of the [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Irish Labour Party]] and executed [[Easter Rising]] leader [[James Connolly]], devoted a chapter in his 1910 book \"Labour in Irish History\" entitled \"A chapter of horrors: Daniel O'Connell and the working class\" in which he criticised O'Connell's parliamentary record, accusing him of siding consistently with the interests of the propertied classes of the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marxists.org/archive/connolly/1910/lih/chap12.htm|title=James Connolly: Labour in Irish History \u2013 Chapter 12|author=James Connolly|work=marxists.org}}</ref> And [[Patrick Pearse]], Connolly's fellow leader of the Easter Rising, wrote: \"The leaders in Ireland have nearly always left the people at the critical moment.&nbsp;... O'Connell recoiled before the cannon at Clontarf\" though adding \"I do not blame these men; you or I might have done the same. It is a terrible responsibility to be cast on a man, that of bidding the cannon speak and the grapeshot pour\".<ref>Se\u00e1n Cronin, ''Our Own Red Blood'', Irish Freedom Press, New York, 1966, p. 15</ref>\n\nIn O'Connell's lifetime, the aims of his [[Repeal Association]]\u2014an independent Kingdom of Ireland governing itself but keeping the British monarch as its Head of State\u2014proved too radical for the British government of the time to accept, and brought upon O'Connell persecution and suppression.\n\nO'Connell is known in Ireland as \"The Liberator\" or \"The Great Emancipator\" for his success in achieving [[Catholic Emancipation]]. O'Connell admired Latin American liberator [[Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar]], and one of his sons, [[Morgan O'Connell]], was a volunteer officer in Bol\u00edvar's army in 1820, aged 15.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://illyria.com/irish/irishven.html|title=Venezuela's Irish Legacy|author=Brian McGinn|date=November 1991|publisher=Irish America Magazine (New York) Vol. VII, No. XI|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927063024/http://illyria.com/irish/irishven.html|archive-date=27 September 2007|accessdate=18 April 2007}}</ref> The principal street in the centre of Dublin, previously called Sackville Street, was renamed [[O'Connell Street]] in his honour in the early 20th century after the [[Irish Free State]] came into being.<ref>{{cite book|title=Dublin Handbook: The Travel Guide|author1=Sheehan, Sean|author2=Levy, Patricia|publisher=Footprint Handbooks|year=2001|isbn=978-1-900949-98-9|page=99|doi=}}</ref> His statue (made by the sculptor [[John Henry Foley]], who also designed the sculptures of the [[Albert Memorial]] in London) stands at one end of the street, with a statue of [[Charles Stewart Parnell]] at the other end.<ref name=\"benn\">{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Dublin|last=Bennett|first=Douglas|publisher=Gill and MacMillan|year=2005|isbn=978-0-7171-3684-1|location=Dublin}}</ref>\n\nThe [[O'Connell Street, Limerick|main street]] of [[Limerick]] is also named after O'Connell, also with a statue at the end (in the centre of the Crescent). O'Connell Streets also exist in [[Ennis]], [[Sligo]], [[Athlone]], [[Kilkee]], [[Clonmel]]. [[Dungarvan]] and [[Waterford]]. The Daniel O'Connell Bridge was built over the Ophir River, [[Central Otago]], [[New Zealand]] in 1880.\n\nThere is a statue honouring O'Connell outside [[St Patrick's Cathedral, Melbourne|St Patrick's Cathedral]] in Melbourne, Australia.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Catholic Church and Community in Australia|author=O'Farrell, Patrick|publisher=Thomas Nelson (Australia), west Melbourne|year=1977}}</ref> There is a museum commemorating him in [[Derrynane House]], near the village of [[Derrynane]], County Kerry, which was once owned by his family.<ref name=\"dh\">{{cite web|url=http://www.heritageireland.ie/en/South-West/DerrynaneHouse/|title=Derrynane House|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090312063843/http://www.heritageireland.ie/en/South-West/DerrynaneHouse/|archivedate=12 March 2009|accessdate=23 January 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was a member of the [[Literary Association of the Friends of Poland]] as well.<ref>Marchlewicz, K. (2005). \"The Pro-Polish Loby in the House of Commons and the House of Lords During the 1830s and 1840s\". ''Przeglad Historyczny'' [''Historical Review''] 96(1), pp. 61\u201376</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=O'Connell, Daniel|volume=19|pages=990-992}}\n*{{CE1913 |first=E. A.|last=d'Alton|wstitle=Daniel O'Connell }}\n*{{cite DNB |wstitle=O'Connell, Daniel (1775-1847)|display=O'Connell, Daniel (1775\u20131847)|volume=41|pages=371\u2013389 }}\n*{{cite encyclopedia|ref=harv|first=Robert Kemp |last=Philp |authorlink=Robert Kemp Philp |url=https://books.google.com/?id=jDsCAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=O'Connell, Morgan|encyclopedia=The dictionary of useful knowledge|year=1861|publisher=Oxford University}}\n*''The Great Dan'', [[Charles Chenevix Trench]], Jonathan Cape Ltd., 1984.\n*''King Dan the Rise of Daniel O'Connell 1775\u20131829,'' Patrick Geoghegan, Gill and Macmillan, 2008.\n*''[[John Mitchel]], A Cause Too Many'', Aidan Hegarty, Camlane Press.\n*''[[Thomas Osborne Davis (Irish politician)|Thomas Davis]], The Thinker and Teacher'', [[Arthur Griffith]], M.H. Gill & Son, 1922.\n*''Daniel O'Connell: The Irish Liberator'', Dennis Gwynn, Hutchinson & Co, Ltd.\n*''O'Connell, Davis and the Colleges Bill'', Dennis Gwynn, Cork University Press 1948.\n*''Labour in Ireland'', [[James Connolly]]'', Fleet Street 1910.''\n*''The Re-Conquest of Ireland'', [[James Connolly]], Fleet Street 1915.\n*''[[John Mitchel]]: Noted Irish Lives'', Louis J. Walsh, The Talbot Press Ltd., 1934.\n*''Life of John Martin'', P. A. Sillard, James Duffy & Co., Ltd 1901.\n*''Ireland Her Own'', T. A. Jackson, Lawrence & Wishart Ltd 1976.\n*''Life and Times of Daniel O'Connell'', T. C. Luby, Cameron & Ferguson.\n*''Paddy's Lament: Ireland 1846\u20131847, Prelude to Hatred'', Thomas Gallagher, Poolbeg 1994.\n*''The Great Shame'', [[Thomas Keneally]], Anchor Books 1999.\n*''Envoi, Taking Leave of [[R. F. Foster (historian)|Roy Foster]]'', by Brendan Clifford and Julianne Herlihy, Aubane Historical Society, Cork.\n*''In Search of Ireland's Heroes'', [[Carmel McCaffrey]]. Ivan R Dee Publisher\n*''O'Connell: The Life of Daniel O'Connell,'' 1775\u20131847, Oliver Macdonagh, Weidenfeld & Nicolson, 1991\n*MacDonagh, Oliver. ''O'Connell: The Life of Daniel O'Connell 1775\u20131847'' 1991.\n* Murphy, Angela F. '' American Slavery, Irish Freedom: Abolition, Immigrant Citizenship, and the Transatlantic Movement for Irish Repeal'' (2010) [http://www.h-net.org/reviews/showrev.php?id=31925 online review]\n*[[Se\u00e1n \u00d3 Faol\u00e1in]], ''King of the Beggars: A Life of Daniel O'Connell'', 1938.\n* O'Ferrall, Fergus. ''Daniel O'Connell'' (Gill's Irish Lives Series), Gill & MacMillan, Dublin, 1981.\n* Tierney, Michael, ed. ''Daniel O'Connell: Nine Centenary Essays'' (1949)\n\n*{{cite book |first=Maurice R. |last=O'Connell |title=The Correspondence of Daniel O'Connell |location=Dublin |date=1972\u20131980 |publisher=[[Irish Manuscripts Commission]] }} 8 vols: [http://www.irishmanuscripts.ie/digital/The%20Correspondence%20of%20Daniel%20O'Connell%20Vol.%20I.%201792-1814/ Vol. I. 1792\u20131814] [http://www.irishmanuscripts.ie/digital/The%20Correspondence%20of%20Daniel%20O'Connell%20Vol.%20II.%201815-1823/ Vol. II. 1815\u20131823] [http://www.irishmanuscripts.ie/digital/The%20Correspondence%20of%20Daniel%20O'Connell%20Vol.%20III.%201824-1828/ Vol. III. 1824\u20131828] [http://www.irishmanuscripts.ie/digital/The%20Correspondence%20of%20Daniel%20O'Connell%20Vol.%20IV.%201829-1832/ Vol. IV. 1829\u20131832] [http://www.irishmanuscripts.ie/digital/The%20Correspondence%20of%20Daniel%20O'Connell%20Vol.%20V.%201833-1836/ Vol. V. 1833\u20131836] [http://www.irishmanuscripts.ie/digital/The%20Correspondence%20of%20Daniel%20O'Connell%20Vol.%20VI.%201837-1840/ Vol. VI. 1837\u20131840] [http://www.irishmanuscripts.ie/digital/The%20Correspondence%20of%20Daniel%20O'Connell%20Vol.%20VII.%201841-1845/ Vol. VII. 1841\u20131845] [http://www.irishmanuscripts.ie/digital/The%20Correspondence%20of%20Daniel%20O'Connell%20Vol.%20VIII.%201846-1847/index.html Vol. VIII. 1846\u20131847]\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[History of Ireland (1801-1922)]]\n* [[Irish nobility]]\n* [[List of people on stamps of Ireland]]\n* [[List of public art in Dublin]]\n* [[List of public art in Limerick]]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n{{wikisourceauthor}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.heritage.nf.ca/society/oconnell.html Daniel O'Connell and Newfoundland]\n* [http://www.fordham.edu/halsall/mod/1836oconnell.html Modern History Sourcebook: Daniel O'Connell: Justice for Ireland, Feb 4, 1836]\u2014O'Connell's speech in the House of Commons\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130730164720/http://multitext.ucc.ie/d/Daniel_OConnell Daniel O\u2019Connell]\u2014Multitext Project in Irish History (with extensive image gallery)\n* {{hansard-contribs | mr-daniel-oconnell | Daniel O'Connell }}\n* [http://bc-primo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo_library/libweb/action/dlDisplay.do?institution=BCL&vid=bclib&onCampus=false&docId=ALMA-BC21381539170001021 Daniel O'Connell Collection] \u2013 at Boston College John J. Burns Library\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oconnell, Daniel}}\n[[Category:1775 births]]\n[[Category:1847 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at Glasnevin Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Duellists]]\n[[Category:Irish barristers]]\n[[Category:Irish Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Irish tax resisters]]\n[[Category:Lord Mayors of Dublin]]\n[[Category:Members of Lincoln's Inn]]\n[[Category:O'Connell family|Daniel]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Kerry]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic activists]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1826\u20131830]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1830\u20131831]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1831\u20131832]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1832\u20131835]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1835\u20131837]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1837\u20131841]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1841\u20131847]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Clare constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Waterford constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Kerry constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Dublin constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Kilkenny constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Meath constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Cork constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Irish Repeal Association MPs]]\n", "name_user": "OwenBlacker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Language tagging", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniel_O%27Connell"}
{"title_page": "History of the Wales national football team (1876\u20131976)", "text_new": "{{short description|Football team history}}\n{{good article}}\n{{see also|History of the Wales national football team (1977\u2013present)}} \n[[File:Wales national team 1900.jpg|thumb|upright=2|The Wales national team in 1900|alt=A sepia image of a football team]]\nThe [[Wales national football team]] is the third oldest side in international [[association football]]. Wales played its first fixture in March 1876, four years after [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] and [[England national football team|England]] had contested the first-ever international match. The team played annual fixtures against Scotland, England, and later [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] and these were eventually organised into the [[British Home Championship]], an annual competition between the [[Home Nations]]. Wales did not win its first championship until the [[1906\u201307 British Home Championship|1906\u201307 edition]] of the competition and the triumph remained the nation's only one before the First World War. Wales improved considerably in the post-war period, and claimed three titles during the 1920s, despite the team was often hindered by the reluctance of [[English Football League|Football League]] clubs to release its players for international duty. The situation was so grave that, in the early 1930s, Wales was forced to select a team of lower league and amateur players in a side that became known as \"Keenor and the 10 unknowns\", a reference to captain [[Fred Keenor]] and the relative obscurity of his teammates.\n\nAble to call upon its strongest side, Wales enjoyed its most successful period in the British Home Championship, winning four titles in the six years before the Second World War. When competitive football resumed after the war, Wales began facing opponents from farther afield and played matches against numerous other European nations for the first time. The side also began competing in qualification groups for the [[FIFA World Cup]], but failed to qualify for the [[1950 FIFA World Cup|1950]] and [[1954 FIFA World Cup|1954]] editions. Under manager [[Jimmy Murphy (footballer)|Jimmy Murphy]], Wales qualified for its first World Cup in [[1958 FIFA World Cup|1958]] and progressed from its group before being defeated by [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] in the quarter-final in its following match. \n\nThe side suffered a decline in the 1960s as the 1958 World Cup generation gradually retired. [[Dave Bowen]] replaced Murphy and managed the team for a decade on a part-time basis but enjoyed little success, failing to qualify for a World Cup or the early editions of the [[UEFA European Championship|European Nations' Cup]] (later known as the European Championships). He did help the side to share the British Home Championship during the [[1969\u201370 British Home Championship|1969\u201370 season]], the last time Wales won the tournament before the competition was discontinued. In total, Wales won the championship 12 times, sharing five titles. \n\nBowen left the role in 1974, having turned down the chance to take the position full-time. He was replaced by Englishman [[Mike Smith (football manager)|Mike Smith]] who led the side to the quarter-finals of [[UEFA Euro 1976]] in its centenary year, before being defeated by [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]].{{#tag:ref|For the 1976 tournament, quarter-finals were played as a two-legged, home and away tie with the finals hosting only the semi-finals and beyond.<ref name=\"1976rsssf\"/>|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==Formation and early matches==\n[[File:Wales V Scotland 3386999.tif|thumb|A newspaper report of Wales' first competitive match against Scotland in 1876|alt=A newspaper report of a football match]]\nThe [[1872 Scotland v England football match|first]] official international [[association football]] match was held in November 1872 between [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] and [[England national football team|England]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0012/ |title=The first international football match |publisher=BBC |last=Mitchell |first=Paul |accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> Four years later, G. A. Clay-Thomas, a Welshman living in London, placed adverts in sports magazines ''[[The Field (magazine)|The Field]]'' and ''[[Bell's Life in London|Bell's Life]]'' proposing that a Welsh side be raised for a match against either Scotland or Ireland in [[rugby union|rugby]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3853930/3853938/76/Clay |title=Football |newspaper=Wrexham Guardian |p=8 |date=18 March 1876 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref> [[Llewelyn Kenrick]], a solicitor who had helped to found [[Druids F.C.]] in North Wales, pushed ahead with plans for a football match and accepted an invitation to play the Scottish national side. He helped establish the [[Football Association of Wales]] (FAW) in February 1876 to finalise arrangements for the forthcoming match,<ref name=\"Challenge\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wrexham.gov.uk/english/heritage/welsh_football/index.htm#y1876|title=1876 Kenrick's Challenge|work=The Story of Welsh Football |publisher=Wrexham County Borough Council|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> being appointed its first secretary.<ref>{{harvnb|Lile|Farmer|1984|p=196}}</ref> To qualify for selection, players were required to be Welsh or to have resided in the country for at least three years.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3386960/3386966/102/Football |title=The International Football Match |newspaper=The Cardiff Times |p=6 |date=4 March 1876 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref> Kenrick was criticised by some in South Wales for failing to notify players in the region of the forthcoming match, favouring to publish notices in London-based journals.<ref name=\"stead1013\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=10\u201313}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=120}}</ref> Unperturbed, he pushed forward with his plans and trial matches were held to find suitable players for the match.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3853883/3853888/16/Football |title=The International Football Match |newspaper=Wrexham Guardian |p=5 |date=12 February 1876 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref>\n\nThe [[1876 Scotland v Wales football match|first Wales international football match]] was held on 2 March 1876 at [[Hamilton Crescent]] in [[Partick]] with the side wearing white shirts, featuring the [[Prince of Wales's feathers]], and black shorts.<ref name=\"stead1013\"/> The Welsh side were outclassed by their more experienced opponents, suffering a 4\u20130 defeat.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/lifestyle/wales-v-scotland-legendary-clashes-2021031 |title=Wales v Scotland: Legendary clashes |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |last=Beech |first=Richard |date=12 October 2012 |accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> A second fixture between the two sides was arranged for the following year and the [[Racecourse Ground]] in [[Wrexham]] became the venue for [[Wales national football team home stadium|Wales' first home international]].<ref name=\"dprecord\">{{cite news |url=https://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/racecourse-worlds-oldest-international-venue-2830017 |title=Is the Racecourse the world's oldest international venue? |newspaper=Daily Post |date=16 June 2008 |accessdate=25 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925141407/https://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/racecourse-worlds-oldest-international-venue-2830017 |archive-date=25 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Welsh side fell to a 2\u20130 defeat in the match. Wales returned to Scotland in 1878 but a fixture clash with the final of the [[Welsh Cup]] between Druids and [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] led many players to refuse to travel. Such was the desperation to find willing players, the secretary of the [[Scottish Football Association]] travelled to Wales and visited the homes of players in an attempt to raise a side. A squad was eventually assembled but, having travelled overnight to Glasgow and containing many players who were not of sufficient standard, the side suffered a 9\u20130 defeat. The result remains Wales' worst defeat in international football.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=27}}</ref>\n\nIn 1879, Wales and [[England national football team|England]] met for the first time in international football at a snow-covered [[The Oval|Kennington Oval]] in [[South London]]. The poor weather conditions resulted in the match being shortened to 60 minutes and the relatively unknown status of the Welsh side led to a low turnout of spectators; newspaper reports estimate the crowd was in the low hundreds with some even stating less than 100.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1872-00/1878-79/M0008Wal1879.html |title=England 2\u20131 Wales |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=29}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=RcfKAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA79&lpg=PA79&dq=England+Wales+1879+snow+football&source=bl&ots=Cdw8QFMIi4&sig=ACfU3U1mF0MrVD9Z2p2ddF5DyEeI1JsjRQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjgs6mTibXnAhXhQxUIHeT6BbgQ6AEwFnoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=England%20Wales%201879%20snow%20football&f=false |title=The Victorian Football Miscellany |p=79 |last=Brown |first=Paul |publisher=Superelastic |year=2013 |isbn=9780956227058}}</ref> In the match, [[William Davies (footballer, born 1855)|William Davies]] scored Wales' first international goal but his side were defeated 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wrexham.gov.uk/english/heritage/welsh_football/1877_1879.htm |title=The Story of Welsh Football 1877\u20131879 |work=The Story of Welsh Football |publisher=Wrexham County Borough Council|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> The standard of the Welsh side was slowly improving and the side nearly held the visiting English side in March 1880. Having trailed 3\u20130, the Welsh side scored twice in the final ten minutes through [[William Roberts (footballer, born 1859)|William Roberts]] and [[John Roberts (footballer, born 1857)|John Roberts]] but were unable to equalise.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1872-00/1879-80/M0011Wal1880.html |title=Wales 2\u20134 England |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref> William Roberts also scored Wales' goal against Scotland two weeks later in a 5\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=30}}</ref> Wales travelled to [[Alexandra Meadows]] in [[Blackburn]] the following year to play England. [[John Vaughan (footballer, born 1856)|John Vaughan]] scored the only goal of the game as Wales won its first international football match.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/4478237/4478241/90/Wales%20football |title=England V Wales |newspaper=Western Mail |p=4 |date=28 February 1881 |accessdate=15 December 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref><ref name=\"wcbc1880\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wrexham.gov.uk/english/heritage/welsh_football/1880_1914.htm|title=The Story of Welsh Football 1880\u20131914 ||work=The Story of Welsh Football |publisher=Wrexham County Borough Council|accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] were the final [[Home Nations|Home Nation]] to establish an international football team, playing its first fixture in February 1882 against England. Having suffered a 13\u20130 defeat against the English,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1872-00/1881-82/M0014Ire1882.html |title=Ireland 0\u201313 England |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref> the Irish side travelled to the Racecourse Ground to meet Wales for the first time. The more experienced Welsh side also proved too strong for the Irish, with [[John Price (footballer, born 1854)|John Price]] becoming the first [[List of Wales national football team hat-tricks|Welshman to score a hat-trick in international football]] during a 7\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://tinyurl.gale.com/tinyurl/CXDsd2 |url-access=subscription |title=Wales V Ireland |newspaper=The Times |p=10 |date=27 February 1882 |accessdate=15 December 2019 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Buoyed by their win, the Welsh side met England a month later and recorded a second victory over their neighbours. England had taken a 2\u20131 lead but were reduced to ten men when [[Charles Bambridge]] suffered a shoulder injury.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=31}}</ref> Wales pulled the score back to 3\u20133 before scoring twice in the final three minutes to claim a 5\u20133 victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1872-00/1881-82/M0016Wal1882.html |title=Wales 5\u20133 England |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Start of the British International Championship==\n\nWith all of the Home Nations competing regularly, the decision was taken to introduce a competitive tournament between the sides and the [[British Home Championship|British International Championship]] (later to become better known as the British Home Championship) was created in 1884.<ref name=\"stead3234\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=32\u201334}}</ref> The [[1883\u201384 British Home Championship|inaugural edition of the tournament]] was won by Scotland which won all three of its ties. Having defeated Ireland 6\u20130 in its opening match, Wales went on to finish third after suffering successive defeats to England and Scotland.<ref name=\"bhc\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1884-99.html#1884 |title=British Home Championship 1884\u20131899 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref> The early stages of the competition continued on the same lines; England and Scotland competed for the title, while Wales would finish third by defeating Ireland. In the first three years of competition, Wales' only points other than in matches against Ireland was a 1\u20131 draw with England in the [[1884\u201385 British Home Championship|1884\u201385 tournament]].<ref name=\"stead3234\"/> In the [[1886\u201387 British Home Championship|1886\u201387 edition]], Wales finished bottom of the competition for the first time after losing all three of its matches, including a 4\u20131 defeat to Ireland in the nation's first victory in international football. Wales had struggled to raise a team for the match and included Wrexham defender [[Bob Roberts (footballer, born 1863)|Bob Roberts]] playing as the goalkeeper. FAW secretary [[Alexander Hunter (footballer)|Alexander Hunter]] also stepped in when [[Humphrey Jones]] withdrew late.<ref name=\"stead3234\"/> Hunter had never played football at such a level and his performance was described as \"glaringly deficient\".<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=93}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wales national team 1887.jpg|thumb|upright|The Welsh national side in 1887|alt=A black and white photo of a football team]]\nIn a reversal of the previous year's events, the ''[[Freeman's Journal]]'' claimed a weakened Ireland team travelled to Wales for the [[1887\u201388 British Home Championship]] and went on to lose the match 11\u20130,<ref name=\"wcbc1880\"/> although there were only four debutants in the team on the day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nifootball.blogspot.com/2010/11/017-3-march-1888.html?m=1 |title=Wales 11\u20130 Ireland |publisher=Northern Ireland Footballing Great |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> The scoreline remains a record victory for Wales. [[Jack Doughty]] scored four of the goals. Such was the one-sided nature of the game that three Welsh players left the field before the match ended to ensure they were on time for their train home.<ref name=\"stead3234\"/> 5\u20131 defeats to both England and Scotland however ensured another third-place finish for Wales.<ref name=\"bhc\"/>\n\nWales avoided defeat in a fixture against Scotland for the first time with a goalless draw in the [[1888\u201389 British Home Championship]], simultaneously recording a first clean sheet against the Scots. The feat was achieved despite local amateur [[Alf Pugh]] starting in goal for Wales after the original selection, [[James Trainer]], failed to arrive at the match.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3670619/3670622/93/Wales%20football |title=Scotland vs Wales Association |newspaper=South Wales Daily News |p=3 |date=16 April 1889 |accessdate=16 December 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref> Pugh played the first 30 minutes before Wrexham's [[Sam Gillam]] arrived and took his place,<ref name=\"stead3234\"/> thus becoming the first substitution ever used in international football.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wales 0 Scotland 0|url=http://www.londonhearts.com/scotland/games/18890415.html|publisher=londonhearts.com|accessdate=16 December 2019|date=15 April 1889}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/columns/story/_/id/1521829/ask-espn-fc-champions-league-winning-skippers |title=Champions League-winning skippers |publisher=ESPN |last=Jolly |first=Richard |date=14 August 2013 |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> The following year, Wales played a home fixture outside the nation for the first time when a meeting with Ireland was held in [[Shrewsbury]] in an attempt to draw a large crowd. Wales won the match 5\u20132.<ref name=\"stead4041\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=40\u201341}}</ref> By the early 1890s, with the domestic game thriving in England, Wales was struggling to get players released for international fixtures, particularly for away matches against Ireland which required a three-day absence from a player's club due to ferry travel. As a result, Wales finished bottom of the British Home Championship five times during the decade, including three consecutive seasons between 1891 and 1893.<ref name=\"bhc\"/><ref name=\"stead4041\"/> Wales did record its highest placed finish to date in 1895 by finishing as runners-up to England after drawing all three of its fixtures, inspired by the likes of James Trainer, [[Billy Lewis (footballer)|Billy Lewis]] and a debuting [[Billy Meredith]].<ref name=\"bhc\"/><ref name=\"stead4748\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=47\u201348}}</ref>\n\nWales continued its good form at the start of the [[1895\u201396 British Home Championship]] by thrashing Ireland 6\u20130 with both Meredith and Lewis scoring [[hat-trick|braces]]. The team's optimism was short-lived however when they suffered a crushing 9\u20131 defeat to England in their following match,<ref name=\"stead4748\"/> with [[Steve Bloomer]] scoring five of his side's goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/bloomer-intlg.html |title=Stephen Bloomer \u2013 International Goals |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last=Klukowski |first=Tomasz |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> Wales would finish the 20th century by losing nine of its final ten matches, only avoiding defeat in a 2\u20132 draw with Scotland in March 1897. The difficulties in calling up players from English teams became so pronounced that the FAW put forward a motion that national teams be granted the right to overrule clubs on player selection, although this was rejected. An approach to the English governing body, [[The Football Association]], also fell on deaf ears.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=51}}</ref>\n\n==New century==\n[[File:Billymeredith.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Billy Meredith]], who made his debut for Wales in 1895|alt=A footballer poses for a photo]]\nThe [[1899\u20131900 British Home Championship]] revived hope in the side as Wales finished as runners-up to Scotland, led largely by the goals of Meredith and [[Tom Parry (footballer)|Tom Parry]]. Although results were still disappointing, the standard of the Welsh side was deemed to be improving rapidly as margins of defeat became smaller and several defeats to the English and Scottish sides between 1902 and 1905 were deemed unlucky based on the run of play.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=66\u201367}}</ref> The side also avoided defeat in an away fixture against the Scots in March 1904 after holding their opponents to a 1\u20131 draw. The following year, Wales defeated Scotland for the first time in its history after 29 years when goals from Meredith, [[Grenville Morris]] and [[Walter Watkins]] secured a 3\u20131 victory,<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=69}}</ref> although Wales was unable to capitalise on the victory as they finished second to England in the [[1905\u201306 British Home Championship]] after failing to win either of its other fixtures.<ref name=\"bhc1900\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1900-14.html |title=British Home Championship 1900\u20131914 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> Having missed the previous two years while serving a ban for his part in the [[English football bribery scandal|1905 English football bribery scandal]], Meredith returned to play for Wales in the [[1906\u201307 British Home Championship]]. In its first match, Wales defeated Ireland 3\u20132 in [[Belfast]] with Meredith scoring his side's second goal before [[Lot Jones]] scored the winning goal. Grenville Morris scored the only goal of the match to give Wales its third consecutive victory over Scotland.<ref name=\"stead7476\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=74\u201376}}</ref> In Wales' final match, Lot Jones gave his side the lead at [[Craven Cottage]] before England equalised in the second half.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1900-39/1906-07/M0090Wal1907.html |title=England 1\u20131 Wales |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> England went on to draw its final game of the tournament against Scotland, handing Wales its first British Home Championship success. All 21 players used in the tournament were awarded a commemoration medal by the FAW for the achievement.<ref name=\"stead7476\"/>\n\nThe team's fortunes suffered a complete reversal in the [[1907\u201308 British Home Championship|1907\u201308 Championship]]. After losing their opening match against Scotland, the side suffered a 7\u20131 home defeat to England in a match where three goalkeepers were used. A final defeat against Ireland resulted in Wales finishing bottom of the championship table one year after winning the tournament outright.<ref name=\"stead7679\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=76\u201379}}</ref> Several personnel changes were implemented soon after, [[Ted Robbins (football administrator)|Ted Robbins]] was appointed FAW secretary in 1909 and one of Wales' most prominent players of the era, goalkeeper [[Leigh Richmond Roose]], was dropped.<ref name=\"stead7679\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=234}}</ref> Although considered \"one of the greatest players of his generation\",<ref name=\"Roose\">{{cite web |url=https://biography.wales/article/s-ROOS-RIC-1877 |title=Leigh Richmond Roose |publisher=Dictionary of Welsh Biography |last=Richards |first=Thomas |accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> Roose had developed a reputation for eccentricity that proved costly at times. In March 1910, Wales suffered a 1\u20130 defeat to Scotland when Roose allowed a speculative shot into the net having had his back turned towards play, talking to a spectator. In November of the same year, Roose suffered a broken arm while playing for his club side but declared himself fit for the British Home Championship internationals in March 1911. A poor performance in a 2\u20132 draw with Scotland ultimately ended his international career as he was never selected for Wales again.<ref name=\"stead7679\"/>\n\nWales came within one match of winning a second title in 1912 and 1913, losing deciding matches against England on both occasions.<ref name=\"bhc1900\"/> In the [[1913\u201314 British Home Championship|final edition of the championship]] before the First World War, Wales finished bottom of the table with one point. Robbins complained that English clubs had been \"antagonistic\" when asked to release players for international duty. In December 1914, the Home Nations took the decision to suspend the British Home Championship following the outbreak of the war.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=85}}</ref> Eight players who had represented Wales in international football were killed during the conflict, including Leigh Roose.<ref name=\"Roose\"/>\n\nWales' first fixtures at the end of the war were two friendly matches against England, organised to raise funds for the FAW. The matches were not considered full internationals, being titled victory matches instead. Wales won the first meeting, led by 40-year old Meredith, but was defeated in the return match a fortnight later.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=89}}</ref> The British Home Championship returned for the [[1919\u201320 British Home Championship|1919\u201320 season]] with Wales' first post-war match ending in a 2\u20132 draw with pre-war champions Ireland in Belfast.<ref name=\"bhc1920\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1920-39.html |title=British Home Championship 1920\u20131939 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> A draw against Scotland was followed by a 2\u20131 victory over England, the first time Wales had defeated its neighbour in a competitive fixture since 1882. Goals from [[Stan Davies]] and [[Dick Richards (footballer)|Dick Richards]] secured victory for Wales, which had been reduced to ten men in the second half when [[Harry Millership]] went off injured, but the performance of the now 45-year old Meredith drew headlines.<ref name=\"stead9293\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=92\u201393}}</ref> Winning his final cap, 25 years after his debut, Meredith wept openly at the end of the match.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=57}}</ref> He ended his international career as both Wales' most-capped player and its record goalscorer having scored 11 times in 48 appearances.<ref name=\"rsssfplayers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/wal-recintlp.html |title=Wales \u2013 Record International Players |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last=Passo Alpuin |first=Luis Fernando |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref> The team were still reliant on England defeating Scotland to secure its second championship. Despite leading 4\u20132 at half-time, Scotland lost the match 5\u20134.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/><ref name=\"stead9293\"/>\n\n==1920s success and decline==\n\nWales was unable to defend its title in the [[1920\u201321 British Home Championship|1920\u201321 season]], losing 2\u20131 to Scotland in the opening game. A goalless draw with England and a 2\u20131 victory over Ireland did secure the side the runners-up spot.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/> With club sides in Wales attracting record crowds, the national team often found itself losing out to the domestic game. The victory over Ireland was held on the same day that [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] hosted [[South Shields F.C.|South Shields]] in the [[Football League Second Division]], with only 11,000 attending the national side's match in Swansea while more than 30,000 attended Cardiff's fixture.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=94\u201395}}</ref> Disappointing results between 1922 and 1923 prompted a revamp of the team for the [[1923\u201324 British Home Championship]]. One of the debutants in the team was [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea Town's]] [[Willie Davies (footballer)|Willie Davies]] who made an instant impact, scoring one of his side's goals during a 2\u20130 victory over Scotland in the opening game. Davies scored again in Wales' second match, a 2\u20131 victory over England with [[Ted Vizard]] scoring the winning goal. A final victory over Ireland, via a [[Moses Russell]] penalty, secured the title for Wales having beaten all three sides in the same tournament for the first time.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=98\u201399}}</ref> The success was partly attributed to the team's star players being released to play, but this trend soon reverted to type for the opening match of the [[1924\u201325 British Home Championship|1924\u201325 tournament]]; six players withdrew from the squad for the opening match, a 3\u20131 defeat to Scotland. Wales' success did prompt England to agree to a Saturday fixture in Wales for the first time; [[Fred Keenor]] scored for Wales but the side fell to a 2\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=100\u2013101}}</ref> Only a goalless draw with Ireland stopped Wales finishing last, only a year after winning the tournament.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/>\n\nSquad withdrawals proved a continued problem for the Welsh side. When Wales was left short for the visit of Scotland in the [[1925\u201326 British Home Championship|1925\u201326 Championship]], Ted Robbins called up debutant [[Jack Lewis (footballer, born 1902)|Jack Lewis]] after following him to a train station in [[Newport, Wales|Newport]] where he was due to travel to Birmingham to play for Cardiff City.<ref name=\"s105106\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=105\u2013106}}</ref> Defeats to Scotland and Ireland followed and Robbins was again forced to make a last minute interception for the final match against England. [[John Pullen]] had been travelling to London with Moses Russell and was persuaded to join up to win his first cap, alongside [[Charlie Jones (footballer, born 1899)|Charlie Jones]].<ref name=\"s105106\"/> Wales went on to win the match 3\u20131.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/> Wales recorded a third championship win of the decade during the [[1927\u201328 British Home Championship|1927\u201328 tournament]]. The competition had started poorly for the side, conceding two goals in the first half against Scotland before [[Ernie Curtis]] and an own goal by [[Jimmy Gibson (footballer, born 1901)|Jimmy Gibson]] salvaged a point. Wales defeated England 2\u20131 before travelling to Belfast to play Ireland in the final match. The game was tied at 1\u20131 until [[Wilf Lewis]] secured the win for Wales, scoring the winning goal by charging both the ball and opposition goalkeeper into the net. When Ireland defeated Scotland two weeks later, Wales was officially confirmed as winners.<ref name=\"s110112\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=110\u2013112}}</ref>\n\nIn 1929, the FAW received an invitation to tour Canada and selected a 20-man squad for the trip.<ref name=\"s110112\"/> Wales played 15 matches against regional teams in little over a month on the tour, winning each one.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/britishfatours.html#1929WAL |title=British FA XI Tours |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |last=Morrison |first=Neil |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref> [[Len Davies]] proved prolific during the tour, scoring seven of his side's goals in an 8\u20130 victory over Lower Mainland.<ref name=\"s110112\"/> However, Wales returned to one of the worst British Home Championship campaigns in its history. After suffering a 4\u20132 defeat to Scotland in the opening match, Wales endured a 6\u20130 defeat to England in its second fixture.<ref name=\"s113114\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=113\u2013114}}</ref> The tournament ended with a severely depleted Wales side succumbing to a 7\u20130 defeat to Ireland in which [[Joe Bambrick]] scored six of his side's goals,<ref>{{harvnb|Leighton|2010|p=142}}</ref> the most any player has scored in a single match against Wales. The national side's poor results at the end of the 1920s were partly blamed on the deterioration of Welsh club sides. By the end of the decade, Cardiff City had been relegated to the Second Division, [[Aberdare Athletic F.C.|Aberdare Athletic]] had dropped out of the Football League and both [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] and [[Merthyr Town F.C.|Merthyr Town]] had survived re-elections to avoid the same fate.<ref name=\"s113114\"/>\n\n==Pre-war recovery==\n[[File:Fred Keenor, Brentford FC footballer, 1919.jpg|thumb|left|[[Fred Keenor]], who captained the team of \"unknowns\" in 1930|alt=A black and white image of a footballer]]\nIn 1930, the Football League introduced a new ruling which prohibited its members from releasing players for international fixtures. The ruling was designed to force international matches to be scheduled on days that would not clash with Football League fixtures. Wales' first match under the ruling was the opening game of the [[1930\u201331 British Home Championship]] against Scotland, which was largely unaffected as it drew the majority of its players from its own leagues. Wales were forced to call up a mixture of lower division and amateur players in order to field a side. Nine of Wales' eleven players made their international debut in the game, with only captain Fred Keenor and goalkeeper [[Len Evans (footballer)|Len Evans]] having previous international experience. As a result, the team was dubbed \"Keenor and the 10 unknowns\".<ref name=\"BBCunknowns\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45425572 |title=Denmark v Wales: The story of the 1930s 'unknowns' who forced a draw in Scotland |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |last=Williams |first=Aled |date=7 September 2018 |accessdate=14 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324124029/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45425572 |archive-date=24 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"s116118\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=116\u2013118}}</ref> Ahead of the match, Keenor asked Ted Robbins if he could have the players to himself for four hours before the game. Taking the team to relax and discuss tactics for the match, in his pre-match team talk he exhorted his teammates, \"There's eleven of them and eleven of us, and there's only one ball, and it's ours\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/2014-world-cup-qualifying/2013/3/21/4132198/scotland-vs-wales-2014-world-cup-qualifying |title=Scotland vs. Wales: Five classic matches |publisher=[[SB Nation]] |first=Andi |last=Thomas |date=21 March 2013 |accessdate=14 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818094059/http://www.sbnation.com/2014-world-cup-qualifying/2013/3/21/4132198/scotland-vs-wales-2014-world-cup-qualifying |archive-date=18 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Despite their inexperience, the Welsh side held Scotland to a 1\u20131 draw having taken the lead after six minutes from a goal by [[Tommy Bamford]].<ref name=\"BBCunknowns\"/> The display led to a Scottish newspaper describing the Welsh performance as \"the pluckiest display in the history of international football\".<ref name=\"s116118\"/> The Welsh public also responded by calling for the same side to remain for the following match against England, although [[Elvet Collins]] was replaced due to injury.<ref name=\"s116118\"/> There was no repeat of the result; the Welsh side lost 4\u20130 at the Racecourse Ground.<ref name=\"BBCunknowns\"/>\n\nA compromise between the Football League and the other Home Nations was reached in 1931, with the sides being required to provide 21 days notice for a player's release, although the club were only obliged to release English players. The FAW would also be responsible for the wages and insurance of the players during the time away, a stipulation that placed increasing strain on the organisation's already slim finances.<ref name=\"s119121\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=119\u2013121}}</ref> However, in practice, the more inclusive ruling provided little improvement as the FAW's release requests for players were continually rejected; during the [[1931\u201332 British Home Championship]], Wales finished bottom after losing all of its matches having used 26 players in only 3 games.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/><ref name=\"s119121\"/> The number included [[Eddie Parris]] who became the first black player to represent Wales.<ref name=\"s119121\"/> The FAW subsequently gave in to the Football League and agreed to hold matches in midweek to avoid a fixture clash. The decision proved astute as Wales defeated Scotland 5\u20132 in the opening game of the [[1932\u201333 British Home Championship|1932\u201333 tournament]]. Fred Keenor won his 32nd and final international cap in the game, earning praise for his performance. A goalless draw with England and a 4\u20131 victory over Ireland secured Wales' fifth Home Championship title.<ref name=\"s122123\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=122\u2013123}}</ref>\n\nWales travelled to [[Paris]], France, in May 1933 to play its first international fixture against an opponent other than the Home Nations. [[Thomas Griffiths (footballer, born 1906)|Tommy Griffiths]] scored Wales' goal in a 1\u20131 draw with [[France national football team|France]] at the [[Stade Olympique Yves-du-Manoir]].<ref name=\"s122123\"/> Buoyed by their championship victory, the Welsh team began their title defense in the [[1933\u201334 British Home Championship]] by securing a 3\u20132 victory over Scotland in front of 40,000 fans at [[Ninian Park]]. A draw with Ireland in Belfast meant Wales required a victory over England to guarantee consecutive titles. The match was played at [[St James' Park]] in [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] with Wales taking an early lead through [[Tommy Mills (footballer)|Tommy Mills]]. The tension of the match was so intense that Mills nearly failed to return for the second half having been sick during half-time. [[Eric Brook]] equalised for England in the second half but, with less than ten minutes remaining, [[Dai Astley]] scored a header to give Wales victory and win the Home Championship in consecutive years for the only time in the nation's history.<ref name=\"s124125\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=124\u2013125}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1900-39/1933-34/M0189Wal1933.html |title=England 1\u20132 Wales |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nWales failed to retain its title in [[1933\u201334 British Home Championship|1934\u201335]], finishing last, but narrowly missed out on another title in the [[1935\u201336 British Home Championship]]. Needing a win against Ireland to secure the championship, Wales went on to lose 3\u20132.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/> The side recovered the following season and defeated England in a home fixture for the first time since 1882 via goals from [[Pat Glover]] and [[Seymour Morris]]. Glover again proved the match winner in Wales' second fixture, scoring both goals as the side defeated Scotland 2\u20131. Wales won its third title in five years by winning 4\u20131 over Ireland in its last fixture, Glover scoring two more to finish as top goalscorer with five goals in the competition.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=128\u2013129}}</ref> Wales also went on to share the [[1938\u201339 British Home Championship]] title with both England and Scotland after all three sides attained four points in the final edition of the tournament before the outbreak of the Second World War.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/>\n\n==Wartime and new overseas competition==\nThe British Home Championship was postponed during wartime; Wales' final fixture before the start of the war was a 2\u20131 defeat against France.<ref name=\"matches\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesw/wal-intres.html |title=International matches of Wales |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last=Nyg\u00e5rd |first=Jostein |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref> The side's first wartime fixture was a 1\u20131 draw with England in a charity match to raise money for the [[Red Cross]]. The following year, Wales were hosted at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] for the first time having previously been considered less of a draw than Scotland. Wales won the match 1\u20130 through a goal by [[Bryn Jones (footballer, born 1912)|Bryn Jones]].<ref name=\"s133135\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=133\u2013135}}</ref> For the majority of the war, Wales only played fixtures against England, the two sides met 15 times between 1939 and 1945. Wales final wartime matches were against Scotland and Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.welshsoccerarchive.co.uk/index.php/internationals/wartime |title=Wartime Internationals |publisher=Welsh Football Data Archive |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref> As the war drew to a close, the national side was rocked by the death of Ted Robbins in January 1946. Robbins had served as secretary of the FAW since 1909 and was credited as a major factor in the team's success in previous decades.<ref name=\"s133135\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CCS134824498&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS134824498&searchId=R2&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Sport in Brief |newspaper=The Times |p=8 |date=18 January 1946 |accessdate=21 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref>\n\n[[File:John Charles, Wales versus Scotland, Ninian Park, 1954.jpg|left|thumb|[[John Charles]] (pictured in 1954) was one of Wales' most prominent players during the 1950s.|alt=A footballer poses for a photo in front of a stand]]\nThe British Home Championship returned for the [[1946\u201347 British Home Championship|1946\u201347 campaign]] and Wales' first competitive post-war fixture was against Scotland in October 1946.<ref name=\"matches\"/> The wartime gap had increased public appetite for the sport and the break resulted in an entirely new generation of players being involved in the squad. One of the debutants, [[Trevor Ford]], scored one of Wales' goals in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=43}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=136}}</ref> However, defeats to England and Northern Ireland resulted in a third-place finish during the first post-war championship.<ref name=\"bhc1940\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1947-66.html |title=British Home Championship 1947\u20131966 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref> The following year, Wales began its campaign with a 3\u20130 defeat against England but defeated Scotland at [[Hampden Park]] for the first time.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=138\u2013139}}</ref> A win over Northern Ireland left Wales leading the group with only one match to be played. In the final match, England defeated Scotland to claim the championship by a single point.<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/> In 1949, the Wales national side embarked on its first overseas tour with matches against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]], [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] and [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]]. As all three opponents wore red shirts, the fixtures necessitated the first away kit in Wales' history. A yellow shirt with green collar and trim was adopted for the tour, featuring the [[Welsh Dragon]] on the pocket. The tour proved disastrous for the squad however, as Wales lost all three fixtures and the squad was involved in a road accident when the team coach crashed during a tour of the Swiss Alps.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=143\u2013144}}</ref>\n\nWales and the other Home Nations entered the [[FIFA World Cup]] for the first time in 1950 and the [[1949\u201350 British Home Championship]] was used to determine qualification for the tournament. The added incentive resulted in a crowd of more than 60,000 attending Wales' opening fixture against England at Ninian Park, but they witnessed their side suffer a 4\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=146}}</ref> A further defeat to Scotland ended Wales' hopes of qualification and only a goalless draw with Northern Ireland stopped the side finishing bottom of the group on [[goal difference]].<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/> Prior to the Ireland match, Belgium had travelled to Cardiff to become the first overseas side to visit Wales for an international match. Trevor Ford scored a hat-trick in a 5\u20131 victory for Wales. Portugal and Switzerland also travelled to Wales in 1951, as Wales avenged its earlier defeats by winning both matches.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=148\u2013149}}</ref> During the following year's championship, Trevor Ford became Wales' leading goalscorer of all-time when he scored a brace during a 4\u20132 defeat to England. Having entered the match on ten goals, his double resulted in him overtaking Billy Meredith's tally of eleven.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/trevor-ford-37679/ |title=Trevor Ford Player Statistics |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|Some sources credit [[Billy Lewis (footballer)|Billy Lewis]] with twelve goals for Wales,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1946-60/1950-51/M0260Wal1950.html |title=England 4\u20132 Wales |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref> but most contemporary sources only list him with 8.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/teams/wales/tab/stats/option/scorers/ |title=Wales national football team statistics and records: top scorers |website=11v11.com |publisher=FAS Enterprises |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=12145 |title= Billy Lewis |website=eu-football.info |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref> Further breakdown can be viewed at [[Talk:Billy Lewis (footballer)]].|group=lower-alpha}}\n\nWales celebrated its 75th anniversary by winning its first post-war British Home Championship title by sharing the [[1951\u201352 British Home Championship]] edition with England.<ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=45}}</ref> The two sides had drawn their meeting in the first fixture before both won their remaining matches to finish on five points.<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/> Wales' final match of the competition was a 3\u20130 victory over Northern Ireland at Vetch Field, the first international match held at the ground in 25 years. The Welsh squad contained several young players born or brought up in the Swansea area, including Ford, [[Ivor Allchurch]] and [[Roy Paul]], and the game was regarded as a homecoming match.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=150}}</ref> Allchurch scored one of his side's goals in the match to finish tied as the competition's top goalscorer.<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=47}}</ref> Wales struggled in the years immediately afterwards, finishing bottom of the Championship in consecutive seasons, including the [[1953\u201354 British Home Championship|1953\u201354 tournament]] which saw the team fail to qualify for the [[1954 FIFA World Cup]].<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/> The period also included a disastrous European tour in 1953 during which Wales suffered a 6\u20131 defeat to France and a 5\u20132 defeat to [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=153}}</ref>\n\n===Austria and The Battle of Wrexham===\n[[File:Trevor Ford (1959).jpg|thumb|right|[[Trevor Ford]], once Wales' record goalscorer and whose physical style of play was a reason for Austrian animosity|alt=A headshot of a footballer]] \nIn 1954, encouraged by the work of [[Walter Winterbottom]] with England, the FAW appointed the first manager of the Welsh national side in former captain [[Walley Barnes]].<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=15}}</ref><ref name=\"s155156\"/> His first match in charge of the side was a match against [[Austria national football team|Austria]] in [[Vienna]] which attracted 60,000 spectators. Despite winning 2\u20130, the Austrians were infuriated by the physical style of play adopted by Wales, particularly forwards Ford and [[Derek Tapscott]], which was unfamiliar outside Britain. The Austria captain [[Ernst Ocwirk]] described the match as \"the dirtiest game he'd ever seen.\"<ref name=\"s155156\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=155}}</ref> Yugoslavia travelled to Wales in September 1954 in a reverse of the two side's fixture in 1953 and became the first foreign opposition to win in Wales after winning 3\u20131, having trailed 1\u20130 at half-time.<ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=51}}</ref> Wales' burgeoning involvement in continental football resulted in the FAW being accepted as members of the recently founded [[Union of European Football Associations]] (UEFA) in 1954.<ref name=\"s155156\"/>\n\nThe [[1955\u201356 British Home Championship]] brought some improvement for Wales as the side recorded its first victory over England in 17 years at Ninian Park. The period also saw the emergence of [[John Charles]] for the national side.<ref name=\"s157160\"/> Charles and his brother [[Mel Charles|Mel]] often played alongside another set of brothers, Ivor and [[Len Allchurch]], becoming the first sets of brothers to play for Wales.<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=12}}</ref> John Charles quickly gained a reputation as the side's leading player, featuring as either a [[centre-half]] or [[centre-forward]], and his performance in the victory over England led ''[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]]'' reporter Dewi Lewis to describe him as \"indeed the perfect footballer if ever there was one.\"<ref name=\"s157160\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=157\u2013160}}</ref> All four sides shared the British Home Championship title after finishing on three points, the only occurrence of a four-way tie in the competition's 100-year history. Wales narrowly missed out on winning the title having drawn 1\u20131 with Northern Ireland in its final game in which Roy Paul missed a penalty with Wales already leading 1\u20130. Ireland later equalised and the game ended as a tie.<ref name=\"s157160\"/>\n\nAt the end of 1955, Austria travelled to Wales a year after its 2\u20130 victory. The Austrian team were eager to match the physicality of the Welsh side shown in the first meeting and the match descended into violent chaos.<ref name=\"s157160\"/> The French referee, Louis Fauquemberghe,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/wales-v-austria-23-november-1955-226605/ |title=Wales v Austria 23 November 1955 |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/referee_summary/louis-fauquembergue/1/1/ |title=Louis Fauquembergue |website=worldfootball.net |accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref> who was unable to speak either German or English had little control as both sides continually resorted to fouling each other resulting in injuries to eight players.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wrexham.gov.uk/english/heritage/welsh_football/1945_1985.htm |title=1945\u20131986 |work=The Story of Welsh Football |publisher=Wrexham County Borough Council|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> The most serious were to Austria's [[Theodor Wagner]], who suffered a fractured tibia, and Wales' Mel Charles, who left the field with ten minutes remaining after being heavily fouled.<ref name=\"timesaustria\">{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CCS67851640&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS67851640&searchId=R7&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Rough International Match at Wrexham |newspaper=The Times |p=4 |date=24 November 1955 |accessdate=26 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Roy Paul later described the scene in the Welsh dressing room after the match in his autobiography, writing \"Our goalkeeper, [[Jack Kelsey]], had scars on both legs. Derek Tapscott [...] had a six-inch gash on his knee. [...] John Charles leaned over his brother Melvyn with tears in his eyes. Melvyn lay silent, still dazed by a tackle which had sent him crashing to the ground.\"<ref name=\"s157160\"/> The national media were highly critical after the match; the ''Western Mail'' described the match as \"a disgrace\",<ref name=\"s157160\"/> while ''[[The Times]]'' wrote \"there were times when the pitch resembled a battlefield, with players down here and there\".<ref name=\"timesaustria\"/>\n\n==1958 FIFA World Cup==\n===Qualification and build-up===\nDisappointing results against European teams prompted a change of approach by the FAW who appointed [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] coach [[Jimmy Murphy (footballer)|Jimmy Murphy]] as manager in 1956. Murphy enjoyed an inauspicious start with draws with Northern Ireland and Scotland before a 3\u20131 defeat to England in a match where Wales finished with nine players due to injuries. The British Home Championship was dropped as a qualifying format for the [[1958 FIFA World Cup]] and replaced by randomly drawn [[1958 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualifying groups]]. Wales was drawn alongside [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] and [[East Germany national football team|East Germany]] and started positively by defeating Czechoslovakia 1\u20130 in its first fixture, via a goal by [[Roy Vernon]]. Wales travelled to East Germany in its second game with a squad of only 12 players. John Charles became highly critical of the FAW's reluctance to travel with more than a bare minimum of players, later writing \"There were more selectors than players. It was crazy. You've got to put the players first but with Wales it was the selectors first and the players second.\"<ref name=\"s161163\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=161\u2013163}}</ref> Wales eventually suffered a 2\u20131 defeat to the largely amateur East Germans in the nation's first competitive fixture.<ref name=\"s161163\"/>\n\n[[File:The Israeli team playing against Wales at the Ramat Gan stadium, 1958 D448-079.jpg|thumb|left|Wales playing [[Israel national football team|Israel]] in a [[1958 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF/AFC\u2013UEFA play-off)|play-off]] match to qualify for the [[1958 FIFA World Cup]]|alt=A black and white image of a football match]]\nThe squad continued to Czechoslovakia but had lost three players to illness and injury. The FAW, however, were still reluctant to call-up replacements and only an outcry from the press prompted Ray Daniel and [[Des Palmer]] to join up with the side. Nevertheless, Wales lost the match 2\u20130 and made qualification unobtainable. In the final group match, Palmer scored a hat-trick to defeat East Germany 4\u20131.<ref name=\"s161163\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/58qual.html#gr4 |title=World Cup 1958 qualifications |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref> A second opportunity at qualification emerged in December 1957 as the volatile political situation in Israel led to [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]], [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]] and [[Sudan national football team|Sudan]] withdrawing from matches against the nation for varying reasons. FIFA rules decreed that no team could qualify for a World Cup without playing a match, and so a [[1958 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF/AFC\u2013UEFA play-off)|play-off]] against a European qualifying group runner-up was arranged. [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] was drawn first but also refused to play Israel leading to a second draw in which Wales was selected. The FAW accepted the offer and Wales travelled to [[Tel Aviv]] for the first leg, winning 2\u20130 after goals from Ivor Allchurch and [[Dave Bowen]].<ref name=\"s165166\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Farmer |Stead|1998|p=89}}</ref> The result was the first time Wales had won an international fixture outside Britain.<ref name=\"58guardian\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/jul/01/wales-1958-world-cup-quarter-final-euro-2016 |title=Wales at the 1958 World Cup: a quarter-final run with a difference |newspaper=The Guardian |last=Burton |first=Simon |date=1 July 2016 |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref> Allchurch scored again in the second leg and a further goal from [[Cliff Jones (Welsh footballer)|Cliff Jones]] secured Wales' first qualification to a major international tournament.<ref name=\"s165166\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=165\u2013166}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/15584126.from-the-argus-archive-when-wales-qualified-for-the-world-cup-in-1958-by-beating-israel-at-ninian-park-in-cardiff/ |title=From the Argus archive: When Wales qualified for the World Cup - in 1958 by beating Israel at Ninian Park in Cardiff |newspaper=South Wales Argus |date=27 October 2017 |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nWales received a favourable draw for the group stage of the tournament, being placed alongside [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] and hosts [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]]. The side's preparations for the tournament were hampered by confusion over the availability of John Charles; having failed to qualify, the [[Italian Football Federation]] had instead organised a club tournament featuring Charles' side [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] who were reluctant to release the player. Wales manager Jimmy Murphy prepared his team to play without Charles, but the player eventually secured his release and arrived in Sweden only three days before the start of the competition.<ref name=\"s167168\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=167\u2013168}}</ref> The side was further weakened by the omission of Trevor Ford, the nation's record goalscorer. Ford had been banned from playing in Britain in 1956 after he revealed an illegal payments scandal in club football in his autobiography. Despite continuing to play abroad, he was overlooked for selection.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/league-legend-ford-one-finest-2486582 |title=League legend Ford one of finest Wales players |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |date=30 May 2003 |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref> Derek Tapscott had also fallen out with the FAW while Des Palmer missed out due to injury, leading to [[Colin Webster]] being selected in their stead.<ref name=\"s172173\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=172\u2013173}}</ref> Wales played a single warm-up match prior to the start of the tournament, defeating local amateur side Soltsjobaden 19\u20130.<ref name=\"s167168\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=91}}</ref>\n\n===Tournament===\nWales' opening game of the tournament was against Hungary. Although the Hungarian [[Golden Team]] had previously been considered one of the best teams in the world, the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]] had weakened the side.<ref name=\"58guardian\"/><ref name=\"s169171\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=169\u2013171}}</ref> Nevertheless, Hungary quickly took the lead in the opening five minutes through [[J\u00f3zsef Bozsik]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/wales-v-hungary-08-june-1958-227115/ |title=Wales v Hungary, 08 June 1958 |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref> The Hungarian defensive efforts were largely focused on containing John Charles who received attention described as \"rugged tactics\" by ''The Times''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=12&docId=GALE%7CCS50944713&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS50944713&searchId=R6&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Welsh Fire Earns a Draw |newspaper=The Times |p=3 |date=9 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Journalist Ian Wooldridge wrote that the Hungarian tactics were often \"Just inside or wildly outside the international laws of soccer\".<ref name=\"s169171\"/> Charles scored an equaliser for Wales after 27 minutes, heading in from a corner to secure a 1\u20131 draw.<ref name=\"s169171\"/> In its second match, Wales played a Mexico side that had suffered a 3\u20130 defeat to Sweden in its opening game. The Welsh side entered the game as favourites but struggled to gain the advantage over their opponents.<ref name=\"s169171\"/> Ivor Allchurch gave Wales the lead in the first half but Mexico responded strongly and scored a late equaliser in the 89th minute with Wales having been reduced to 10-men after [[Colin Baker (Welsh footballer)|Colin Baker]] had been injured.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=2&docId=GALE%7CCS235231948&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS235231948&searchId=R7&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Late Goal by Mexico Checks Faltering Wales |newspaper=The Times |p=14 |date=12 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref>\n\nIn its final group match, Wales met Sweden which had already qualified for the quarter-finals and had rested several players as a result.<ref name=\"s169171\"/> The Swedes were still the stronger of the two teams but were unable to breach the Welsh defense and the match ended goalless.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=5&docId=GALE%7CCS50944720&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS50944720&searchId=R8&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales Draw with Sweden |newspaper=The Times |p=3 |date=16 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Wales finished the group stage with three points, tied for second with Hungary necessitating a play-off match between the two sides to determine which would advance.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CCS50551504&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS50551504&searchId=R8&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Three U.K. Teams in World Cup Play-offs |newspaper=The Times |p=3 |date=16 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Wales faced Hungary needing a victory; Hungary's superior goal difference meant a draw would see it advance. Wales were dealt a blow when [[Lajos Tichy]] gave Hungary the lead after 30 minutes while John Charles was again the focus of the Hungarian defence, leaving the field on more than one occasion to receive treatment. Charles though, proved pivotal as he set up Ivor Allchurch for Wales' equalising goal. [[Terry Medwin]] scored a second for Wales and, despite finishing the match with 10-men following an injury to [[Ron Hewitt (footballer, born 1928)|Ron Hewitt]], the side held on to advance to the quarter-finals.<ref name=\"s169171\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=9&docId=GALE%7CCS51337938&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS51337938&searchId=R10&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales to Meet Brazil |newspaper=The Times |p=3 |date=18 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=95}}</ref>\n\nWales met [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], the winners of [[1958 FIFA World Cup Group 4|group 4]], in the quarter-finals. Much of the build-up for Wales focused on John Charles' attempts to recover from injuries sustained against Hungary. Described by one reporter as having received \"the most tremendous battering I have ever seen administered to a soccer player\", Charles failed to recover in time and his place in the side was taken by Colin Webster. Charles' absence proved costly as several chances were spurned with [[Brian Glanville]] of ''The Times'' remarking \"Wales could have won because all sorts of very tempting centres were coming across the goal and John wasn't there to head them in.\"<ref name=\"s172173\"/> Brazil went on to win the match by a single goal, scored by [[Pel\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CCS252140244&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS252140244&searchId=R11&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales' Gallant Exit from World Cup |newspaper=The Times |p=15 |date=20 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref>\n\n==Post World Cup decline==\n===World Cup generation fades===\nThe success of the Welsh team in the World Cup resulted in huge demand for tickets for the side's opening match of the [[1958\u201359 British Home Championship]] against Scotland. However, the capacity home crowd at Ninian Park were left disappointed as Wales suffered a 3\u20130 defeat. Draws against England and Northern Ireland in the final two games left Wales bottom of the Championship, less than a year after its World Cup exploits. The following year, the post World Cup interest in the team led to a crowd of 62,634 attending a match against England at Ninian Park, a new record crowd for Wales and a record attendance for the ground.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=174\u2013176}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/cardiff_city/8007646.stm |title=Farewell Ninian Park |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 April 2009 |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref> Wales began the 1960s by meeting the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] for the first time. The FAW had been against the Irish split and had resisted any attempts for the two sides to play for several years (England had played the Republic for the first time some 14 years earlier). Goals from Cliff Jones and [[Phil Woosnam]] won the match for Wales.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=178}}</ref>\n\nA shared British Home Championship title in [[1959\u201360 British Home Championship]] and a positive finish to the following year's campaign had raised hopes of Wales qualifying for the [[1962 FIFA World Cup]] in Chile.<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/><ref name=\"s179182\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=179\u2013182}}</ref> Wales was drawn in a group with [[Spain national football team|Spain]] and Austria, although Austria withdrew due to financial problems before the matches began.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/62q.html |title=World Cup 1962 Qualifying |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Stokkermans |first1=Karel |last2=Jarreta |first2=Sergio Henrique |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4uJdBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA131&lpg=PA131&dq=Austria+1962+World+cup&source=bl&ots=xw6zGVVbQp&sig=ACfU3U1qFO3zLhQlHcjET-yfjb-mcrttfg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwinmoS1jKznAhU7VxUIHQnQDAYQ6AEwHHoECAIQAQ#v=onepage&q=Austria%201962%20World%20cup&f=false |title=Encyclopedia of the FIFA World Cup |last=Dunmore |first=Tom |publisher=Scarecrow Press |p=131 |year=2015 |isbn=9780810887435}}</ref> Wales met Spain for the first match with a depleted side, missing several players including John Charles and Cliff Jones. Spain won the first match 2\u20131 before the two sides drew 1\u20131 in the second match in [[Madrid]] with Ivor Allchurch scoring Wales' goal. The result subsequently eliminated Wales from qualifying for the World Cup.<ref name=\"s179182\"/> Wales was invited to tour South America in 1962, the first matches played by the team outside Europe. The side played two matches against reigning World Cup holders Brazil, losing both 3\u20131. The tour concluded with a 2\u20131 defeat to Mexico and the retirement of long-serving goalkeeper Jack Kelsey from international football.<ref name=\"s179182\"/>\n\nWales entered the [[UEFA European Championship|European Nations' Cup]] for the first time in 1964 (the Home Nations had not entered the inaugural edition in [[1960 European Nations' Cup|1960]]). In the preliminary qualifying round, Wales were drawn against Hungary and suffered a demoralising 3\u20131 defeat in the first leg in Budapest. A 1\u20131 draw in the return leg resulted in the side's elimination at the first attempt.<ref name=\"s184185\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=184\u2013185}}</ref> In April 1964, manager Jimmy Murphy was forced to miss Wales' match against Northern Ireland after his wife was taken ill. Swansea Town manager [[Trevor Morris (footballer)|Trevor Morris]] was placed in charge as Wales suffered a 3\u20132 defeat. Murphy never took charge of another match for Wales, resigning later in the year due to commitments with his role at Manchester United. The FAW drew up a shortlist of Welsh candidates, which included former players Jack Kelsey, [[Ron Burgess (footballer)|Ron Burgess]] and [[Tommy Jones (footballer, born 1909)|Tommy Jones]]. The role was eventually given to another former player, Dave Bowen, who had captained the team at the 1958 World Cup. Bowen took the job alongside his role as manager of [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]]. His first match in charge ended in victory when two late goals from [[Ken Leek]] secured a 3\u20132 win over Scotland in the [[1964\u201365 British Home Championship]].<ref name=\"s186187\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=186\u2013187}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Swansea Town Football Club (20740154461).jpg|thumb|right|[[Ivor Allchurch]] retired in 1966 as both Wales' record appearance holder and joint record goalscorer.|alt=A footballer jogs around a pitch]]\nIn [[1966 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualifying]] for the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]], Wales was drawn in a group alongside the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]], [[Greece national football team|Greece]] and [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].<ref name=\"66rsssf\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/66qual.html |title=World Cup 1966 qualifications |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> The campaign began poorly for Wales as it lost 1\u20130 to Denmark in [[Copenhagen]] before losing a controversial game against Greece in [[Athens]]. Welsh players Ken Leek and [[Wyn Davies]] were continually fouled which led to brawls between players breaking out on several occasions.<ref name=\"s188190\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=188\u2013190}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CCS67463050&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS67463050&searchId=R2&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales Lose to Greece |newspaper=The Times |p=4 |date=10 December 1964 |accessdate=1 February 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> The home crowd also made attempts to break onto the pitch to confront the Welsh players which led to clashes with local police. Wales would avenge the defeat five months later with a 4\u20131 victory over Greece at Ninian Park in the return fixture. Wales travelled to [[Moscow]] in May 1965, suffering a 2\u20131 defeat in John Charles' final international appearance.<ref name=\"s188190\"/>\n\nDave Bowen was unavailable to manage Wales in its opening match of the [[1965\u201366 British Home Championship]] due to club commitments. Ron Burgess took charge for the match, which ended in a goalless draw.<ref name=\"s188190\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=23}}</ref> Bowen returned for the return fixture against the Soviet Union in October 1965. His side recorded a surprise 2\u20131 victory over their previously unbeaten opponents,<ref name=\"s191\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=191}}</ref> the only match the Soviet Union failed to win during qualifying,<ref name=\"66rsssf\"/> via goals by Roy Vernon and Ivor Allchurch.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/wales-v-ussr-27-october-1965-229197/ |title=Wales v USSR, 27 October 1965 |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> The result was not enough to secure qualification however as, despite beating Denmark 4\u20132 in its final game, Wales finished as runners-up in the group behind the Soviets.<ref name=\"s191\"/> Having failed to qualify for the World Cup, Wales instead embarked on another tour of South America in May 1966, playing two matches against Brazil and one against [[Chile national football team|Chile]]. Ivor Allchurch made his final appearance for Wales in the 2\u20130 defeat to Chile in the final match of the tour.<ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=140}}</ref> He retired as Wales' record appearance holder with 68 caps, and tied with Trevor Ford as the nation's record goalscorer with 23.<ref name=\"rsssfplayers\"/><ref name=\"s191\"/>\n\n===Late 1960s struggles===\nLike the early World Cups, the qualifying phase for [[UEFA Euro 1968]] used the British Home Championship as a qualification group for the tour, with the results of the [[1966\u201367 British Home Championship|1966\u201367]] and [[1967\u201368 British Home Championship|1967\u201368]] editions being combined to determine which of the Home Nations would progress.<ref name=\"s192\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=192}}</ref> Wales began the stage with a 1\u20131 draw against Scotland in October 1966 but ultimately finished third in the 1966\u201367 season after losing heavily to England and recording a goalless draw with Northern Ireland.<ref name=\"bhc1967\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1967-84.html |title=British Home Championship 1967\u20131984 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> For the 1967\u201368 championship, Wales adopted an all-red kit for the first time in its history. The team fared little better, losing to England and Scotland before recording its only victory of the Euro 1968 qualifying campaign by beating Northern Ireland 2\u20130.<ref name=\"s192\"/>\n\nWales recorded a creditable 1\u20131 draw with [[West Germany national football team|West Germany]] in April 1969 ahead of the qualifying campaign for the [[1970 FIFA World Cup]]. However, the side was hampered by withdrawals and refusals to release players for matches. Wales' first match was against reigning European champions [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and Dave Bowen was forced to name several reserve players in the line-up, although the team only lost to a single goal by [[Luigi Riva]]. The side travelled to West Germany to play a return friendly against the side, with Bowen only able to select 13 players for the trip. Nevertheless, Wales recorded a second 1\u20131 draw; [[Barrie Jones]] had given Wales the lead before [[Gerd M\u00fcller]] equalised late in the match. The qualifying campaign for the 1970 World Cup ended with two defeats to East Germany and another to Italy as Wales failed to gain a single point.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/70q.html |title=World Cup 1970 Qualifying |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Stokkermans |first1=Karel |last2=Jarreta |first2=Sergio Henrique |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> Wales also finished bottom of the [[1968\u201369 British Home Championship|last British Home Championship of the decade]] with a single point.<ref name=\"bhc1967\"/>\n\nWales' struggles during the 1960s were blamed on several factors. The refusal of clubs to release players for international duty or to not allow a player to travel until a day before the match often disrupted the team. In his book ''Red Dragons: The Story of Welsh Football'', Phil Stead writes that Dave Bowen often could \"not pick a side until the day of the game because he was never sure who would be available.\"<ref name=\"s195197\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=195\u2013197}}</ref> The final match of the 1970 World Cup qualification group against Italy was nearly forfeited as Wales struggled to name a squad. One player, Wrexham's teenage defender [[Gareth Davies (footballer, born 1949)|Gareth Davies]], was contacted in the early hours of the morning and travelled overnight to make the team's flight to [[Rome]].<ref name=\"s195197\"/> The organisation of the team by the FAW was also criticised. Goalkeeper [[Gary Sprake]] later remarked that \"the international set-up with Wales at this time was amateurish at best\". Sprake later admitted to feigning injury under the guidance of his club manager [[Don Revie]] in order to avoid selection with the national side.<ref name=\"s186187\"/> [[John Toshack]], who made his debut in 1969, made similar comments: \"The whole set-up was a bit of a shambles [...] some of the players with more fashionable clubs were not too concerned about turning up for the less glamorous games.\"<ref name=\"s186187\"/> An incident in 1969 drew considerable criticism of the FAW when it failed to book enough seats for the ten travelling Welsh players and the organisation's members. When none of the officials offered to give up their seat, the crew declared that the last person to board the craft, winger [[Gil Reece]], would have to disembark. A furious Reece was left at the airport and had to travel alone to [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] before crossing the border into East Germany.<ref name=\"s195197\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/other-sport/welsh-greats-pay-tribute-gil-2458945 |title=Welsh greats pay tribute to Gil the Blade |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |date=23 December 2003 |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Departure of Bowen and arrival of Smith==\nWales began the 1970s in a more positive fashion, sharing the [[1969\u201370 British Home Championship]] with England and Scotland. Wales had drawn with both before defeating Northern Ireland.<ref name=\"s200\"/> The success was the final time Wales was victorious in the competition. The title was the 12th time it had won the competition and the fifth time it had shared the title.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc.html |title=British Home Championship Overview |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> The success raised hopes of the team qualifying for [[UEFA Euro 1972]].<ref name=\"s200\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=200}}</ref> Wales were drawn in a group alongside Czechoslovakia, [[Romania national football team|Romania]] and [[Finland national football team|Finland]]. The side began the campaign with a goalless draw against Romania before losing 3\u20131 to Czechoslovakia,<ref name=\"72rsssf\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/72e.html |title=European Championship 1972 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Stokkermans |first1=Karel |last2=Tabeira |first2=Mart\u00edn |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref> having led 1\u20130 with 12 minutes remaining.<ref name=\"s201204\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=201\u2013204}}</ref> Wales recovered with home and away victories over Finland but lost its remaining games to finish third, failing to qualify.<ref name=\"72rsssf\"/> In Wales' home victory over Finland, [[Trevor Hockey]] became the first player to represent the nation under a new parentage rule allowing players to represent countries other than their birth nations.<ref name=\"s201204\"/> His father had been born in [[Abertillery]], thus qualifying him for Wales under the new ruling.<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=83}}</ref>\n\nWales' fortunes dipped alarmingly in the immediate years afterwards; the side finished bottom of the British Home Championship in four consecutive seasons between 1971 and 1975, winning only one match.<ref name=\"bhc1967\"/> The team did perform slightly better during qualifying for the [[1974 FIFA World Cup]] in which they were drawn against England and [[Poland national football team|Poland]]. Wales lost to England in its opening game, failing to score for a sixth consecutive match, but surprised many by holding England to a draw in the return fixture at Wembley Stadium having taken an early lead through John Toshack.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/74qual.html#gr5 |title=World Cup 1974 qualifications |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"s207209\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=207\u2013209}}</ref> Wales met Poland in March 1973 and recorded a 2\u20130 victory through goals by Trevor Hockey and [[Leighton James]]. Hockey would turn villain shortly before half-time in the return match in [[Chorz\u00f3w]], becoming the first Welsh player to be sent-off.<ref name=\"s207209\"/> The match deteriorated further in the second half as both sides committed numerous fouls and several scuffles broke out between the sides. [[Terry Yorath]] commented that he felt \"your physical well being was at risk\" during the game, while ''The Times'' headline referred to the match as \"a night of delinquency\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CCS302217531&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS302217531&searchId=R2&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales lose their place and good name on night of delinquency |newspaper=The Times |p=18 |date=27 September 1973 |accessdate=2 February 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> In 1974, the FAW decided that the Wales manager's job required a full-time occupant and offered Dave Bowen the position on a permanent full-time basis. Bowen however rejected the role, unwilling to leave his position with Northampton. The job was instead given to the FAW's head of coaching, Englishman [[Mike Smith (football manager)|Mike Smith]].<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=211}}</ref>\n\n===UEFA Euro 1976===\n\nSmith's first test was the qualifying stage for [[UEFA Euro 1976]] as Wales were drawn alongside Hungary, Austria and [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]]. In the opening match, Wales took the lead through [[Arfon Griffiths]], but eventually lost 2\u20131 to Austria. Griffiths scored again in Wales' next two matches, a 2\u20130 win over Hungary and a 5\u20130 win over Luxembourg. The side continued its good form by becoming the first British side to win in Hungary since 1909, also inflicting Hungary's first competitive home defeat since 1959, winning 2\u20131 via goals by John Toshack and [[John Mahoney (footballer)|John Mahoney]].<ref name=\"s212214\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=212\u2013214}}</ref> A second victory over Luxembourg was also Gary Sprake's final international appearance. Despite having being considered Wales' first choice goalkeeper for nearly a decade, he finished his career with 37 caps, later remarking \"it was expected of you as a [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds]] player that you put the club first\".<ref name=\"s212214\"/> In the final match, Wales met Austria in Wrexham needing only a draw to guarantee progress to the final eight of the tournament.<ref name=\"s217218\"/> Arfon Griffiths scored the only goal of the match as Wales secured a 1\u20130 victory.<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=73}}</ref> In March 1976, the national side celebrated its centenary year with a friendly against England at the Racecourse Ground, which ended in a 2\u20131 defeat.<ref name=\"s217218\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=217\u2013218}}</ref>\n\nFor the 1976 edition of the European Championships, the quarter-finals were played as two-legged ties with the winners advancing to the semi-finals to be held in Yugoslavia.{{#tag:ref|Yugoslavia's hosting of the finals was dependent on the side progressing to the semi-finals.<ref name=\"s220\"/>|group=lower-alpha}} Wales was drawn against the host nation for its quarter-final tie with the first leg being played in [[Zagreb]]. The Yugoslavians took the lead after only 45 seconds through [[Mom\u010dilo Vukoti\u0107]] before adding a second early in the second half to win 2\u20130.<ref name=\"1976rsssf\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/76e.html |title=European Championship 1976 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Stokkermans |first1=Karel |last2=Tabeira |first2=Mart\u00edn |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref> The second-leg was billed as one of the biggest matches in Wales' history, and the FAW (which had grown increasingly short of funds) considered an offer to move the game to Wembley Stadium to maximise profit. The FAW board was split after a vote, leaving the decision in the hands of president Terry Squire who ultimately chose Ninian Park as the venue.<ref name=\"s220\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=220}}</ref>\n\nEast German referee [[Rudi Gl\u00f6ckner]] was appointed for the match, and was infuriated when the flag of his home nation was not raised before the game.<ref name=\"woyugo\">{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/astonishing-story-forgotten-welsh-football-11361935 |title=The astonishing story of the forgotten Welsh football giants and the day Ninian Park erupted into violent chaos |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |last=Abbandonato |first=Paul |date=22 May 2016 |accessdate=2 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213080442/https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/astonishing-story-forgotten-welsh-football-11361935 |archive-date=13 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Gl\u00f6ckner controversially awarded Yugoslavia a penalty in the first half and disallowed a goal for Wales in the second, as the increasingly-irate crowd made several attempts to enter the pitch. Missiles were aimed at Gl\u00f6ckner for the remainder of the match, which ended in a 1\u20131 draw and eliminated Wales from the competition. Violence flared again at the final whistle; Gl\u00f6ckner required a police escort from the pitch, Yugoslavia midfielder [[Jurica Jerkovi\u0107]] had a physical altercation with a Welsh fan who had run onto the pitch, and another Welsh fan was arrested after a corner flag, which had been thrown in anger at the referee, struck a policeman in the neck.<ref name=\"s220\"/><ref name=\"woyugo\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/wales-and-the-forgotten-quarter-final-team-of-1976-a7112191.html |title=Wales vs Belgium Euro 2016: The Welsh and the forgotten 'quarter-final' team of 1976 |newspaper=The Independent |last=Moore |first=Glen |date=30 June 2016 |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref> As a result of the scenes during the match, Wales was initially handed a two-year ban from international football, although this was reduced on appeal to a fine of 20,000 [[Swiss franc]]s and the limitation of home qualifying matches for [[UEFA Euro 1980]] being held at least {{convert|200|km}} from Cardiff.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=222}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n'''Specific''' \n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Bibliography''' \n* {{cite book |last1=Davies |first1=Gareth M |last2=Garland |first2=Ian |title=Who's Who of Welsh International Soccer Players |publisher=Bridge Books |year=1991 |isbn=1872424112 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |title=Ivor Allchurch M.B.E. |first1=David |last1=Farmer |first2 = Peter |last2= Stead |publisher=Christopher Davies (Publishing) Ltd. |location=Swansea | year= 1998 | isbn=0-7154-0733-3 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |url=https://cylchgronau.llyfrgell.cymru/view/1386666/1421693/201#?xywh=159%2C-142%2C1738%2C3921&cv=201 |title=The Early Development of Association Football in South Wales, 1890\u20131906 |journal=Transactions of the Honourable Society of the Cymmrodorian |last1=Lile |first1=Brian |last2=Farmer |first2=David |year=1984 |ref=harv}} \n* {{cite book |first=James |last=Leighton |title=Fred Keenor \u2013 The Man Who Never Gave Up |year=2010 |publisher=Derby Books Publishing Company |location=Derby |isbn=9781859838280 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/fredkeenormanwho0000leig }}\n*{{citation |title=Red Dragons \u2013 The Story of Welsh Football |last1=Stead |first1=Phil |publisher=Y Llofa |year=2013 |location=Ceredigion |isbn=9781847714688 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{Wales national football team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of The Wales National Football Team}}\n[[Category:Wales national football team| ]]\n[[Category:History of association football by national team|Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Football team history}}\n{{good article}}\n{{see also|History of the Wales national football team (1977\u2013present)}} \n[[File:Wales national team 1900.jpg|thumb|upright|The Wales national team in 1900|alt=A sepia image of a football team]]\nThe [[Wales national football team]] is the third oldest side in international [[association football]]. Wales played its first fixture in March 1876, four years after [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] and [[England national football team|England]] had contested the first-ever international match. The team played annual fixtures against Scotland, England, and later [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] and these were eventually organised into the [[British Home Championship]], an annual competition between the [[Home Nations]]. Wales did not win its first championship until the [[1906\u201307 British Home Championship|1906\u201307 edition]] of the competition and the triumph remained the nation's only one before the First World War. Wales improved considerably in the post-war period, and claimed three titles during the 1920s, despite the team was often hindered by the reluctance of [[English Football League|Football League]] clubs to release its players for international duty. The situation was so grave that, in the early 1930s, Wales was forced to select a team of lower league and amateur players in a side that became known as \"Keenor and the 10 unknowns\", a reference to captain [[Fred Keenor]] and the relative obscurity of his teammates.\n\nAble to call upon its strongest side, Wales enjoyed its most successful period in the British Home Championship, winning four titles in the six years before the Second World War. When competitive football resumed after the war, Wales began facing opponents from farther afield and played matches against numerous other European nations for the first time. The side also began competing in qualification groups for the [[FIFA World Cup]], but failed to qualify for the [[1950 FIFA World Cup|1950]] and [[1954 FIFA World Cup|1954]] editions. Under manager [[Jimmy Murphy (footballer)|Jimmy Murphy]], Wales qualified for its first World Cup in [[1958 FIFA World Cup|1958]] and progressed from its group before being defeated by [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] in the quarter-final in its following match. \n\nThe side suffered a decline in the 1960s as the 1958 World Cup generation gradually retired. [[Dave Bowen]] replaced Murphy and managed the team for a decade on a part-time basis but enjoyed little success, failing to qualify for a World Cup or the early editions of the [[UEFA European Championship|European Nations' Cup]] (later known as the European Championships). He did help the side to share the British Home Championship during the [[1969\u201370 British Home Championship|1969\u201370 season]], the last time Wales won the tournament before the competition was discontinued. In total, Wales won the championship 12 times, sharing five titles. \n\nBowen left the role in 1974, having turned down the chance to take the position full-time. He was replaced by Englishman [[Mike Smith (football manager)|Mike Smith]] who led the side to the quarter-finals of [[UEFA Euro 1976]] in its centenary year, before being defeated by [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]].{{#tag:ref|For the 1976 tournament, quarter-finals were played as a two-legged, home and away tie with the finals hosting only the semi-finals and beyond.<ref name=\"1976rsssf\"/>|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==Formation and early matches==\n[[File:Wales V Scotland 3386999.tif|thumb|A newspaper report of Wales' first competitive match against Scotland in 1876|alt=A newspaper report of a football match]]\nThe [[1872 Scotland v England football match|first]] official international [[association football]] match was held in November 1872 between [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] and [[England national football team|England]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0012/ |title=The first international football match |publisher=BBC |last=Mitchell |first=Paul |accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> Four years later, G. A. Clay-Thomas, a Welshman living in London, placed adverts in sports magazines ''[[The Field (magazine)|The Field]]'' and ''[[Bell's Life in London|Bell's Life]]'' proposing that a Welsh side be raised for a match against either Scotland or Ireland in [[rugby union|rugby]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3853930/3853938/76/Clay |title=Football |newspaper=Wrexham Guardian |p=8 |date=18 March 1876 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref> [[Llewelyn Kenrick]], a solicitor who had helped to found [[Druids F.C.]] in North Wales, pushed ahead with plans for a football match and accepted an invitation to play the Scottish national side. He helped establish the [[Football Association of Wales]] (FAW) in February 1876 to finalise arrangements for the forthcoming match,<ref name=\"Challenge\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wrexham.gov.uk/english/heritage/welsh_football/index.htm#y1876|title=1876 Kenrick's Challenge|work=The Story of Welsh Football |publisher=Wrexham County Borough Council|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> being appointed its first secretary.<ref>{{harvnb|Lile|Farmer|1984|p=196}}</ref> To qualify for selection, players were required to be Welsh or to have resided in the country for at least three years.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3386960/3386966/102/Football |title=The International Football Match |newspaper=The Cardiff Times |p=6 |date=4 March 1876 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref> Kenrick was criticised by some in South Wales for failing to notify players in the region of the forthcoming match, favouring to publish notices in London-based journals.<ref name=\"stead1013\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=10\u201313}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=120}}</ref> Unperturbed, he pushed forward with his plans and trial matches were held to find suitable players for the match.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3853883/3853888/16/Football |title=The International Football Match |newspaper=Wrexham Guardian |p=5 |date=12 February 1876 |accessdate=25 November 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref>\n\nThe [[1876 Scotland v Wales football match|first Wales international football match]] was held on 2 March 1876 at [[Hamilton Crescent]] in [[Partick]] with the side wearing white shirts, featuring the [[Prince of Wales's feathers]], and black shorts.<ref name=\"stead1013\"/> The Welsh side were outclassed by their more experienced opponents, suffering a 4\u20130 defeat.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/lifestyle/wales-v-scotland-legendary-clashes-2021031 |title=Wales v Scotland: Legendary clashes |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |last=Beech |first=Richard |date=12 October 2012 |accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> A second fixture between the two sides was arranged for the following year and the [[Racecourse Ground]] in [[Wrexham]] became the venue for [[Wales national football team home stadium|Wales' first home international]].<ref name=\"dprecord\">{{cite news |url=https://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/racecourse-worlds-oldest-international-venue-2830017 |title=Is the Racecourse the world's oldest international venue? |newspaper=Daily Post |date=16 June 2008 |accessdate=25 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925141407/https://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/racecourse-worlds-oldest-international-venue-2830017 |archive-date=25 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Welsh side fell to a 2\u20130 defeat in the match. Wales returned to Scotland in 1878 but a fixture clash with the final of the [[Welsh Cup]] between Druids and [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] led many players to refuse to travel. Such was the desperation to find willing players, the secretary of the [[Scottish Football Association]] travelled to Wales and visited the homes of players in an attempt to raise a side. A squad was eventually assembled but, having travelled overnight to Glasgow and containing many players who were not of sufficient standard, the side suffered a 9\u20130 defeat. The result remains Wales' worst defeat in international football.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=27}}</ref>\n\nIn 1879, Wales and [[England national football team|England]] met for the first time in international football at a snow-covered [[The Oval|Kennington Oval]] in [[South London]]. The poor weather conditions resulted in the match being shortened to 60 minutes and the relatively unknown status of the Welsh side led to a low turnout of spectators; newspaper reports estimate the crowd was in the low hundreds with some even stating less than 100.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1872-00/1878-79/M0008Wal1879.html |title=England 2\u20131 Wales |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=29}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=RcfKAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA79&lpg=PA79&dq=England+Wales+1879+snow+football&source=bl&ots=Cdw8QFMIi4&sig=ACfU3U1mF0MrVD9Z2p2ddF5DyEeI1JsjRQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjgs6mTibXnAhXhQxUIHeT6BbgQ6AEwFnoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=England%20Wales%201879%20snow%20football&f=false |title=The Victorian Football Miscellany |p=79 |last=Brown |first=Paul |publisher=Superelastic |year=2013 |isbn=9780956227058}}</ref> In the match, [[William Davies (footballer, born 1855)|William Davies]] scored Wales' first international goal but his side were defeated 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wrexham.gov.uk/english/heritage/welsh_football/1877_1879.htm |title=The Story of Welsh Football 1877\u20131879 |work=The Story of Welsh Football |publisher=Wrexham County Borough Council|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> The standard of the Welsh side was slowly improving and the side nearly held the visiting English side in March 1880. Having trailed 3\u20130, the Welsh side scored twice in the final ten minutes through [[William Roberts (footballer, born 1859)|William Roberts]] and [[John Roberts (footballer, born 1857)|John Roberts]] but were unable to equalise.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1872-00/1879-80/M0011Wal1880.html |title=Wales 2\u20134 England |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref> William Roberts also scored Wales' goal against Scotland two weeks later in a 5\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=30}}</ref> Wales travelled to [[Alexandra Meadows]] in [[Blackburn]] the following year to play England. [[John Vaughan (footballer, born 1856)|John Vaughan]] scored the only goal of the game as Wales won its first international football match.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/4478237/4478241/90/Wales%20football |title=England V Wales |newspaper=Western Mail |p=4 |date=28 February 1881 |accessdate=15 December 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref><ref name=\"wcbc1880\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wrexham.gov.uk/english/heritage/welsh_football/1880_1914.htm|title=The Story of Welsh Football 1880\u20131914 ||work=The Story of Welsh Football |publisher=Wrexham County Borough Council|accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] were the final [[Home Nations|Home Nation]] to establish an international football team, playing its first fixture in February 1882 against England. Having suffered a 13\u20130 defeat against the English,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1872-00/1881-82/M0014Ire1882.html |title=Ireland 0\u201313 England |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref> the Irish side travelled to the Racecourse Ground to meet Wales for the first time. The more experienced Welsh side also proved too strong for the Irish, with [[John Price (footballer, born 1854)|John Price]] becoming the first [[List of Wales national football team hat-tricks|Welshman to score a hat-trick in international football]] during a 7\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://tinyurl.gale.com/tinyurl/CXDsd2 |url-access=subscription |title=Wales V Ireland |newspaper=The Times |p=10 |date=27 February 1882 |accessdate=15 December 2019 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Buoyed by their win, the Welsh side met England a month later and recorded a second victory over their neighbours. England had taken a 2\u20131 lead but were reduced to ten men when [[Charles Bambridge]] suffered a shoulder injury.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=31}}</ref> Wales pulled the score back to 3\u20133 before scoring twice in the final three minutes to claim a 5\u20133 victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1872-00/1881-82/M0016Wal1882.html |title=Wales 5\u20133 England |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Start of the British International Championship==\n\nWith all of the Home Nations competing regularly, the decision was taken to introduce a competitive tournament between the sides and the [[British Home Championship|British International Championship]] (later to become better known as the British Home Championship) was created in 1884.<ref name=\"stead3234\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=32\u201334}}</ref> The [[1883\u201384 British Home Championship|inaugural edition of the tournament]] was won by Scotland which won all three of its ties. Having defeated Ireland 6\u20130 in its opening match, Wales went on to finish third after suffering successive defeats to England and Scotland.<ref name=\"bhc\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1884-99.html#1884 |title=British Home Championship 1884\u20131899 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref> The early stages of the competition continued on the same lines; England and Scotland competed for the title, while Wales would finish third by defeating Ireland. In the first three years of competition, Wales' only points other than in matches against Ireland was a 1\u20131 draw with England in the [[1884\u201385 British Home Championship|1884\u201385 tournament]].<ref name=\"stead3234\"/> In the [[1886\u201387 British Home Championship|1886\u201387 edition]], Wales finished bottom of the competition for the first time after losing all three of its matches, including a 4\u20131 defeat to Ireland in the nation's first victory in international football. Wales had struggled to raise a team for the match and included Wrexham defender [[Bob Roberts (footballer, born 1863)|Bob Roberts]] playing as the goalkeeper. FAW secretary [[Alexander Hunter (footballer)|Alexander Hunter]] also stepped in when [[Humphrey Jones]] withdrew late.<ref name=\"stead3234\"/> Hunter had never played football at such a level and his performance was described as \"glaringly deficient\".<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=93}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wales national team 1887.jpg|thumb|upright|The Welsh national side in 1887|alt=A black and white photo of a football team]]\nIn a reversal of the previous year's events, the ''[[Freeman's Journal]]'' claimed a weakened Ireland team travelled to Wales for the [[1887\u201388 British Home Championship]] and went on to lose the match 11\u20130,<ref name=\"wcbc1880\"/> although there were only four debutants in the team on the day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nifootball.blogspot.com/2010/11/017-3-march-1888.html?m=1 |title=Wales 11\u20130 Ireland |publisher=Northern Ireland Footballing Great |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> The scoreline remains a record victory for Wales. [[Jack Doughty]] scored four of the goals. Such was the one-sided nature of the game that three Welsh players left the field before the match ended to ensure they were on time for their train home.<ref name=\"stead3234\"/> 5\u20131 defeats to both England and Scotland however ensured another third-place finish for Wales.<ref name=\"bhc\"/>\n\nWales avoided defeat in a fixture against Scotland for the first time with a goalless draw in the [[1888\u201389 British Home Championship]], simultaneously recording a first clean sheet against the Scots. The feat was achieved despite local amateur [[Alf Pugh]] starting in goal for Wales after the original selection, [[James Trainer]], failed to arrive at the match.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3670619/3670622/93/Wales%20football |title=Scotland vs Wales Association |newspaper=South Wales Daily News |p=3 |date=16 April 1889 |accessdate=16 December 2019 |via=The National Library of Wales}}</ref> Pugh played the first 30 minutes before Wrexham's [[Sam Gillam]] arrived and took his place,<ref name=\"stead3234\"/> thus becoming the first substitution ever used in international football.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wales 0 Scotland 0|url=http://www.londonhearts.com/scotland/games/18890415.html|publisher=londonhearts.com|accessdate=16 December 2019|date=15 April 1889}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/columns/story/_/id/1521829/ask-espn-fc-champions-league-winning-skippers |title=Champions League-winning skippers |publisher=ESPN |last=Jolly |first=Richard |date=14 August 2013 |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> The following year, Wales played a home fixture outside the nation for the first time when a meeting with Ireland was held in [[Shrewsbury]] in an attempt to draw a large crowd. Wales won the match 5\u20132.<ref name=\"stead4041\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=40\u201341}}</ref> By the early 1890s, with the domestic game thriving in England, Wales was struggling to get players released for international fixtures, particularly for away matches against Ireland which required a three-day absence from a player's club due to ferry travel. As a result, Wales finished bottom of the British Home Championship five times during the decade, including three consecutive seasons between 1891 and 1893.<ref name=\"bhc\"/><ref name=\"stead4041\"/> Wales did record its highest placed finish to date in 1895 by finishing as runners-up to England after drawing all three of its fixtures, inspired by the likes of James Trainer, [[Billy Lewis (footballer)|Billy Lewis]] and a debuting [[Billy Meredith]].<ref name=\"bhc\"/><ref name=\"stead4748\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=47\u201348}}</ref>\n\nWales continued its good form at the start of the [[1895\u201396 British Home Championship]] by thrashing Ireland 6\u20130 with both Meredith and Lewis scoring [[hat-trick|braces]]. The team's optimism was short-lived however when they suffered a crushing 9\u20131 defeat to England in their following match,<ref name=\"stead4748\"/> with [[Steve Bloomer]] scoring five of his side's goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/bloomer-intlg.html |title=Stephen Bloomer \u2013 International Goals |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last=Klukowski |first=Tomasz |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> Wales would finish the 20th century by losing nine of its final ten matches, only avoiding defeat in a 2\u20132 draw with Scotland in March 1897. The difficulties in calling up players from English teams became so pronounced that the FAW put forward a motion that national teams be granted the right to overrule clubs on player selection, although this was rejected. An approach to the English governing body, [[The Football Association]], also fell on deaf ears.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=51}}</ref>\n\n==New century==\n[[File:Billymeredith.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Billy Meredith]], who made his debut for Wales in 1895|alt=A footballer poses for a photo]]\nThe [[1899\u20131900 British Home Championship]] revived hope in the side as Wales finished as runners-up to Scotland, led largely by the goals of Meredith and [[Tom Parry (footballer)|Tom Parry]]. Although results were still disappointing, the standard of the Welsh side was deemed to be improving rapidly as margins of defeat became smaller and several defeats to the English and Scottish sides between 1902 and 1905 were deemed unlucky based on the run of play.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=66\u201367}}</ref> The side also avoided defeat in an away fixture against the Scots in March 1904 after holding their opponents to a 1\u20131 draw. The following year, Wales defeated Scotland for the first time in its history after 29 years when goals from Meredith, [[Grenville Morris]] and [[Walter Watkins]] secured a 3\u20131 victory,<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=69}}</ref> although Wales was unable to capitalise on the victory as they finished second to England in the [[1905\u201306 British Home Championship]] after failing to win either of its other fixtures.<ref name=\"bhc1900\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1900-14.html |title=British Home Championship 1900\u20131914 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> Having missed the previous two years while serving a ban for his part in the [[English football bribery scandal|1905 English football bribery scandal]], Meredith returned to play for Wales in the [[1906\u201307 British Home Championship]]. In its first match, Wales defeated Ireland 3\u20132 in [[Belfast]] with Meredith scoring his side's second goal before [[Lot Jones]] scored the winning goal. Grenville Morris scored the only goal of the match to give Wales its third consecutive victory over Scotland.<ref name=\"stead7476\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=74\u201376}}</ref> In Wales' final match, Lot Jones gave his side the lead at [[Craven Cottage]] before England equalised in the second half.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1900-39/1906-07/M0090Wal1907.html |title=England 1\u20131 Wales |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> England went on to draw its final game of the tournament against Scotland, handing Wales its first British Home Championship success. All 21 players used in the tournament were awarded a commemoration medal by the FAW for the achievement.<ref name=\"stead7476\"/>\n\nThe team's fortunes suffered a complete reversal in the [[1907\u201308 British Home Championship|1907\u201308 Championship]]. After losing their opening match against Scotland, the side suffered a 7\u20131 home defeat to England in a match where three goalkeepers were used. A final defeat against Ireland resulted in Wales finishing bottom of the championship table one year after winning the tournament outright.<ref name=\"stead7679\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=76\u201379}}</ref> Several personnel changes were implemented soon after, [[Ted Robbins (football administrator)|Ted Robbins]] was appointed FAW secretary in 1909 and one of Wales' most prominent players of the era, goalkeeper [[Leigh Richmond Roose]], was dropped.<ref name=\"stead7679\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=234}}</ref> Although considered \"one of the greatest players of his generation\",<ref name=\"Roose\">{{cite web |url=https://biography.wales/article/s-ROOS-RIC-1877 |title=Leigh Richmond Roose |publisher=Dictionary of Welsh Biography |last=Richards |first=Thomas |accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> Roose had developed a reputation for eccentricity that proved costly at times. In March 1910, Wales suffered a 1\u20130 defeat to Scotland when Roose allowed a speculative shot into the net having had his back turned towards play, talking to a spectator. In November of the same year, Roose suffered a broken arm while playing for his club side but declared himself fit for the British Home Championship internationals in March 1911. A poor performance in a 2\u20132 draw with Scotland ultimately ended his international career as he was never selected for Wales again.<ref name=\"stead7679\"/>\n\nWales came within one match of winning a second title in 1912 and 1913, losing deciding matches against England on both occasions.<ref name=\"bhc1900\"/> In the [[1913\u201314 British Home Championship|final edition of the championship]] before the First World War, Wales finished bottom of the table with one point. Robbins complained that English clubs had been \"antagonistic\" when asked to release players for international duty. In December 1914, the Home Nations took the decision to suspend the British Home Championship following the outbreak of the war.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=85}}</ref> Eight players who had represented Wales in international football were killed during the conflict, including Leigh Roose.<ref name=\"Roose\"/>\n\nWales' first fixtures at the end of the war were two friendly matches against England, organised to raise funds for the FAW. The matches were not considered full internationals, being titled victory matches instead. Wales won the first meeting, led by 40-year old Meredith, but was defeated in the return match a fortnight later.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=89}}</ref> The British Home Championship returned for the [[1919\u201320 British Home Championship|1919\u201320 season]] with Wales' first post-war match ending in a 2\u20132 draw with pre-war champions Ireland in Belfast.<ref name=\"bhc1920\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1920-39.html |title=British Home Championship 1920\u20131939 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> A draw against Scotland was followed by a 2\u20131 victory over England, the first time Wales had defeated its neighbour in a competitive fixture since 1882. Goals from [[Stan Davies]] and [[Dick Richards (footballer)|Dick Richards]] secured victory for Wales, which had been reduced to ten men in the second half when [[Harry Millership]] went off injured, but the performance of the now 45-year old Meredith drew headlines.<ref name=\"stead9293\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=92\u201393}}</ref> Winning his final cap, 25 years after his debut, Meredith wept openly at the end of the match.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=57}}</ref> He ended his international career as both Wales' most-capped player and its record goalscorer having scored 11 times in 48 appearances.<ref name=\"rsssfplayers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/wal-recintlp.html |title=Wales \u2013 Record International Players |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last=Passo Alpuin |first=Luis Fernando |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref> The team were still reliant on England defeating Scotland to secure its second championship. Despite leading 4\u20132 at half-time, Scotland lost the match 5\u20134.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/><ref name=\"stead9293\"/>\n\n==1920s success and decline==\n\nWales was unable to defend its title in the [[1920\u201321 British Home Championship|1920\u201321 season]], losing 2\u20131 to Scotland in the opening game. A goalless draw with England and a 2\u20131 victory over Ireland did secure the side the runners-up spot.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/> With club sides in Wales attracting record crowds, the national team often found itself losing out to the domestic game. The victory over Ireland was held on the same day that [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] hosted [[South Shields F.C.|South Shields]] in the [[Football League Second Division]], with only 11,000 attending the national side's match in Swansea while more than 30,000 attended Cardiff's fixture.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=94\u201395}}</ref> Disappointing results between 1922 and 1923 prompted a revamp of the team for the [[1923\u201324 British Home Championship]]. One of the debutants in the team was [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea Town's]] [[Willie Davies (footballer)|Willie Davies]] who made an instant impact, scoring one of his side's goals during a 2\u20130 victory over Scotland in the opening game. Davies scored again in Wales' second match, a 2\u20131 victory over England with [[Ted Vizard]] scoring the winning goal. A final victory over Ireland, via a [[Moses Russell]] penalty, secured the title for Wales having beaten all three sides in the same tournament for the first time.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=98\u201399}}</ref> The success was partly attributed to the team's star players being released to play, but this trend soon reverted to type for the opening match of the [[1924\u201325 British Home Championship|1924\u201325 tournament]]; six players withdrew from the squad for the opening match, a 3\u20131 defeat to Scotland. Wales' success did prompt England to agree to a Saturday fixture in Wales for the first time; [[Fred Keenor]] scored for Wales but the side fell to a 2\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=100\u2013101}}</ref> Only a goalless draw with Ireland stopped Wales finishing last, only a year after winning the tournament.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/>\n\nSquad withdrawals proved a continued problem for the Welsh side. When Wales was left short for the visit of Scotland in the [[1925\u201326 British Home Championship|1925\u201326 Championship]], Ted Robbins called up debutant [[Jack Lewis (footballer, born 1902)|Jack Lewis]] after following him to a train station in [[Newport, Wales|Newport]] where he was due to travel to Birmingham to play for Cardiff City.<ref name=\"s105106\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=105\u2013106}}</ref> Defeats to Scotland and Ireland followed and Robbins was again forced to make a last minute interception for the final match against England. [[John Pullen]] had been travelling to London with Moses Russell and was persuaded to join up to win his first cap, alongside [[Charlie Jones (footballer, born 1899)|Charlie Jones]].<ref name=\"s105106\"/> Wales went on to win the match 3\u20131.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/> Wales recorded a third championship win of the decade during the [[1927\u201328 British Home Championship|1927\u201328 tournament]]. The competition had started poorly for the side, conceding two goals in the first half against Scotland before [[Ernie Curtis]] and an own goal by [[Jimmy Gibson (footballer, born 1901)|Jimmy Gibson]] salvaged a point. Wales defeated England 2\u20131 before travelling to Belfast to play Ireland in the final match. The game was tied at 1\u20131 until [[Wilf Lewis]] secured the win for Wales, scoring the winning goal by charging both the ball and opposition goalkeeper into the net. When Ireland defeated Scotland two weeks later, Wales was officially confirmed as winners.<ref name=\"s110112\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=110\u2013112}}</ref>\n\nIn 1929, the FAW received an invitation to tour Canada and selected a 20-man squad for the trip.<ref name=\"s110112\"/> Wales played 15 matches against regional teams in little over a month on the tour, winning each one.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/britishfatours.html#1929WAL |title=British FA XI Tours |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |last=Morrison |first=Neil |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref> [[Len Davies]] proved prolific during the tour, scoring seven of his side's goals in an 8\u20130 victory over Lower Mainland.<ref name=\"s110112\"/> However, Wales returned to one of the worst British Home Championship campaigns in its history. After suffering a 4\u20132 defeat to Scotland in the opening match, Wales endured a 6\u20130 defeat to England in its second fixture.<ref name=\"s113114\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=113\u2013114}}</ref> The tournament ended with a severely depleted Wales side succumbing to a 7\u20130 defeat to Ireland in which [[Joe Bambrick]] scored six of his side's goals,<ref>{{harvnb|Leighton|2010|p=142}}</ref> the most any player has scored in a single match against Wales. The national side's poor results at the end of the 1920s were partly blamed on the deterioration of Welsh club sides. By the end of the decade, Cardiff City had been relegated to the Second Division, [[Aberdare Athletic F.C.|Aberdare Athletic]] had dropped out of the Football League and both [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] and [[Merthyr Town F.C.|Merthyr Town]] had survived re-elections to avoid the same fate.<ref name=\"s113114\"/>\n\n==Pre-war recovery==\n[[File:Fred Keenor, Brentford FC footballer, 1919.jpg|thumb|left|[[Fred Keenor]], who captained the team of \"unknowns\" in 1930|alt=A black and white image of a footballer]]\nIn 1930, the Football League introduced a new ruling which prohibited its members from releasing players for international fixtures. The ruling was designed to force international matches to be scheduled on days that would not clash with Football League fixtures. Wales' first match under the ruling was the opening game of the [[1930\u201331 British Home Championship]] against Scotland, which was largely unaffected as it drew the majority of its players from its own leagues. Wales were forced to call up a mixture of lower division and amateur players in order to field a side. Nine of Wales' eleven players made their international debut in the game, with only captain Fred Keenor and goalkeeper [[Len Evans (footballer)|Len Evans]] having previous international experience. As a result, the team was dubbed \"Keenor and the 10 unknowns\".<ref name=\"BBCunknowns\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45425572 |title=Denmark v Wales: The story of the 1930s 'unknowns' who forced a draw in Scotland |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |last=Williams |first=Aled |date=7 September 2018 |accessdate=14 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324124029/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45425572 |archive-date=24 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"s116118\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=116\u2013118}}</ref> Ahead of the match, Keenor asked Ted Robbins if he could have the players to himself for four hours before the game. Taking the team to relax and discuss tactics for the match, in his pre-match team talk he exhorted his teammates, \"There's eleven of them and eleven of us, and there's only one ball, and it's ours\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/2014-world-cup-qualifying/2013/3/21/4132198/scotland-vs-wales-2014-world-cup-qualifying |title=Scotland vs. Wales: Five classic matches |publisher=[[SB Nation]] |first=Andi |last=Thomas |date=21 March 2013 |accessdate=14 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818094059/http://www.sbnation.com/2014-world-cup-qualifying/2013/3/21/4132198/scotland-vs-wales-2014-world-cup-qualifying |archive-date=18 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Despite their inexperience, the Welsh side held Scotland to a 1\u20131 draw having taken the lead after six minutes from a goal by [[Tommy Bamford]].<ref name=\"BBCunknowns\"/> The display led to a Scottish newspaper describing the Welsh performance as \"the pluckiest display in the history of international football\".<ref name=\"s116118\"/> The Welsh public also responded by calling for the same side to remain for the following match against England, although [[Elvet Collins]] was replaced due to injury.<ref name=\"s116118\"/> There was no repeat of the result; the Welsh side lost 4\u20130 at the Racecourse Ground.<ref name=\"BBCunknowns\"/>\n\nA compromise between the Football League and the other Home Nations was reached in 1931, with the sides being required to provide 21 days notice for a player's release, although the club were only obliged to release English players. The FAW would also be responsible for the wages and insurance of the players during the time away, a stipulation that placed increasing strain on the organisation's already slim finances.<ref name=\"s119121\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=119\u2013121}}</ref> However, in practice, the more inclusive ruling provided little improvement as the FAW's release requests for players were continually rejected; during the [[1931\u201332 British Home Championship]], Wales finished bottom after losing all of its matches having used 26 players in only 3 games.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/><ref name=\"s119121\"/> The number included [[Eddie Parris]] who became the first black player to represent Wales.<ref name=\"s119121\"/> The FAW subsequently gave in to the Football League and agreed to hold matches in midweek to avoid a fixture clash. The decision proved astute as Wales defeated Scotland 5\u20132 in the opening game of the [[1932\u201333 British Home Championship|1932\u201333 tournament]]. Fred Keenor won his 32nd and final international cap in the game, earning praise for his performance. A goalless draw with England and a 4\u20131 victory over Ireland secured Wales' fifth Home Championship title.<ref name=\"s122123\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=122\u2013123}}</ref>\n\nWales travelled to [[Paris]], France, in May 1933 to play its first international fixture against an opponent other than the Home Nations. [[Thomas Griffiths (footballer, born 1906)|Tommy Griffiths]] scored Wales' goal in a 1\u20131 draw with [[France national football team|France]] at the [[Stade Olympique Yves-du-Manoir]].<ref name=\"s122123\"/> Buoyed by their championship victory, the Welsh team began their title defense in the [[1933\u201334 British Home Championship]] by securing a 3\u20132 victory over Scotland in front of 40,000 fans at [[Ninian Park]]. A draw with Ireland in Belfast meant Wales required a victory over England to guarantee consecutive titles. The match was played at [[St James' Park]] in [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] with Wales taking an early lead through [[Tommy Mills (footballer)|Tommy Mills]]. The tension of the match was so intense that Mills nearly failed to return for the second half having been sick during half-time. [[Eric Brook]] equalised for England in the second half but, with less than ten minutes remaining, [[Dai Astley]] scored a header to give Wales victory and win the Home Championship in consecutive years for the only time in the nation's history.<ref name=\"s124125\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=124\u2013125}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1900-39/1933-34/M0189Wal1933.html |title=England 1\u20132 Wales |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nWales failed to retain its title in [[1933\u201334 British Home Championship|1934\u201335]], finishing last, but narrowly missed out on another title in the [[1935\u201336 British Home Championship]]. Needing a win against Ireland to secure the championship, Wales went on to lose 3\u20132.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/> The side recovered the following season and defeated England in a home fixture for the first time since 1882 via goals from [[Pat Glover]] and [[Seymour Morris]]. Glover again proved the match winner in Wales' second fixture, scoring both goals as the side defeated Scotland 2\u20131. Wales won its third title in five years by winning 4\u20131 over Ireland in its last fixture, Glover scoring two more to finish as top goalscorer with five goals in the competition.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=128\u2013129}}</ref> Wales also went on to share the [[1938\u201339 British Home Championship]] title with both England and Scotland after all three sides attained four points in the final edition of the tournament before the outbreak of the Second World War.<ref name=\"bhc1920\"/>\n\n==Wartime and new overseas competition==\nThe British Home Championship was postponed during wartime; Wales' final fixture before the start of the war was a 2\u20131 defeat against France.<ref name=\"matches\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesw/wal-intres.html |title=International matches of Wales |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last=Nyg\u00e5rd |first=Jostein |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref> The side's first wartime fixture was a 1\u20131 draw with England in a charity match to raise money for the [[Red Cross]]. The following year, Wales were hosted at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] for the first time having previously been considered less of a draw than Scotland. Wales won the match 1\u20130 through a goal by [[Bryn Jones (footballer, born 1912)|Bryn Jones]].<ref name=\"s133135\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=133\u2013135}}</ref> For the majority of the war, Wales only played fixtures against England, the two sides met 15 times between 1939 and 1945. Wales final wartime matches were against Scotland and Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.welshsoccerarchive.co.uk/index.php/internationals/wartime |title=Wartime Internationals |publisher=Welsh Football Data Archive |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref> As the war drew to a close, the national side was rocked by the death of Ted Robbins in January 1946. Robbins had served as secretary of the FAW since 1909 and was credited as a major factor in the team's success in previous decades.<ref name=\"s133135\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CCS134824498&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS134824498&searchId=R2&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Sport in Brief |newspaper=The Times |p=8 |date=18 January 1946 |accessdate=21 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref>\n\n[[File:John Charles, Wales versus Scotland, Ninian Park, 1954.jpg|left|thumb|[[John Charles]] (pictured in 1954) was one of Wales' most prominent players during the 1950s.|alt=A footballer poses for a photo in front of a stand]]\nThe British Home Championship returned for the [[1946\u201347 British Home Championship|1946\u201347 campaign]] and Wales' first competitive post-war fixture was against Scotland in October 1946.<ref name=\"matches\"/> The wartime gap had increased public appetite for the sport and the break resulted in an entirely new generation of players being involved in the squad. One of the debutants, [[Trevor Ford]], scored one of Wales' goals in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=43}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=136}}</ref> However, defeats to England and Northern Ireland resulted in a third-place finish during the first post-war championship.<ref name=\"bhc1940\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1947-66.html |title=British Home Championship 1947\u20131966 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref> The following year, Wales began its campaign with a 3\u20130 defeat against England but defeated Scotland at [[Hampden Park]] for the first time.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=138\u2013139}}</ref> A win over Northern Ireland left Wales leading the group with only one match to be played. In the final match, England defeated Scotland to claim the championship by a single point.<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/> In 1949, the Wales national side embarked on its first overseas tour with matches against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]], [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] and [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]]. As all three opponents wore red shirts, the fixtures necessitated the first away kit in Wales' history. A yellow shirt with green collar and trim was adopted for the tour, featuring the [[Welsh Dragon]] on the pocket. The tour proved disastrous for the squad however, as Wales lost all three fixtures and the squad was involved in a road accident when the team coach crashed during a tour of the Swiss Alps.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=143\u2013144}}</ref>\n\nWales and the other Home Nations entered the [[FIFA World Cup]] for the first time in 1950 and the [[1949\u201350 British Home Championship]] was used to determine qualification for the tournament. The added incentive resulted in a crowd of more than 60,000 attending Wales' opening fixture against England at Ninian Park, but they witnessed their side suffer a 4\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=146}}</ref> A further defeat to Scotland ended Wales' hopes of qualification and only a goalless draw with Northern Ireland stopped the side finishing bottom of the group on [[goal difference]].<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/> Prior to the Ireland match, Belgium had travelled to Cardiff to become the first overseas side to visit Wales for an international match. Trevor Ford scored a hat-trick in a 5\u20131 victory for Wales. Portugal and Switzerland also travelled to Wales in 1951, as Wales avenged its earlier defeats by winning both matches.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=148\u2013149}}</ref> During the following year's championship, Trevor Ford became Wales' leading goalscorer of all-time when he scored a brace during a 4\u20132 defeat to England. Having entered the match on ten goals, his double resulted in him overtaking Billy Meredith's tally of eleven.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/trevor-ford-37679/ |title=Trevor Ford Player Statistics |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|Some sources credit [[Billy Lewis (footballer)|Billy Lewis]] with twelve goals for Wales,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1946-60/1950-51/M0260Wal1950.html |title=England 4\u20132 Wales |website=englandfootballonline.com |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref> but most contemporary sources only list him with 8.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/teams/wales/tab/stats/option/scorers/ |title=Wales national football team statistics and records: top scorers |website=11v11.com |publisher=FAS Enterprises |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=12145 |title= Billy Lewis |website=eu-football.info |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref> Further breakdown can be viewed at [[Talk:Billy Lewis (footballer)]].|group=lower-alpha}}\n\nWales celebrated its 75th anniversary by winning its first post-war British Home Championship title by sharing the [[1951\u201352 British Home Championship]] edition with England.<ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=45}}</ref> The two sides had drawn their meeting in the first fixture before both won their remaining matches to finish on five points.<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/> Wales' final match of the competition was a 3\u20130 victory over Northern Ireland at Vetch Field, the first international match held at the ground in 25 years. The Welsh squad contained several young players born or brought up in the Swansea area, including Ford, [[Ivor Allchurch]] and [[Roy Paul]], and the game was regarded as a homecoming match.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=150}}</ref> Allchurch scored one of his side's goals in the match to finish tied as the competition's top goalscorer.<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=47}}</ref> Wales struggled in the years immediately afterwards, finishing bottom of the Championship in consecutive seasons, including the [[1953\u201354 British Home Championship|1953\u201354 tournament]] which saw the team fail to qualify for the [[1954 FIFA World Cup]].<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/> The period also included a disastrous European tour in 1953 during which Wales suffered a 6\u20131 defeat to France and a 5\u20132 defeat to [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=153}}</ref>\n\n===Austria and The Battle of Wrexham===\n[[File:Trevor Ford (1959).jpg|thumb|right|[[Trevor Ford]], once Wales' record goalscorer and whose physical style of play was a reason for Austrian animosity|alt=A headshot of a footballer]] \nIn 1954, encouraged by the work of [[Walter Winterbottom]] with England, the FAW appointed the first manager of the Welsh national side in former captain [[Walley Barnes]].<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=15}}</ref><ref name=\"s155156\"/> His first match in charge of the side was a match against [[Austria national football team|Austria]] in [[Vienna]] which attracted 60,000 spectators. Despite winning 2\u20130, the Austrians were infuriated by the physical style of play adopted by Wales, particularly forwards Ford and [[Derek Tapscott]], which was unfamiliar outside Britain. The Austria captain [[Ernst Ocwirk]] described the match as \"the dirtiest game he'd ever seen.\"<ref name=\"s155156\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=155}}</ref> Yugoslavia travelled to Wales in September 1954 in a reverse of the two side's fixture in 1953 and became the first foreign opposition to win in Wales after winning 3\u20131, having trailed 1\u20130 at half-time.<ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=51}}</ref> Wales' burgeoning involvement in continental football resulted in the FAW being accepted as members of the recently founded [[Union of European Football Associations]] (UEFA) in 1954.<ref name=\"s155156\"/>\n\nThe [[1955\u201356 British Home Championship]] brought some improvement for Wales as the side recorded its first victory over England in 17 years at Ninian Park. The period also saw the emergence of [[John Charles]] for the national side.<ref name=\"s157160\"/> Charles and his brother [[Mel Charles|Mel]] often played alongside another set of brothers, Ivor and [[Len Allchurch]], becoming the first sets of brothers to play for Wales.<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=12}}</ref> John Charles quickly gained a reputation as the side's leading player, featuring as either a [[centre-half]] or [[centre-forward]], and his performance in the victory over England led ''[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]]'' reporter Dewi Lewis to describe him as \"indeed the perfect footballer if ever there was one.\"<ref name=\"s157160\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=157\u2013160}}</ref> All four sides shared the British Home Championship title after finishing on three points, the only occurrence of a four-way tie in the competition's 100-year history. Wales narrowly missed out on winning the title having drawn 1\u20131 with Northern Ireland in its final game in which Roy Paul missed a penalty with Wales already leading 1\u20130. Ireland later equalised and the game ended as a tie.<ref name=\"s157160\"/>\n\nAt the end of 1955, Austria travelled to Wales a year after its 2\u20130 victory. The Austrian team were eager to match the physicality of the Welsh side shown in the first meeting and the match descended into violent chaos.<ref name=\"s157160\"/> The French referee, Louis Fauquemberghe,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/wales-v-austria-23-november-1955-226605/ |title=Wales v Austria 23 November 1955 |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/referee_summary/louis-fauquembergue/1/1/ |title=Louis Fauquembergue |website=worldfootball.net |accessdate=26 January 2020}}</ref> who was unable to speak either German or English had little control as both sides continually resorted to fouling each other resulting in injuries to eight players.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wrexham.gov.uk/english/heritage/welsh_football/1945_1985.htm |title=1945\u20131986 |work=The Story of Welsh Football |publisher=Wrexham County Borough Council|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> The most serious were to Austria's [[Theodor Wagner]], who suffered a fractured tibia, and Wales' Mel Charles, who left the field with ten minutes remaining after being heavily fouled.<ref name=\"timesaustria\">{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CCS67851640&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS67851640&searchId=R7&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Rough International Match at Wrexham |newspaper=The Times |p=4 |date=24 November 1955 |accessdate=26 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Roy Paul later described the scene in the Welsh dressing room after the match in his autobiography, writing \"Our goalkeeper, [[Jack Kelsey]], had scars on both legs. Derek Tapscott [...] had a six-inch gash on his knee. [...] John Charles leaned over his brother Melvyn with tears in his eyes. Melvyn lay silent, still dazed by a tackle which had sent him crashing to the ground.\"<ref name=\"s157160\"/> The national media were highly critical after the match; the ''Western Mail'' described the match as \"a disgrace\",<ref name=\"s157160\"/> while ''[[The Times]]'' wrote \"there were times when the pitch resembled a battlefield, with players down here and there\".<ref name=\"timesaustria\"/>\n\n==1958 FIFA World Cup==\n===Qualification and build-up===\nDisappointing results against European teams prompted a change of approach by the FAW who appointed [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] coach [[Jimmy Murphy (footballer)|Jimmy Murphy]] as manager in 1956. Murphy enjoyed an inauspicious start with draws with Northern Ireland and Scotland before a 3\u20131 defeat to England in a match where Wales finished with nine players due to injuries. The British Home Championship was dropped as a qualifying format for the [[1958 FIFA World Cup]] and replaced by randomly drawn [[1958 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualifying groups]]. Wales was drawn alongside [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] and [[East Germany national football team|East Germany]] and started positively by defeating Czechoslovakia 1\u20130 in its first fixture, via a goal by [[Roy Vernon]]. Wales travelled to East Germany in its second game with a squad of only 12 players. John Charles became highly critical of the FAW's reluctance to travel with more than a bare minimum of players, later writing \"There were more selectors than players. It was crazy. You've got to put the players first but with Wales it was the selectors first and the players second.\"<ref name=\"s161163\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=161\u2013163}}</ref> Wales eventually suffered a 2\u20131 defeat to the largely amateur East Germans in the nation's first competitive fixture.<ref name=\"s161163\"/>\n\n[[File:The Israeli team playing against Wales at the Ramat Gan stadium, 1958 D448-079.jpg|thumb|left|Wales playing [[Israel national football team|Israel]] in a [[1958 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF/AFC\u2013UEFA play-off)|play-off]] match to qualify for the [[1958 FIFA World Cup]]|alt=A black and white image of a football match]]\nThe squad continued to Czechoslovakia but had lost three players to illness and injury. The FAW, however, were still reluctant to call-up replacements and only an outcry from the press prompted Ray Daniel and [[Des Palmer]] to join up with the side. Nevertheless, Wales lost the match 2\u20130 and made qualification unobtainable. In the final group match, Palmer scored a hat-trick to defeat East Germany 4\u20131.<ref name=\"s161163\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/58qual.html#gr4 |title=World Cup 1958 qualifications |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref> A second opportunity at qualification emerged in December 1957 as the volatile political situation in Israel led to [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]], [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]] and [[Sudan national football team|Sudan]] withdrawing from matches against the nation for varying reasons. FIFA rules decreed that no team could qualify for a World Cup without playing a match, and so a [[1958 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF/AFC\u2013UEFA play-off)|play-off]] against a European qualifying group runner-up was arranged. [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] was drawn first but also refused to play Israel leading to a second draw in which Wales was selected. The FAW accepted the offer and Wales travelled to [[Tel Aviv]] for the first leg, winning 2\u20130 after goals from Ivor Allchurch and [[Dave Bowen]].<ref name=\"s165166\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Farmer |Stead|1998|p=89}}</ref> The result was the first time Wales had won an international fixture outside Britain.<ref name=\"58guardian\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/jul/01/wales-1958-world-cup-quarter-final-euro-2016 |title=Wales at the 1958 World Cup: a quarter-final run with a difference |newspaper=The Guardian |last=Burton |first=Simon |date=1 July 2016 |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref> Allchurch scored again in the second leg and a further goal from [[Cliff Jones (Welsh footballer)|Cliff Jones]] secured Wales' first qualification to a major international tournament.<ref name=\"s165166\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=165\u2013166}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/15584126.from-the-argus-archive-when-wales-qualified-for-the-world-cup-in-1958-by-beating-israel-at-ninian-park-in-cardiff/ |title=From the Argus archive: When Wales qualified for the World Cup - in 1958 by beating Israel at Ninian Park in Cardiff |newspaper=South Wales Argus |date=27 October 2017 |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nWales received a favourable draw for the group stage of the tournament, being placed alongside [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] and hosts [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]]. The side's preparations for the tournament were hampered by confusion over the availability of John Charles; having failed to qualify, the [[Italian Football Federation]] had instead organised a club tournament featuring Charles' side [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] who were reluctant to release the player. Wales manager Jimmy Murphy prepared his team to play without Charles, but the player eventually secured his release and arrived in Sweden only three days before the start of the competition.<ref name=\"s167168\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=167\u2013168}}</ref> The side was further weakened by the omission of Trevor Ford, the nation's record goalscorer. Ford had been banned from playing in Britain in 1956 after he revealed an illegal payments scandal in club football in his autobiography. Despite continuing to play abroad, he was overlooked for selection.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/league-legend-ford-one-finest-2486582 |title=League legend Ford one of finest Wales players |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |date=30 May 2003 |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref> Derek Tapscott had also fallen out with the FAW while Des Palmer missed out due to injury, leading to [[Colin Webster]] being selected in their stead.<ref name=\"s172173\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=172\u2013173}}</ref> Wales played a single warm-up match prior to the start of the tournament, defeating local amateur side Soltsjobaden 19\u20130.<ref name=\"s167168\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=91}}</ref>\n\n===Tournament===\nWales' opening game of the tournament was against Hungary. Although the Hungarian [[Golden Team]] had previously been considered one of the best teams in the world, the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]] had weakened the side.<ref name=\"58guardian\"/><ref name=\"s169171\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=169\u2013171}}</ref> Nevertheless, Hungary quickly took the lead in the opening five minutes through [[J\u00f3zsef Bozsik]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/wales-v-hungary-08-june-1958-227115/ |title=Wales v Hungary, 08 June 1958 |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref> The Hungarian defensive efforts were largely focused on containing John Charles who received attention described as \"rugged tactics\" by ''The Times''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=12&docId=GALE%7CCS50944713&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS50944713&searchId=R6&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Welsh Fire Earns a Draw |newspaper=The Times |p=3 |date=9 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Journalist Ian Wooldridge wrote that the Hungarian tactics were often \"Just inside or wildly outside the international laws of soccer\".<ref name=\"s169171\"/> Charles scored an equaliser for Wales after 27 minutes, heading in from a corner to secure a 1\u20131 draw.<ref name=\"s169171\"/> In its second match, Wales played a Mexico side that had suffered a 3\u20130 defeat to Sweden in its opening game. The Welsh side entered the game as favourites but struggled to gain the advantage over their opponents.<ref name=\"s169171\"/> Ivor Allchurch gave Wales the lead in the first half but Mexico responded strongly and scored a late equaliser in the 89th minute with Wales having been reduced to 10-men after [[Colin Baker (Welsh footballer)|Colin Baker]] had been injured.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=2&docId=GALE%7CCS235231948&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS235231948&searchId=R7&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Late Goal by Mexico Checks Faltering Wales |newspaper=The Times |p=14 |date=12 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref>\n\nIn its final group match, Wales met Sweden which had already qualified for the quarter-finals and had rested several players as a result.<ref name=\"s169171\"/> The Swedes were still the stronger of the two teams but were unable to breach the Welsh defense and the match ended goalless.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=5&docId=GALE%7CCS50944720&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS50944720&searchId=R8&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales Draw with Sweden |newspaper=The Times |p=3 |date=16 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Wales finished the group stage with three points, tied for second with Hungary necessitating a play-off match between the two sides to determine which would advance.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CCS50551504&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS50551504&searchId=R8&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Three U.K. Teams in World Cup Play-offs |newspaper=The Times |p=3 |date=16 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> Wales faced Hungary needing a victory; Hungary's superior goal difference meant a draw would see it advance. Wales were dealt a blow when [[Lajos Tichy]] gave Hungary the lead after 30 minutes while John Charles was again the focus of the Hungarian defence, leaving the field on more than one occasion to receive treatment. Charles though, proved pivotal as he set up Ivor Allchurch for Wales' equalising goal. [[Terry Medwin]] scored a second for Wales and, despite finishing the match with 10-men following an injury to [[Ron Hewitt (footballer, born 1928)|Ron Hewitt]], the side held on to advance to the quarter-finals.<ref name=\"s169171\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=9&docId=GALE%7CCS51337938&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS51337938&searchId=R10&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales to Meet Brazil |newspaper=The Times |p=3 |date=18 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=95}}</ref>\n\nWales met [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], the winners of [[1958 FIFA World Cup Group 4|group 4]], in the quarter-finals. Much of the build-up for Wales focused on John Charles' attempts to recover from injuries sustained against Hungary. Described by one reporter as having received \"the most tremendous battering I have ever seen administered to a soccer player\", Charles failed to recover in time and his place in the side was taken by Colin Webster. Charles' absence proved costly as several chances were spurned with [[Brian Glanville]] of ''The Times'' remarking \"Wales could have won because all sorts of very tempting centres were coming across the goal and John wasn't there to head them in.\"<ref name=\"s172173\"/> Brazil went on to win the match by a single goal, scored by [[Pel\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=1&docId=GALE%7CCS252140244&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS252140244&searchId=R11&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales' Gallant Exit from World Cup |newspaper=The Times |p=15 |date=20 June 1958 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref>\n\n==Post World Cup decline==\n===World Cup generation fades===\nThe success of the Welsh team in the World Cup resulted in huge demand for tickets for the side's opening match of the [[1958\u201359 British Home Championship]] against Scotland. However, the capacity home crowd at Ninian Park were left disappointed as Wales suffered a 3\u20130 defeat. Draws against England and Northern Ireland in the final two games left Wales bottom of the Championship, less than a year after its World Cup exploits. The following year, the post World Cup interest in the team led to a crowd of 62,634 attending a match against England at Ninian Park, a new record crowd for Wales and a record attendance for the ground.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=174\u2013176}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/cardiff_city/8007646.stm |title=Farewell Ninian Park |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 April 2009 |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref> Wales began the 1960s by meeting the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] for the first time. The FAW had been against the Irish split and had resisted any attempts for the two sides to play for several years (England had played the Republic for the first time some 14 years earlier). Goals from Cliff Jones and [[Phil Woosnam]] won the match for Wales.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=178}}</ref>\n\nA shared British Home Championship title in [[1959\u201360 British Home Championship]] and a positive finish to the following year's campaign had raised hopes of Wales qualifying for the [[1962 FIFA World Cup]] in Chile.<ref name=\"bhc1940\"/><ref name=\"s179182\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=179\u2013182}}</ref> Wales was drawn in a group with [[Spain national football team|Spain]] and Austria, although Austria withdrew due to financial problems before the matches began.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/62q.html |title=World Cup 1962 Qualifying |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Stokkermans |first1=Karel |last2=Jarreta |first2=Sergio Henrique |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4uJdBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA131&lpg=PA131&dq=Austria+1962+World+cup&source=bl&ots=xw6zGVVbQp&sig=ACfU3U1qFO3zLhQlHcjET-yfjb-mcrttfg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwinmoS1jKznAhU7VxUIHQnQDAYQ6AEwHHoECAIQAQ#v=onepage&q=Austria%201962%20World%20cup&f=false |title=Encyclopedia of the FIFA World Cup |last=Dunmore |first=Tom |publisher=Scarecrow Press |p=131 |year=2015 |isbn=9780810887435}}</ref> Wales met Spain for the first match with a depleted side, missing several players including John Charles and Cliff Jones. Spain won the first match 2\u20131 before the two sides drew 1\u20131 in the second match in [[Madrid]] with Ivor Allchurch scoring Wales' goal. The result subsequently eliminated Wales from qualifying for the World Cup.<ref name=\"s179182\"/> Wales was invited to tour South America in 1962, the first matches played by the team outside Europe. The side played two matches against reigning World Cup holders Brazil, losing both 3\u20131. The tour concluded with a 2\u20131 defeat to Mexico and the retirement of long-serving goalkeeper Jack Kelsey from international football.<ref name=\"s179182\"/>\n\nWales entered the [[UEFA European Championship|European Nations' Cup]] for the first time in 1964 (the Home Nations had not entered the inaugural edition in [[1960 European Nations' Cup|1960]]). In the preliminary qualifying round, Wales were drawn against Hungary and suffered a demoralising 3\u20131 defeat in the first leg in Budapest. A 1\u20131 draw in the return leg resulted in the side's elimination at the first attempt.<ref name=\"s184185\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=184\u2013185}}</ref> In April 1964, manager Jimmy Murphy was forced to miss Wales' match against Northern Ireland after his wife was taken ill. Swansea Town manager [[Trevor Morris (footballer)|Trevor Morris]] was placed in charge as Wales suffered a 3\u20132 defeat. Murphy never took charge of another match for Wales, resigning later in the year due to commitments with his role at Manchester United. The FAW drew up a shortlist of Welsh candidates, which included former players Jack Kelsey, [[Ron Burgess (footballer)|Ron Burgess]] and [[Tommy Jones (footballer, born 1909)|Tommy Jones]]. The role was eventually given to another former player, Dave Bowen, who had captained the team at the 1958 World Cup. Bowen took the job alongside his role as manager of [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]]. His first match in charge ended in victory when two late goals from [[Ken Leek]] secured a 3\u20132 win over Scotland in the [[1964\u201365 British Home Championship]].<ref name=\"s186187\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=186\u2013187}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Swansea Town Football Club (20740154461).jpg|thumb|right|[[Ivor Allchurch]] retired in 1966 as both Wales' record appearance holder and joint record goalscorer.|alt=A footballer jogs around a pitch]]\nIn [[1966 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualifying]] for the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]], Wales was drawn in a group alongside the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]], [[Greece national football team|Greece]] and [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].<ref name=\"66rsssf\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/66qual.html |title=World Cup 1966 qualifications |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> The campaign began poorly for Wales as it lost 1\u20130 to Denmark in [[Copenhagen]] before losing a controversial game against Greece in [[Athens]]. Welsh players Ken Leek and [[Wyn Davies]] were continually fouled which led to brawls between players breaking out on several occasions.<ref name=\"s188190\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=188\u2013190}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CCS67463050&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS67463050&searchId=R2&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales Lose to Greece |newspaper=The Times |p=4 |date=10 December 1964 |accessdate=1 February 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> The home crowd also made attempts to break onto the pitch to confront the Welsh players which led to clashes with local police. Wales would avenge the defeat five months later with a 4\u20131 victory over Greece at Ninian Park in the return fixture. Wales travelled to [[Moscow]] in May 1965, suffering a 2\u20131 defeat in John Charles' final international appearance.<ref name=\"s188190\"/>\n\nDave Bowen was unavailable to manage Wales in its opening match of the [[1965\u201366 British Home Championship]] due to club commitments. Ron Burgess took charge for the match, which ended in a goalless draw.<ref name=\"s188190\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=23}}</ref> Bowen returned for the return fixture against the Soviet Union in October 1965. His side recorded a surprise 2\u20131 victory over their previously unbeaten opponents,<ref name=\"s191\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=191}}</ref> the only match the Soviet Union failed to win during qualifying,<ref name=\"66rsssf\"/> via goals by Roy Vernon and Ivor Allchurch.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/wales-v-ussr-27-october-1965-229197/ |title=Wales v USSR, 27 October 1965 |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> The result was not enough to secure qualification however as, despite beating Denmark 4\u20132 in its final game, Wales finished as runners-up in the group behind the Soviets.<ref name=\"s191\"/> Having failed to qualify for the World Cup, Wales instead embarked on another tour of South America in May 1966, playing two matches against Brazil and one against [[Chile national football team|Chile]]. Ivor Allchurch made his final appearance for Wales in the 2\u20130 defeat to Chile in the final match of the tour.<ref>{{harvnb|Farmer|Stead|1998|p=140}}</ref> He retired as Wales' record appearance holder with 68 caps, and tied with Trevor Ford as the nation's record goalscorer with 23.<ref name=\"rsssfplayers\"/><ref name=\"s191\"/>\n\n===Late 1960s struggles===\nLike the early World Cups, the qualifying phase for [[UEFA Euro 1968]] used the British Home Championship as a qualification group for the tour, with the results of the [[1966\u201367 British Home Championship|1966\u201367]] and [[1967\u201368 British Home Championship|1967\u201368]] editions being combined to determine which of the Home Nations would progress.<ref name=\"s192\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=192}}</ref> Wales began the stage with a 1\u20131 draw against Scotland in October 1966 but ultimately finished third in the 1966\u201367 season after losing heavily to England and recording a goalless draw with Northern Ireland.<ref name=\"bhc1967\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc1967-84.html |title=British Home Championship 1967\u20131984 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> For the 1967\u201368 championship, Wales adopted an all-red kit for the first time in its history. The team fared little better, losing to England and Scotland before recording its only victory of the Euro 1968 qualifying campaign by beating Northern Ireland 2\u20130.<ref name=\"s192\"/>\n\nWales recorded a creditable 1\u20131 draw with [[West Germany national football team|West Germany]] in April 1969 ahead of the qualifying campaign for the [[1970 FIFA World Cup]]. However, the side was hampered by withdrawals and refusals to release players for matches. Wales' first match was against reigning European champions [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and Dave Bowen was forced to name several reserve players in the line-up, although the team only lost to a single goal by [[Luigi Riva]]. The side travelled to West Germany to play a return friendly against the side, with Bowen only able to select 13 players for the trip. Nevertheless, Wales recorded a second 1\u20131 draw; [[Barrie Jones]] had given Wales the lead before [[Gerd M\u00fcller]] equalised late in the match. The qualifying campaign for the 1970 World Cup ended with two defeats to East Germany and another to Italy as Wales failed to gain a single point.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/70q.html |title=World Cup 1970 Qualifying |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Stokkermans |first1=Karel |last2=Jarreta |first2=Sergio Henrique |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> Wales also finished bottom of the [[1968\u201369 British Home Championship|last British Home Championship of the decade]] with a single point.<ref name=\"bhc1967\"/>\n\nWales' struggles during the 1960s were blamed on several factors. The refusal of clubs to release players for international duty or to not allow a player to travel until a day before the match often disrupted the team. In his book ''Red Dragons: The Story of Welsh Football'', Phil Stead writes that Dave Bowen often could \"not pick a side until the day of the game because he was never sure who would be available.\"<ref name=\"s195197\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=195\u2013197}}</ref> The final match of the 1970 World Cup qualification group against Italy was nearly forfeited as Wales struggled to name a squad. One player, Wrexham's teenage defender [[Gareth Davies (footballer, born 1949)|Gareth Davies]], was contacted in the early hours of the morning and travelled overnight to make the team's flight to [[Rome]].<ref name=\"s195197\"/> The organisation of the team by the FAW was also criticised. Goalkeeper [[Gary Sprake]] later remarked that \"the international set-up with Wales at this time was amateurish at best\". Sprake later admitted to feigning injury under the guidance of his club manager [[Don Revie]] in order to avoid selection with the national side.<ref name=\"s186187\"/> [[John Toshack]], who made his debut in 1969, made similar comments: \"The whole set-up was a bit of a shambles [...] some of the players with more fashionable clubs were not too concerned about turning up for the less glamorous games.\"<ref name=\"s186187\"/> An incident in 1969 drew considerable criticism of the FAW when it failed to book enough seats for the ten travelling Welsh players and the organisation's members. When none of the officials offered to give up their seat, the crew declared that the last person to board the craft, winger [[Gil Reece]], would have to disembark. A furious Reece was left at the airport and had to travel alone to [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] before crossing the border into East Germany.<ref name=\"s195197\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/other-sport/welsh-greats-pay-tribute-gil-2458945 |title=Welsh greats pay tribute to Gil the Blade |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |date=23 December 2003 |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Departure of Bowen and arrival of Smith==\nWales began the 1970s in a more positive fashion, sharing the [[1969\u201370 British Home Championship]] with England and Scotland. Wales had drawn with both before defeating Northern Ireland.<ref name=\"s200\"/> The success was the final time Wales was victorious in the competition. The title was the 12th time it had won the competition and the fifth time it had shared the title.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc.html |title=British Home Championship Overview |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Reyes |first1=Macario |last2=Morrison |first2=Neil |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> The success raised hopes of the team qualifying for [[UEFA Euro 1972]].<ref name=\"s200\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=200}}</ref> Wales were drawn in a group alongside Czechoslovakia, [[Romania national football team|Romania]] and [[Finland national football team|Finland]]. The side began the campaign with a goalless draw against Romania before losing 3\u20131 to Czechoslovakia,<ref name=\"72rsssf\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/72e.html |title=European Championship 1972 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Stokkermans |first1=Karel |last2=Tabeira |first2=Mart\u00edn |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref> having led 1\u20130 with 12 minutes remaining.<ref name=\"s201204\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=201\u2013204}}</ref> Wales recovered with home and away victories over Finland but lost its remaining games to finish third, failing to qualify.<ref name=\"72rsssf\"/> In Wales' home victory over Finland, [[Trevor Hockey]] became the first player to represent the nation under a new parentage rule allowing players to represent countries other than their birth nations.<ref name=\"s201204\"/> His father had been born in [[Abertillery]], thus qualifying him for Wales under the new ruling.<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=83}}</ref>\n\nWales' fortunes dipped alarmingly in the immediate years afterwards; the side finished bottom of the British Home Championship in four consecutive seasons between 1971 and 1975, winning only one match.<ref name=\"bhc1967\"/> The team did perform slightly better during qualifying for the [[1974 FIFA World Cup]] in which they were drawn against England and [[Poland national football team|Poland]]. Wales lost to England in its opening game, failing to score for a sixth consecutive match, but surprised many by holding England to a draw in the return fixture at Wembley Stadium having taken an early lead through John Toshack.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/74qual.html#gr5 |title=World Cup 1974 qualifications |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"s207209\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=207\u2013209}}</ref> Wales met Poland in March 1973 and recorded a 2\u20130 victory through goals by Trevor Hockey and [[Leighton James]]. Hockey would turn villain shortly before half-time in the return match in [[Chorz\u00f3w]], becoming the first Welsh player to be sent-off.<ref name=\"s207209\"/> The match deteriorated further in the second half as both sides committed numerous fouls and several scuffles broke out between the sides. [[Terry Yorath]] commented that he felt \"your physical well being was at risk\" during the game, while ''The Times'' headline referred to the match as \"a night of delinquency\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=3&docId=GALE%7CCS302217531&docType=Sports+news&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&contentSet=GALE%7CCS302217531&searchId=R2&userGroupName=wikipedia&inPS=true |url-access=subscription |title=Wales lose their place and good name on night of delinquency |newspaper=The Times |p=18 |date=27 September 1973 |accessdate=2 February 2020 |via=The Times Digital Archive}}</ref> In 1974, the FAW decided that the Wales manager's job required a full-time occupant and offered Dave Bowen the position on a permanent full-time basis. Bowen however rejected the role, unwilling to leave his position with Northampton. The job was instead given to the FAW's head of coaching, Englishman [[Mike Smith (football manager)|Mike Smith]].<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=211}}</ref>\n\n===UEFA Euro 1976===\n\nSmith's first test was the qualifying stage for [[UEFA Euro 1976]] as Wales were drawn alongside Hungary, Austria and [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]]. In the opening match, Wales took the lead through [[Arfon Griffiths]], but eventually lost 2\u20131 to Austria. Griffiths scored again in Wales' next two matches, a 2\u20130 win over Hungary and a 5\u20130 win over Luxembourg. The side continued its good form by becoming the first British side to win in Hungary since 1909, also inflicting Hungary's first competitive home defeat since 1959, winning 2\u20131 via goals by John Toshack and [[John Mahoney (footballer)|John Mahoney]].<ref name=\"s212214\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=212\u2013214}}</ref> A second victory over Luxembourg was also Gary Sprake's final international appearance. Despite having being considered Wales' first choice goalkeeper for nearly a decade, he finished his career with 37 caps, later remarking \"it was expected of you as a [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds]] player that you put the club first\".<ref name=\"s212214\"/> In the final match, Wales met Austria in Wrexham needing only a draw to guarantee progress to the final eight of the tournament.<ref name=\"s217218\"/> Arfon Griffiths scored the only goal of the match as Wales secured a 1\u20130 victory.<ref>{{harvnb|Davies|Garland|1991|p=73}}</ref> In March 1976, the national side celebrated its centenary year with a friendly against England at the Racecourse Ground, which ended in a 2\u20131 defeat.<ref name=\"s217218\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|pp=217\u2013218}}</ref>\n\nFor the 1976 edition of the European Championships, the quarter-finals were played as two-legged ties with the winners advancing to the semi-finals to be held in Yugoslavia.{{#tag:ref|Yugoslavia's hosting of the finals was dependent on the side progressing to the semi-finals.<ref name=\"s220\"/>|group=lower-alpha}} Wales was drawn against the host nation for its quarter-final tie with the first leg being played in [[Zagreb]]. The Yugoslavians took the lead after only 45 seconds through [[Mom\u010dilo Vukoti\u0107]] before adding a second early in the second half to win 2\u20130.<ref name=\"1976rsssf\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/76e.html |title=European Championship 1976 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. |last1=Stokkermans |first1=Karel |last2=Tabeira |first2=Mart\u00edn |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref> The second-leg was billed as one of the biggest matches in Wales' history, and the FAW (which had grown increasingly short of funds) considered an offer to move the game to Wembley Stadium to maximise profit. The FAW board was split after a vote, leaving the decision in the hands of president Terry Squire who ultimately chose Ninian Park as the venue.<ref name=\"s220\">{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=220}}</ref>\n\nEast German referee [[Rudi Gl\u00f6ckner]] was appointed for the match, and was infuriated when the flag of his home nation was not raised before the game.<ref name=\"woyugo\">{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/astonishing-story-forgotten-welsh-football-11361935 |title=The astonishing story of the forgotten Welsh football giants and the day Ninian Park erupted into violent chaos |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |last=Abbandonato |first=Paul |date=22 May 2016 |accessdate=2 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213080442/https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/astonishing-story-forgotten-welsh-football-11361935 |archive-date=13 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Gl\u00f6ckner controversially awarded Yugoslavia a penalty in the first half and disallowed a goal for Wales in the second, as the increasingly-irate crowd made several attempts to enter the pitch. Missiles were aimed at Gl\u00f6ckner for the remainder of the match, which ended in a 1\u20131 draw and eliminated Wales from the competition. Violence flared again at the final whistle; Gl\u00f6ckner required a police escort from the pitch, Yugoslavia midfielder [[Jurica Jerkovi\u0107]] had a physical altercation with a Welsh fan who had run onto the pitch, and another Welsh fan was arrested after a corner flag, which had been thrown in anger at the referee, struck a policeman in the neck.<ref name=\"s220\"/><ref name=\"woyugo\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/wales-and-the-forgotten-quarter-final-team-of-1976-a7112191.html |title=Wales vs Belgium Euro 2016: The Welsh and the forgotten 'quarter-final' team of 1976 |newspaper=The Independent |last=Moore |first=Glen |date=30 June 2016 |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref> As a result of the scenes during the match, Wales was initially handed a two-year ban from international football, although this was reduced on appeal to a fine of 20,000 [[Swiss franc]]s and the limitation of home qualifying matches for [[UEFA Euro 1980]] being held at least {{convert|200|km}} from Cardiff.<ref>{{harvnb|Stead|2013|p=222}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n'''Specific''' \n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Bibliography''' \n* {{cite book |last1=Davies |first1=Gareth M |last2=Garland |first2=Ian |title=Who's Who of Welsh International Soccer Players |publisher=Bridge Books |year=1991 |isbn=1872424112 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |title=Ivor Allchurch M.B.E. |first1=David |last1=Farmer |first2 = Peter |last2= Stead |publisher=Christopher Davies (Publishing) Ltd. |location=Swansea | year= 1998 | isbn=0-7154-0733-3 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |url=https://cylchgronau.llyfrgell.cymru/view/1386666/1421693/201#?xywh=159%2C-142%2C1738%2C3921&cv=201 |title=The Early Development of Association Football in South Wales, 1890\u20131906 |journal=Transactions of the Honourable Society of the Cymmrodorian |last1=Lile |first1=Brian |last2=Farmer |first2=David |year=1984 |ref=harv}} \n* {{cite book |first=James |last=Leighton |title=Fred Keenor \u2013 The Man Who Never Gave Up |year=2010 |publisher=Derby Books Publishing Company |location=Derby |isbn=9781859838280 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/fredkeenormanwho0000leig }}\n*{{citation |title=Red Dragons \u2013 The Story of Welsh Football |last1=Stead |first1=Phil |publisher=Y Llofa |year=2013 |location=Ceredigion |isbn=9781847714688 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{Wales national football team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of The Wales National Football Team}}\n[[Category:Wales national football team| ]]\n[[Category:History of association football by national team|Wales]]\n", "name_user": "The ed17", "label": "safe", "comment": "upright=2", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Wales_national_football_team_(1876%E2%80%931976)"}
{"title_page": "HMS Surprise (replica ship)", "text_new": "{{short description|Replica tall ship built at Lunenburg, Nova Scotia, Canada in 1970}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image= HMS-Surprise-overall.jpg\n|Ship caption=''Surprise'' in 2005 at the [[Maritime Museum of San Diego]]\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=\n|Ship name= HMS ''Surprise''\n|Ship renamed= HMS ''Rose'' (1970-2007)\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship owner=*Maritime Museum of San Diego\n*20th Century Fox (2001-2007)\n*HMS Rose Foundation (1970-2001)\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship registry={{flag|United States}}\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder=[[Smith and Rhuland]] Shipyard, [[Lunenburg, Nova Scotia (town)|Lunenburg]], [[Nova Scotia]]\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=1970\n|Ship completed= \n|Ship homeport=[[San Diego, California|San Diego]], [[California]] \n|Ship identification=*{{MMSI Number|338167202}}\n*[[Maritime call sign]]: WSA2459\n*Primary Vessel Number: 928811\n*USCG VIN: CG006327\n*Connecticut VIN: CT8069AB \n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship fate= \n|Ship status= Active Museum Ship\n|Ship notes= \n}}\n\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship type=\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship displacement= {{convert|500|LT|t|0|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship tons burthen=\n|Ship length=*{{convert|179|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}} [[spar (sailing)|spar]]red length\n*{{convert|135|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}} on [[Deck (ship)|deck]]\n*{{convert|114|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}} [[Length at the waterline|w/l]]\n|Ship beam={{convert|32|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height= of [[Rigging|Rig]] {{convert|130|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|13|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship decks=\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship sail plan=[[Full rigged ship]], sail area {{convert|13000|ft2|m2|abbr=on}}\n|Ship speed=\n|Ship range=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship boats=\n|Ship complement=\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship armament=28 x 9 pound cannons (non-operational)\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''\"HMS\" ''Surprise''''' is a modern [[tall ship]] built at [[Lunenburg, Nova Scotia|Lunenburg]], [[Nova Scotia]], [[Canada]]. The vessel was built in 1970 as '''HMS ''Rose''''' to a [[Phil Bolger]] design based on the original 18th-century British [[Admiralty]] drawings of {{HMS|Rose|1757|6}}, a 20-gun [[sixth-rate]] [[post ship]] from 1757.\n\n==As HMS ''Rose''==\nThe ship was meant to be a close replica of the original ''Rose'', but still fill a commercial function. John Fitzhugh Millar<ref>{{cite web|last1=Millar|first1=John F.|title=Building the Replicas of Revolutionary War Ships Rose and Providence|url=http://smallstatebighistory.com/building-replicas-revolutionary-war-ships-rose-providence/|website=smallstatebighistory.com|accessdate=22 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Millar|first1=J. F.|title=John Fitzhugh Millar|url=http://www.newporthousebb.com/photo_album/page22/|website=newporthousebb.com|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref> who commissioned the ship build gave Bolger copies of the original British Admiralty drawings, Bolger modified the hull shape below the water line, sharpening up her entry so she sailed to windward better. Unlike some square-riggers, she could sail two points (22-1/2 degrees) on the wind provided that seas remained under four feet or so. Bolger also changed the arrangement of her decks, at the bank's insistence, so that she could be used as a tavern and restaurant, though she was never used as such.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bolger|first1=Philip C.|title=30-Odd Boats|date=1982|publisher=International Marine Publishing Company|isbn=0877421528}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=HMS Rose Sails Soon|journal=Boating|issue=October 1969|page=85|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=nHv-v3JYFgYC&lpg=RA4-PA85&ots=VM07Gf6m_y&dq=phil%20bolger%20book%20AND%20HMS%20Rose&pg=RA4-PA85#v=onepage&q=phil%20bolger%20book%20AND%20HMS%20Rose&f=false|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n''Rose'' was built at the [[Smith and Rhuland]] shipyard in Lunenburg, a yard which had established a reputation for large and successful replicas such as HMS {{ship||Bounty|1960 ship|2}} in 1960 and {{ship||Bluenose II}} in 1963.\n\nThe ship was inspected and certified by the [[United States Coast Guard]]. She spent the first ten years of her life in Newport, Rhode Island sailing in Newport Harbor and as a dockside attraction. \n\nIn the summer of 1972, ''Rose'' was hired for the film \"''[[The Man Without a Country (1973 film)|The Man Without a Country]]''\", a made-for-television production. Norman Rosemont Productions couldn't find the money to take the ship out sailing, so all the filming was shot with sails set, as the ship was securely moored to the pier, next to the causeway to [[Goat Island (Rhode Island)|Goat Island]]. During filming Cliff Robertson had to hide that he had a broken leg at the time.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Millar|first1=John Fitzhugh|title=Building the Replicas of Revolutionary War Ships Rose and Providence|url=http://smallstatebighistory.com/building-replicas-revolutionary-war-ships-rose-providence/|website=smallstatebighistory|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, already in serious disrepair, she was purchased by Kaye Williams<ref>{{cite book|last1=Biebel|first1=Frederick|title=Path of a Patriot|date=2008|isbn=0615236650|page=186|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8sT2AgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA186&ots=OYVRzkFl0h&dq=hms%20rose%20replica&pg=PA186#v=onepage&q=hms%20rose%20replica&f=false}}</ref> and brought to Bridgeport, Connecticut, and operated as a [[sail training]] vessel in the 1980s and 1990s, run by the HMS Rose Foundation based in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut|Bridgeport]], [[Connecticut]], [[United States]]. In her lifetime as ''Rose'', her figurehead had to be replaced twice, each time slightly upgraded. One was damaged in a storm off Bermuda on her way to [[Norfolk, Virginia]] in June 1998. The figurehead was named in fun as \"Chester\" by the crew.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nyden|first1=W. A.|title=Vacation June 1998|url=http://www.nyden.us/roserpt.html|website=nyden.us|accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nLate in the 1990s, the publisher W. W. Norton & Company rented ''Rose'' in New York for a pier-side party to celebrate the publication of  [[Patrick O'Brian]]'s latest novel. O'Brian himself was present, and he casually mentioned to ''Rose''{{'}}s captain Richard Bailey that if ''Rose'' were painted in an 1805 colour scheme she would be a \"dead ringer\" for the frigate ''Surprise'' that appeared in his books. Bailey quickly ordered his crew to get out the paint and make the changes. O'Brian was so impressed that he changed his mind about his prohibition of having any of his books converted into film, and Norton immediately started looking for a Hollywood production company.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Millar|first1=John Fitzhugh|title=Building the Replicas of Revolutionary War Ships Rose and Providence|url=http://smallstatebighistory.com/building-replicas-revolutionary-war-ships-rose-providence/|website=smallstatebighistory|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:HMS Rose - 1971 under sail off Massachusetts.png|thumb|200px|right|Replica HMS ''Rose'' off Massachusetts in 1971, the hull painted as her namesake]]\n\n==Transformation into HMS ''Surprise''==\n\nThe ship was sold to the [[20th Century Fox]] film studio in March 2001,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cummings|first1=Bill|title=Goodbye, Rose: Filmmaker Pays $1.5m for Bridgeport Frigate|url=http://www.peterweircave.com/master/rose1.html|accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref> and underwent extensive modifications to be used in the making of the film ''[[Master and Commander: The Far Side of the World]]'', in which she portrayed the [[Royal Navy]] frigate HMS {{HMS|Surprise|1796|2}} with a story based on several of the books by Patrick O'Brian. The modifications included a reshaped stern, all deck structures removed, the single ship's wheel replaced by a double wheel, period fighting tops fitted, new sails, and the figurehead replaced.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Quinlan|first1=Eric|title=Cross Currents|journal=Yachting|date=Nov 2003|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZPTPomKTxHsC&lpg=PA24&ots=JdRea5AnXt&dq=hms%20surprise%20extensive%20modifications&pg=PA24#v=onepage&q=hms%20surprise%20extensive%20modifications&f=false|accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Renaming as HMS ''Surprise''==\nAfter the film was complete, the ship was leased and then purchased by the [[Maritime Museum of San Diego]] which has restored her to sailing condition as of September 2007.<ref>[http://legacy.sname.org/sections/san_diego/Presentations/2007-10_Reviving_Surprise.pdf \"Reviving Surprise\"(pdf) David L. Kolthoff, P.E.]</ref> The ship has officially been re-registered as \"HMS ''Surprise''\" in honor of her role in the film. She sails several times a year, often with the museum's other tall ships, the schooner {{ship||Californian|schooner|2}} and the 1863 barque {{ship||Star of India|ship|2}}.<ref>[http://www.sdmaritime.com/contentpage.asp?ContentID=152 SDMM article on ''Surprise''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050405203518/http://www.sdmaritime.com/ContentPage.asp?ContentID=152 |date=2005-04-05 }}</ref> In 2010, she portrayed HMS ''Providence'' in the [[Disney]] [[adventure film]] ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides]]''.<ref>http://img835.imageshack.us/slideshow/webplayer.php?id=lb1f.jpg</ref>\n\n==Related facts==\nAlthough she is known by the prefix '''HMS''', meaning Her (or His) [[Her Majesty's Ship|Majesty's Ship]], she is not, and had never been, [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] in the Royal Navy.\n\nIn 1991, The [[Connecticut General Assembly]] passed \"An Act Concerning the HMS Rose\" in which the ship was commissioned as a vessel of the [[Connecticut Naval Militia]].  The act stated that the H.M.S. Rose Foundation was responsible for maintaining the ship, but when the ship was sold to 20th Century Fox, the statute was not repealed and is still in effect.<ref>[http://www.cga.ct.gov/current/pub/chap_504.htm#sec_27-5 CGS 27-5 - Public Act 91-31]</ref>\n\n[[File:HMS Rose - 2000 coming into Baltimore 51741315 265eec262c.jpg|thumb|300px|right|''HMS Rose'' in 2000 painted to resemble the original ''Surprise'' coming into Baltimore]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|HMS Surprise (ship, 1970)}}\n{{Commons category|HMS Rose (ship, 1970)}}\n* [http://www.sdmaritime.org/hms-surprise/ Maritime Museum of San Diego page on the ''Surprise'']\n* [http://www.tallshiprose.org/ Tall ship ''Rose'']\n* [http://www.modelships.de/Museums_and_replicas/Frigate_HMS_Rose/HMS_Rose_replica.htm Photo gallery of ''Surprise'' in San Diego, October 2005]\n\n{{coord|32|43|15|N|117|10|26|W|type:landmark_region:US|display=title}}\n\n{{Maritime Museum of San Diego}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Surprise, Hms, Replica}}\n[[Category:1970 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Maritime Museum of San Diego]]\n[[Category:Museum ships in San Diego]]\n[[Category:Individual sailing vessels]]\n[[Category:Vessels of the American Sail Training Association]]\n[[Category:Tall ships of the United States]]\n[[Category:Replica ships]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Replica tall ship built at Lunenburg, Nova Scotia, Canada in 1970}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image= HMS-Surprise-overall.jpg\n|Ship caption=''Surprise'' in 2005 at the [[Maritime Museum of San Diego]]\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=\n|Ship name= HMS ''Surprise''\n|Ship renamed= HMS ''Rose'' (1970-2007)\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship owner=*Maritime Museum of San Diego\n*20th Century Fox (2001-2007)\n*HMS Rose Foundation (1970-2001)\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship registry={{flag|United States}}\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder=[[Smith and Rhuland]] Shipyard, [[Lunenburg, Nova Scotia (town)|Lunenburg]], [[Nova Scotia]]\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=1970\n|Ship completed= \n|Ship homeport=[[San Diego, California|San Diego]], [[California]] \n|Ship identification=*{{MMSI Number|338167202}}\n*Call Sign: WSA2459\n*Primary Vessel Number: 928811\n*USCG VIN: CG006327\n*Connecticut VIN: CT8069AB \n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship fate= \n|Ship status= Active Museum Ship\n|Ship notes= \n}}\n\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship type=\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship displacement= {{convert|500|LT|t|0|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship tons burthen=\n|Ship length=*{{convert|179|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}} [[spar (sailing)|spar]]red length\n*{{convert|135|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}} on [[Deck (ship)|deck]]\n*{{convert|114|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}} [[Length at the waterline|w/l]]\n|Ship beam={{convert|32|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height= of [[Rigging|Rig]] {{convert|130|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|13|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship decks=\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship sail plan=[[Full rigged ship]], sail area {{convert|13000|ft2|m2|abbr=on}}\n|Ship speed=\n|Ship range=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship boats=\n|Ship complement=\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship armament=28 x 9 pound cannons (non-operational)\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''\"HMS\" ''Surprise''''' is a modern [[tall ship]] built at [[Lunenburg, Nova Scotia|Lunenburg]], [[Nova Scotia]], [[Canada]]. The vessel was built in 1970 as '''HMS ''Rose''''' to a [[Phil Bolger]] design based on the original 18th-century British [[Admiralty]] drawings of {{HMS|Rose|1757|6}}, a 20-gun [[sixth-rate]] [[post ship]] from 1757.\n\n==As HMS ''Rose''==\nThe ship was meant to be a close replica of the original ''Rose'', but still fill a commercial function. John Fitzhugh Millar<ref>{{cite web|last1=Millar|first1=John F.|title=Building the Replicas of Revolutionary War Ships Rose and Providence|url=http://smallstatebighistory.com/building-replicas-revolutionary-war-ships-rose-providence/|website=smallstatebighistory.com|accessdate=22 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Millar|first1=J. F.|title=John Fitzhugh Millar|url=http://www.newporthousebb.com/photo_album/page22/|website=newporthousebb.com|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref> who commissioned the ship build gave Bolger copies of the original British Admiralty drawings, Bolger modified the hull shape below the water line, sharpening up her entry so she sailed to windward better. Unlike some square-riggers, she could sail two points (22-1/2 degrees) on the wind provided that seas remained under four feet or so. Bolger also changed the arrangement of her decks, at the bank's insistence, so that she could be used as a tavern and restaurant, though she was never used as such.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bolger|first1=Philip C.|title=30-Odd Boats|date=1982|publisher=International Marine Publishing Company|isbn=0877421528}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=HMS Rose Sails Soon|journal=Boating|issue=October 1969|page=85|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=nHv-v3JYFgYC&lpg=RA4-PA85&ots=VM07Gf6m_y&dq=phil%20bolger%20book%20AND%20HMS%20Rose&pg=RA4-PA85#v=onepage&q=phil%20bolger%20book%20AND%20HMS%20Rose&f=false|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n''Rose'' was built at the [[Smith and Rhuland]] shipyard in Lunenburg, a yard which had established a reputation for large and successful replicas such as HMS {{ship||Bounty|1960 ship|2}} in 1960 and {{ship||Bluenose II}} in 1963.\n\nThe ship was inspected and certified by the [[United States Coast Guard]]. She spent the first ten years of her life in Newport, Rhode Island sailing in Newport Harbor and as a dockside attraction. \n\nIn the summer of 1972, ''Rose'' was hired for the film \"''[[The Man Without a Country (1973 film)|The Man Without a Country]]''\", a made-for-television production. Norman Rosemont Productions couldn't find the money to take the ship out sailing, so all the filming was shot with sails set, as the ship was securely moored to the pier, next to the causeway to [[Goat Island (Rhode Island)|Goat Island]]. During filming Cliff Robertson had to hide that he had a broken leg at the time.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Millar|first1=John Fitzhugh|title=Building the Replicas of Revolutionary War Ships Rose and Providence|url=http://smallstatebighistory.com/building-replicas-revolutionary-war-ships-rose-providence/|website=smallstatebighistory|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, already in serious disrepair, she was purchased by Kaye Williams<ref>{{cite book|last1=Biebel|first1=Frederick|title=Path of a Patriot|date=2008|isbn=0615236650|page=186|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8sT2AgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA186&ots=OYVRzkFl0h&dq=hms%20rose%20replica&pg=PA186#v=onepage&q=hms%20rose%20replica&f=false}}</ref> and brought to Bridgeport, Connecticut, and operated as a [[sail training]] vessel in the 1980s and 1990s, run by the HMS Rose Foundation based in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut|Bridgeport]], [[Connecticut]], [[United States]]. In her lifetime as ''Rose'', her figurehead had to be replaced twice, each time slightly upgraded. One was damaged in a storm off Bermuda on her way to [[Norfolk, Virginia]] in June 1998. The figurehead was named in fun as \"Chester\" by the crew.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nyden|first1=W. A.|title=Vacation June 1998|url=http://www.nyden.us/roserpt.html|website=nyden.us|accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nLate in the 1990s, the publisher W. W. Norton & Company rented ''Rose'' in New York for a pier-side party to celebrate the publication of  [[Patrick O'Brian]]'s latest novel. O'Brian himself was present, and he casually mentioned to ''Rose''{{'}}s captain Richard Bailey that if ''Rose'' were painted in an 1805 colour scheme she would be a \"dead ringer\" for the frigate ''Surprise'' that appeared in his books. Bailey quickly ordered his crew to get out the paint and make the changes. O'Brian was so impressed that he changed his mind about his prohibition of having any of his books converted into film, and Norton immediately started looking for a Hollywood production company.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Millar|first1=John Fitzhugh|title=Building the Replicas of Revolutionary War Ships Rose and Providence|url=http://smallstatebighistory.com/building-replicas-revolutionary-war-ships-rose-providence/|website=smallstatebighistory|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:HMS Rose - 1971 under sail off Massachusetts.png|thumb|200px|right|Replica HMS ''Rose'' off Massachusetts in 1971, the hull painted as her namesake]]\n\n==Transformation into HMS ''Surprise''==\n\nThe ship was sold to the [[20th Century Fox]] film studio in March 2001,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cummings|first1=Bill|title=Goodbye, Rose: Filmmaker Pays $1.5m for Bridgeport Frigate|url=http://www.peterweircave.com/master/rose1.html|accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref> and underwent extensive modifications to be used in the making of the film ''[[Master and Commander: The Far Side of the World]]'', in which she portrayed the [[Royal Navy]] frigate HMS {{HMS|Surprise|1796|2}} with a story based on several of the books by Patrick O'Brian. The modifications included a reshaped stern, all deck structures removed, the single ship's wheel replaced by a double wheel, period fighting tops fitted, new sails, and the figurehead replaced.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Quinlan|first1=Eric|title=Cross Currents|journal=Yachting|date=Nov 2003|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZPTPomKTxHsC&lpg=PA24&ots=JdRea5AnXt&dq=hms%20surprise%20extensive%20modifications&pg=PA24#v=onepage&q=hms%20surprise%20extensive%20modifications&f=false|accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Renaming as HMS ''Surprise''==\nAfter the film was complete, the ship was leased and then purchased by the [[Maritime Museum of San Diego]] which has restored her to sailing condition as of September 2007.<ref>[http://legacy.sname.org/sections/san_diego/Presentations/2007-10_Reviving_Surprise.pdf \"Reviving Surprise\"(pdf) David L. Kolthoff, P.E.]</ref> The ship has officially been re-registered as \"HMS ''Surprise''\" in honor of her role in the film. She sails several times a year, often with the museum's other tall ships, the schooner {{ship||Californian|schooner|2}} and the 1863 barque {{ship||Star of India|ship|2}}.<ref>[http://www.sdmaritime.com/contentpage.asp?ContentID=152 SDMM article on ''Surprise''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050405203518/http://www.sdmaritime.com/ContentPage.asp?ContentID=152 |date=2005-04-05 }}</ref> In 2010, she portrayed HMS ''Providence'' in the [[Disney]] [[adventure film]] ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides]]''.<ref>http://img835.imageshack.us/slideshow/webplayer.php?id=lb1f.jpg</ref>\n\n==Related facts==\nAlthough she is known by the prefix '''HMS''', meaning Her (or His) [[Her Majesty's Ship|Majesty's Ship]], she is not, and had never been, [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] in the Royal Navy.\n\nIn 1991, The [[Connecticut General Assembly]] passed \"An Act Concerning the HMS Rose\" in which the ship was commissioned as a vessel of the [[Connecticut Naval Militia]].  The act stated that the H.M.S. Rose Foundation was responsible for maintaining the ship, but when the ship was sold to 20th Century Fox, the statute was not repealed and is still in effect.<ref>[http://www.cga.ct.gov/current/pub/chap_504.htm#sec_27-5 CGS 27-5 - Public Act 91-31]</ref>\n\n[[File:HMS Rose - 2000 coming into Baltimore 51741315 265eec262c.jpg|thumb|300px|right|''HMS Rose'' in 2000 painted to resemble the original ''Surprise'' coming into Baltimore]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|HMS Surprise (ship, 1970)}}\n{{Commons category|HMS Rose (ship, 1970)}}\n* [http://www.sdmaritime.org/hms-surprise/ Maritime Museum of San Diego page on the ''Surprise'']\n* [http://www.tallshiprose.org/ Tall ship ''Rose'']\n* [http://www.modelships.de/Museums_and_replicas/Frigate_HMS_Rose/HMS_Rose_replica.htm Photo gallery of ''Surprise'' in San Diego, October 2005]\n\n{{coord|32|43|15|N|117|10|26|W|type:landmark_region:US|display=title}}\n\n{{Maritime Museum of San Diego}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Surprise, Hms, Replica}}\n[[Category:1970 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Maritime Museum of San Diego]]\n[[Category:Museum ships in San Diego]]\n[[Category:Individual sailing vessels]]\n[[Category:Vessels of the American Sail Training Association]]\n[[Category:Tall ships of the United States]]\n[[Category:Replica ships]]\n", "name_user": "SpaceNavy", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated call sign type.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HMS_Surprise_(replica_ship)"}
{"title_page": "Social Democrats of Montenegro", "text_new": "{{Infobox political party\n|country             = Montenegro\n|name = Social Democrats of Montenegro\n|native_name         = Socijaldemokrate Crne Gore<br />\u0421\u043e\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430\u043b\u0434\u0435\u043c\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0435 \u0426\u0440\u043d\u0435 \u0413\u043e\u0440\u0435\n|logo                = Logo SD.png\n| abbreviation     = SD\n|split               = [[Social Democratic Party of Montenegro|Social Democratic Party]]\n|leader              = [[Ivan Brajovi\u0107]]\n|foundation          = 31 July 2015\n|ideology            = [[Social democracy]]<ref name=\"PAE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/montenegro.html|website=Parties and Elections in Europe|title=Montenegro|first=Wolfram|last=Nordsieck|year=2016|accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref><br>[[Social liberalism]]<br>[[Atlanticism]]<br />[[Pro-Europeanism]]\n|position            = [[Centrism|Centre]] to [[Centre-left politics|centre-left]]\n|headquarters        = [[Podgorica]]\n|colorcode           = {{Social Democrats of Montenegro/meta/color}}\n|seats1_title        = [[Parliament of Montenegro|Parliament]]\n|seats1              = {{Composition bar|2|81|hex={{Social Democrats of Montenegro/meta/color}}}}\n|seats2_title       = [[Municipalities of Montenegro|Local Parliaments]]\n|seats2             = {{Composition bar|63|786|hex={{Social Democrats of Montenegro/meta/color}}}}\n|website             = [https://sdcg.me www.sdcg.me]\n}}\n\n'''Social Democrats of Montenegro''' ([[Montenegrin language|Montenegrin]]: ''Socijaldemokrate Crne Gore'', ''\u0421\u043e\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430\u043b\u0434\u0435\u043c\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0435 \u0426\u0440\u043d\u0435 \u0413\u043e\u0440\u0435'', ''SD CG''), or just the '''Social Democrats''' ([[Montenegrin language|Montenegrin]]: Socijaldemokrate, \u0421\u043e\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430\u043b\u0434\u0435\u043c\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0442e, '''SD'''), is a [[centre-left]] [[List of political parties in Montenegro|political party]] in [[Montenegro]] formed in 2015 by a split faction of [[Social Democratic Party of Montenegro]]. ''SD'' is one of the ruling parties in Montenegro with the [[President of the Parliament of Montenegro|President of the Parliament]] and two ministers. It currently has two representatives in the [[Parliament of Montenegro]], [[2016 Montenegrin parliamentary election|elected in 2016]].\n\n==History==\nThe party was founded in July 2015<ref name=\"vijesti.me Founding Document\">[http://www.vijesti.me/vijesti/socijaldemokrate-crne-gore-nova-partija-841975 Socijaldemokrate Crne Gore nova partija ]</ref> after the split between two [[Social Democratic Party of Montenegro|Social Democratic Party]] (SDP) vice-presidents Vujica Lazovi\u0107 and Ivan Brajovi\u0107, that advocated unconditional support for the ruling [[Democratic Party of Socialists]] (DPS) and Prime Minister [[Milo \u0110ukanovi\u0107]] with the party leader [[Ranko Krivokapi\u0107]], who advocated pursuing an independent political course.<ref name=\"aljazeera.net Founding Document\">[http://balkans.aljazeera.net/vijesti/crna-gora-raskol-u-sdp-u-upitna-koalicija Crna Gora: Raskol u SDP-u, upitna koalicija ]</ref><ref name=\"slobodnaevropa.org Founding Document\">[http://www.slobodnaevropa.org/content/sdp-opstaje-a-ko-odlazi/27102328.html Raskol u SDP: Brajovi\u0107eva struja napustila stranku, Krivokapi\u0107 tra\u017ei da vrate mandate]</ref> [[Ivan Brajovi\u0107]], Minister of Transport and Maritime Affairs in [[Government of Montenegro]] at the time, was chosen as the first president of the new party. After 2016 parliamentary election, party won two seats in the [[Parliament of Montenegro]], remain part of the government with two ministers while the Party leader Brajovi\u0107 was elected [[President of the Parliament of Montenegro]].\n\n==Elections==\n===Parliamentary elections===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|